{"title_page": "Tudeh Party of Iran", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Redirect|Tudeh|places in Iran|Tudeh, Iran (disambiguation){{!}}Tudeh, Iran}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Tudeh Party of Iran\n| logo = Tudeh.PNG\n| leader1_title = International Secretary\n| leader1_name = Navid Shomali<ref name=\"MS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/a-f8cb-Tudeh-75-years-fighting-for-Irans-working-class |title=Tudeh: 75 Years Fighting For Iran\u2019s Working Class |date=8 October 2016 |access-date=11 March 2017 |work=[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]}}</ref>\n| leader2_title = Spokesperson\n| leader2_name = Mohammad Omidvar<ref name=\"MS\"/>\n| founders = [[The Fifty-Three]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1941|10|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"MS\"/>\n| banned = {{start date and age|1949|2|5|df=y}} (by [[Pahlavi dynasty]])<br>{{start date and age|1983|2|df=y}} (by [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Islamic Republic]])\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Marxism-Leninism]]\n| international = [[International Meeting of Communist and Workers' Parties|IMCWP]]<br>[[International Communist Seminar|ICS]] (defunct)\n| national = [[United Front of Progressive Parties|UFPP]] (1946\u20131948)<ref>{{cite book |last=Abrahamian |first=Ervand |year=1982 |title=Iran Between Two Revolutions |isbn=0-691-10134-5 |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/300 300] |url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/300 }}</ref>\n| newspaper = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Rahbar (newspaper)|Rahbar]]'' (1942\u20131945)\n* ''[[Khavar-e no]]'' (1943\u20131945)\n}}\n| predecessor = [[Communist Party of Persia]]\n| position = [[Left-wing]]<ref>{{citation|author=Touraj Atabaki|title=Azerbaijan: Ethnicity and the Struggle for Power in Iran|page=137|year=2000|publisher=I.B.Tauris}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Berlin, Germany]]<br />[[London, England]]<br>[[Leipzig]], [[East Germany|GDR]] (1949\u20131979)<br>[[Tehran]], [[Iran]] (1943\u20131983)\n| website = {{ConditionalURL}}\n| colorcode = {{Tudeh Party of Iran/meta/color}}\n| anthem = ''Anthem for Tudeh''<br />(composed by [[Parviz Mahmoud]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Meftahi|first=Ida|year=2016|title=Gender and Dance in Modern Iran: Biopolitics on Stage|isbn=9781317620624|publisher=Routledge|page=57}}</ref>\n| youth_wing = [[Tudeh Youth]]\n| womens_wing = [[Democratic Organization of Women]]\n| wing1_title = Military wing\n| wing1 = [[Tudeh Military Network|Officers' Organization]]\n| wing2_title = Parliamentary wing\n| wing2 = [[Tudeh fraction]]\n| wing3_title = Worker wing\n| wing3 = [[Central Council of United Trade Unions]]\n| country = Iran\n}}\nThe '''Tudeh Party of Iran''' ({{lang-fa-at|\u062d\u0632\u0628 \u062a\u0648\u062f\u06c0 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646|\u1e24ezb-e T\u016bde-ye \u012ar\u0101n|lit=Party of the Masses of Iran}}) is an [[Iran]]ian [[communist party]]. Formed in 1941, with Soleiman Mohsen Eskandari as its head, it had considerable influence in its early years and played an important role during [[Mohammad Mosaddegh]]'s campaign to nationalize the [[Anglo-Persian Oil Company]] and his term as prime minister.<ref>Tudeh News, [https://web.archive.org/web/20121019002919/http://tudehpartyiran.org/TN%20247-oct-2007.pdf Statement of the Central Committee of the Tudeh Party of Iran], 2007.</ref> The crackdown that followed the 1953 coup against Mosaddegh is said to have \"destroyed\" the party,<ref name=\"Abrahamian, Ervand p.122\">Abrahamian, Ervand, ''A History of Modern Iran'', p.122</ref><ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'', (1999), p.92</ref> although a remnant persisted. The party still exists, but has remained much weaker as a result of its banning in Iran and mass arrests by the [[Iranian Revolution|Islamic Republic]] in 1982, as well as the [[1988 executions of Iranian political prisoners|executions of political prisoners in 1988]].\n\nTudeh identified itself as the historical offshoot of the [[Communist Party of Persia]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vahabzadeh|first1=Peyman|title=Guerrilla Odyssey: Modernization, Secularism, Democracy, and the Fadai Period of National Liberation In Iran, 1971\u20131979|date=2010|publisher=Syracuse University Press|page=182|isbn=9780815651475}}</ref>\n==Definition==\nThe party has generally been described as \"communist\" by historians (for example: \"The Tudeh Party was a classical pro-[[Soviet Union]] communist party, but wrapped itself at the time in [[nationalism]] to be more attractive to Iranians\"<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/tehranbureau/2011/06/the-nationalist-religious-movement-part-1-patriots-and-mosaddeghists.html#ixzz1Qn0vJaLs The Nationalist-Religious Movement | Part 1: Patriots and Mosaddeghists] by MUHAMMAD SAHIMI Tehran Bureau in Los Angeles| 28 June 2011</ref>), but is sometimes described simply as \"leftist\" or even \"left-leaning\" by more sympathetic sources.<ref>''US Foreign Policy in Perspective: Clients, enemies and empire'' by David Sylvan and Stephen Majeski, Routledge, 2009, p.85</ref> Various academic sources have described the party as \"[[Stalinism|Stalinist]]\".<ref>\n* {{cite book |author=Stephanie Cronin |title=Reformers and Revolutionaries in Modern Iran: New Perspectives on the Iranian Left |publisher=Routledge |series=Routledge/BIPS Persian Studies Series |year=2013 |isbn=1134328907 |pages=42\u201343}}\n* {{cite book |authors=Samih K. Farsoun, Mehrdad Mashayekhi |title=Iran: Political Culture in the Islamic Republic |year=2005 |publisher=Routledge |page=68 |quote=Thus the Tudeh Party introduced the Stalinist version of Marxism into Iran. As was discussed before, in the late 1950s the Third Worldist ideology and its socialist variant appeared in Iran, basically through the impact of the Chinese, Cuban and Vietnamese Revolutions}}\n* {{cite book |author=Tadd Fern\u00e9e |year=2014 |title=Enlightenment and Violence: Modernity and Nation-Making |publisher=SAGE |page=318 |quote=Yet, when the Soviet Union demanded its oil concession the following year the Tudeh Party extended full support on ideological grounds. The Tudeh Party evolved towards a Stalinist pro-Moscow Party, ultimately losing much public support. International political pressures transformed the Tudeh Party into the local evangelical force of the Stalinist faith by 1949.}}\n* {{cite book |author=Sepehr Zabir |year=2012 |title=The Left in Contemporary Iran (RLE Iran D) |publisher=Taylor & Francis |page=198 |quote=At the end of 1984 the party returned to a rigid Stalinist interpretation of post-Second World War developments in Soviet-Iranian relations...}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Communist Parties|expanded=Asia}}\n\n===Birth of the communist movement in Iran===\nThe history of the [[communist]] movement in Iran dates back to the late 19th century, when [[Marxism]] first became introduced to the nation's intellectual and working classes as a result of the rapid growth of industry and the subsequent transformation of the country's economy from a [[feudalistic]] system into a [[capitalistic]] one. Being close to the Soviet Union and the [[Caucasus]], northern Iran became the primary center of underground Marxist and [[social democrat]] political activity, and many such groups came into being over the years.\n\nThe [[Communist Party of Iran (1920)|Communist Party of Iran]] was founded in June 1920 in [[Bandar-e Anzali]], in the province of [[Gilan]], as a result of the first congress of Iranian social democrats. [[Haydar Khan e Amo-oghli|Heidar Amou Oghly]], who was one of the leaders of the [[Constitutional Revolution of Iran]], became the secretary-general of the new party. At the same time, [[Mirza Koochak Khan|Mirza Koochak Khan Jangali]], another major leader of the Constitutional Revolution and also leader of the revolutionary [[Jungle Movement of Gilan|Jangali]] (Foresters Movement), established the [[Soviet Republic of Gilan]] with the assistance of the [[Red Army]] of the Soviet Union.<ref>H. RamHormozi, ''Averting An Iranian Geopolitical Crisis: A Tale of Power Play for Dominance Between Colonial Powers, Tribal and Government Actors in the Pre and Post World War One Era'' (Victoria, BC, Canada: Friesen Press, 2016), 274.</ref><ref>Arutiun Airapetian and Marcelo Gryckiewicz, ''Transcaucasian Banknotes'' (BoD \u2013 Books on Demand, 2009), 190.</ref><ref>The [[United Kingdom|British]], who were a dominant influence in the [[Qajar dynasty|Qajar]] court of [[Tehran]], reportedly sent agents to infiltrate the Foresters Movement in a carefully prepared plot.</ref>\n\nWith the defeat of both the newly formed Soviet Republic of Gilan and the Communist Party, Communist and social democrat activity once again went underground. In the early 1920s the Qajar dynasty finally collapsed, and [[Reza Shah]] ascended to the throne in 1925, establishing the [[Pahlavi dynasty]]. The new Shah introduced many reforms, such as limiting the power of the [[Shi'a]] clergy, but also in turn established an [[authoritarian]] dictatorship.\n\nIn 1929\u201330, the party organized strikes in an [[Isfahan]] textile mill, the [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]] railways, [[Mashhad]] carpet workshops, and most importantly, in the British-owned oil industry. The government cracked down heavily and some 200 communists were arrested; 38 were incarcerated in [[Qasr Prison]] in Tehran. \"Seven died there - all from natural causes.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2010}} Along with the [[Purge of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Stalin purges]], which took a heavy toll from Iranian communist exiles living in the Soviet Union, these arrests meant the Communist Party of Iran \"ceased to exist for all practical purposes outside the walls of Qasr.\"<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Tortured Confessions: Prisons and Public Recantations in Modern Iran'' by Ervand Abrahamian, (University of California Press, 1999) p. 28\u201329</ref>\n\n===Foundation of the Tudeh Party===\nThe British-Soviet [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[Persian Corridor|invasion]] of 1941\u201342 resulted in the end of Reza Shah's reign and his forced exile to [[South Africa]]. Many political prisoners were subsequently released and under this new atmosphere, [[nationalist]] and [[socialist]] groups once again flourished. [[Iraj Iskandari]] and his closest colleagues decided to form a [[Marxist\u2013Leninist]] party appealing to the broad masses.<ref>Abrahamian, ''History of Modern Iran'' (2008) p. 107</ref> They founded the Tudeh party on 29 September 1941, electing [[Soleiman Mohsen Eskandari]] as chairman.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3312-2016-10-04-06-51-45&usg=ALkJrhihJ3cxamgvL1C8NuCMT9sGqG7fCA DOCUMENT CENTRAL COMMITTEE OF THE TUDEH PARTY OF IRAN ON THE OCCASION OF 75TH ANNIVERSARY OF THE TUDEH PARTY OF IRAN], 2016</ref>\n\nInitially the party was intended to be \"a [[Liberalism|liberal]] rather than a radical party\", with a platform stressing the importance of \"constitutional\" and \"individual rights\", protecting \"democracy\" and \"judicial integrity\" from [[fascism]], [[imperialism]] and [[militarism]]. \"At Soleiman Eskandari's urging\", the party initially attempted to appeal to non-secular masses by barring women from membership, organizing [[Day of Ashura|Moharram processions]], and designating \"a special prayer room in its main clubhouse.\" This orientation did not last and the party moved \"rapidly to the left\" within months of its founding.<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'' (1999), pp. 77\u201378</ref>\n\n===Early peak===\n{{see also|Coalition government of Ahmad Qavam}}\nIn 1944, the party entered the 14th [[Majlis of Iran|Majlis]] elections and eight of its candidates were elected. It also established the secret [[Tudeh Party Military Organization of Iran]], or TPMO (''Sazman-e Nezami-ye Hezb-e Tudeh-ye Iran'') made up of officers in the military. The TPMO provided the party with intelligence and information from the military to protect it from the security forces and give it military strength, though historians believe the party had no plan at that time to use the TPMO to stage a coup.<ref name=\"Behrooz103\" />\n\nAt the same time, Tudeh took a strong stand in favor of women's rights, starting in 1943. This included advocating for equal pay for equal work, two months of maternity leave for female workers and otherwise standing for women's social rights, working with those who had been fighting for these goals for years and were [[socialist]].<ref>Women and Islam: Women's movements in Muslim societies, ed. Haideh Moghissi, p. 92-94.</ref>\nEven so, issues of [[reproduction]], [[sexuality]], and other elements within family life were not discussed.\n\nFrom this point on the party grew immensely and became a major force in Iranian politics. By early 1945, the party had managed to create the first mass organization in Iran's history. Police records later revealed it had an estimated 2,200 hard-core members \u2013 700 of them in [[Tehran]] \u2013 \"10,000s of sympathizers in its youth and women's organizations, and 100,000s of sympathizers in its labor and craft unions.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999) p. 81</ref> Its main newspaper, ''[[Rahbar (newspaper)|Rahbar]]'' (Leader), boasted a circulation of more than 100,000 \u2013 triple that of the \"semi-official newspaper\" ''[[Ettela'at]].'' British ambassador [[Reader Bullard]] called it the only coherent political force in the country, and the ''[[New York Times]]'' reckoned it and its allies could win as much as 40% of the vote in a fair election.<ref>''Ettela'at'', 24 September 1979, quoted in Abrahamian, ''History of Modern Iran'' (2008) pp. 108\u201309</ref>\n\nThis period has been called the height of the party's intellectual influence which came in large part from the prestige and propaganda of the [[Soviet Union]] as \"the world's most progressive nation.\" Few intellectuals \"dared oppose\" the party \"even if they did not join.\" Marking the end of the \"near hegemony of the party over intellectual life\" in Iran was the resignation from the party of celebrated writer [[Jalal Al-e-Ahmad]] circa 1948 to form a [[socialist]] splinter group \u2013[[Third Force (Iran)|Third Force]]\u2013 in protest against the Tudeh's \"nakedly pro-Soviet\" policies.<ref>Mottahedeh, Roy, ''The Mantle of the Prophet: Religion and Politics in Iran'', One World, Oxford, 1985, 2000, p. 290</ref>\n\nTarnishing the appeal of the Tudeh in the next two years 1944\u201346 were Soviet demands for a [[petroleum]] concession in northern Iran and the Soviet sponsoring of ethnic revolts in [[Iranian Kurdistan|Kurdestan]] and [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]]. Despite the fact that Tudeh deputies in the [[Majles of Iran#Pre-Revolution Majlis \u2013 National Consultative Assembly|Majles]] had previously vigorously demanded the [[nationalization]] of the whole petroleum industry, the Tudeh party supported granting the Soviet petroleum industry in Iran its wishes on grounds of \"socialist solidarity\", \"internationalism,\" and \"anti-imperialism.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'' (1999) p. 82</ref>\n\n====International Cold War context====\nDuring this time the rest of the international communist movement was also thriving. The communist world expanded dramatically in the decade following [[World War II]] with [[Eastern Bloc|Eastern Europe]], [[Chinese Civil War|China]], [[Division of Korea|North Korea]], and [[First Indochina War|Vietnam]] all becoming states dominated by their respective communist parties, usually via military victory. In the United States, Iran was seen as the holder of reserves of petroleum with \"vital strategic\" value to western countries,<ref>Byrne, p. 213</ref> and as part of \"a Northern Tier\" of countries (along with Greece and Turkey) that constituted a geopolitical \"first line of defense\" for the [[Mediterranean]] and for [[Asia]],<ref>Byrne, p. 214</ref>  To counter the activities of the USSR, the CIA established [[Operation TPBEDAMN]] in the late 1940s, funded at $1 million a year. It prepared both \"disguised (`gray` propaganda) or deliberately misrepresented [[black propaganda]]\" in the form of \"newspaper articles, cartoons, leaflets, and books\" which it translated into Persian, most of which \"portrayed the Soviet Union and the Tudeh as anti-Iranian or anti-Islamic, described the harsh reality of life in the Soviet Union, or explained the Tudeh's close relationship with the Soviets and its popular-front strategy.\"<ref>Gasiorowski writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark J. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, [[Syracuse University Press]], 2004, p. 243</ref> In addition it paid \"right-wing nationalist organizations\" and some [[Shia]] religious figures. Its agents provoked \"violent acts\" and blamed them on the communists, and hired \"thugs to break up Tudeh rallies.\"<ref>Byrne writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.217</ref> Nonetheless the party was able to fill the streets of Tehran and Abadan \"with tens of thousands of enthusiastic demonstrators\" for [[International Workers' Day|May Day]] in 1946.<ref>Kinzer, ''All the Shah's Men'', 2003, p. 65</ref>\n\n===1949 crackdown===\nIn February 1949 there was an attempt on the life of Shah [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]].  The party was blamed by the government and banned. The government \"confiscated its assets, dissolved affiliated organizations, especially the Central Council and rounded up some 200 leaders and cadres.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999) p.84</ref>\n\nThe party continued to function underground however and by 1950 it had organized its supporters under the banner of the Iran Society for Peace (''Jam'iyat-e Irani-ye Havadar-e Solh'') and was publishing three daily papers, ''Razm'', ''Mardom'', and ''Besui-ye Ayandeh.''<ref name=\"Behrooz103\">Behrooz writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.103</ref> In December 1950, the TPMO, its military organization, managed \"to arrange for escape of key members of the party leadership who had been in jail since early 1949.\"<ref name=\"Behrooz103\"/>\n\nSuch suppression was assisted by conservatives detesting the Tudeh Party, which was later outlawed and allied with Mossadegh.<ref name=\"Michele Penner Angris 2011\">Michele Penner Angris, Party Building in the Modern Middle East (US: University of Washington Press, 2011),\n131.</ref> One Iranian conservative newspaper even editorialized:\n\n<blockquote> the Tudeh Party, with its santonic doctrine of class struggles, has incited ignorant workers to violate the sacred right of private property and inflict social anarchy upon the center of the country. This uprising proves that Tudeh is an enemy of private property, of Iran, and of Islam. If the government does not stamp out Tudeh, the local revolt will inevitably spread into a general revolution.</blockquote>\n\n===Mosaddeq era, his overthrow and aftermath===\n\nThe party played an important role both directly and indirectly during the pivotal era of Iranian history that began with the 1951 [[nationalization]] of the British [[Anglo Iranian Oil Company]] (AIOC), and ending with the 1953 overthrow of [[Mohammad Mosaddeq]] by a [[CIA]]-led [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]].  The party's policy \"fluctuated,\" first attacking Mosaddeq as `an agent of American imperialism,` then giving him some support during and after the July 1952 uprising.  On 15 August a coup attempt against Mosaddeq was thwarted thanks in part to information uncovered by the Tudeh TPMO military network, but two days later party militants inadvertently helped destabilized the government by staging demonstrations to pressure Mosaddeq to declare Iran a democratic republic. As this would have overturned Iran's constitutional monarchy, Mosaddeq reacted by calling out troops to suppress the demonstrators. The party then demobilized late the next day making it unavailable to fight the coup the day after.<ref name=\"Behrooz121\">Behrooz writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.121</ref>  By 1957 the TPMO was crushed and thousands of party members had been arrested.<ref name=assassination>Doug Noble, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2012/07/19/assassination-nation/ Assassination Nation], [[CounterPunch]], 2012.</ref>\n\n====Oil nationalization====\n[[File:Tudeh leaders Soviet party Congress.jpg|thumb|300px|Senior members of Tudeh in 1955 (left to right): [[Reza Rousta|Rousta]], [[Fereydoun Keshavarz|Keshavarz]], [[Reza Radmanesh|Radmanesh]], [[Iraj Eskandari|Eskandari]] and [[Abdolsamad Kambakhsh|Kambakhsh]]]]\nFollowing World War II, Iranian public support was growing for nationalization of the British Anglo Iranian Oil Company (AIOC)<ref>Saikal, Amin, ''The Rise and Fall of the Shah'', (Princeton University Press, 1980), p.42. Note: AIOC later became [[British Petroleum]] (BP)</ref> whose profits had greatly exceeded its royalty payments to the Iranian government.\n\nIn 1951, [[Mohammad Mosaddeq]], head of the [[nationalist]] movement known as the [[National Front of Iran]], led parliament in the nationalization of AIOC, and shortly after was appointed [[prime minister]] by the Shah. Mosaddeq oversaw the takeover of British oil facilities and rising economic difficulty and polarization in Iran as the AIOC withdrew its employees and retaliated with a boycott of Iranian oil.<ref>Saikal, ''The Rise and Fall of the Shah'', (1980), p.43-4</ref>\n\nIn early April 1951 the Tudeh revealing its \"true strength\" by launched strikes and riots protesting low wages and bad housing in oil industry and delays in nationalization of the oil industry.<ref name=\"Michele Penner Angris 2011\" /> There were \"street demonstrations and sympathy strikes in [[Tehran]], [[Isfahan]], and the northern cities.\" Police opened fire on demonstrators. A result was \"panic\" in Iran's parliament at the power of Marxist forces in Iran.<ref>\"Abrahamian, 1982, p.266\"</ref> With this, it is clear that not only was Mossadegh not a communist but Tudeh did not control the government or want to overthrow him even as was establishing a broad public base.<ref>Ron Jacobs, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2013/02/15/the-coup-of-coups/ The Coup of Coups], [[CounterPunch]], 15 February 2013.</ref><ref>Vijay Prashad, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/01/iran-and-us/ Iran and Us], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 1 July 2009.</ref>\n\nDuring this period the Tudeh followed a \"leftist\" rather than \"[[Popular front#The Comintern's Popular Front policy 1934\u20131939|popular front]]\" strategy, refusing to ally with Mosaddeq. Despite the fact that Mosaddeq had introduced a new policy of tolerance toward the party,<ref>Azimi writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.72</ref> that both the Tudeh and Mosaddeq had worked for nationalization of the AIOC,<ref>Hussein Fateh, \"the anticommunist leader of the defunct Comrade's party\": Panjah ''Saleh-e Naft-i Iran'' Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' (1982), p.320</ref> and that expropriation of [[capitalist]] Western-owned resource extracting corporations by [[developing countries|poor countries]] was central to [[Marxism-Leninism|Marxist-Leninist]] doctrine, the party vigorously and relentlessly opposed Mosaddeq and his program.  In a June 1950 article in its daily ''Mardom'' it described the effects of Mosaddeq's policy thusly:\n\n<blockquote>Already we can be sure that revisions in the southern oil contract will not be in favor of our people and will only result in the consolidation of England's position in our country. ... The solution of the oil question is related to the victory of our party, that is, the people of Iran.<ref name=\"Behrooz108\">Behrooz writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.108</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn 16 July 1952, Mosaddeq resigned after the shah refused to accept his nomination for War Minister. Mosaddeq appealed to the general public for support, but Tudeh press continued to attack him, describing his differences with the shah \"as merely one between different factions of a reactionary ruling elite.\"<ref name=\"Behrooz, p.109\">Behrooz, p.109</ref> It was only after the explosion of popular support for Mosaddeq in the street that \"many rank-and-file\" Tudeh party members \"could see first hand Mosaddeq's popularity\",<ref name=\"Behrooz, p.109\" /> and came to his aid.\n\nAccording to one observer:\n<blockquote>although diverse elements participated in the July uprising, the impartial observer must confess that the Tudeh played an important part\u2014perhaps even the most important part. ... If in the rallies before March 1952 one-third of the demonstrators had been Tudeh and two-thirds had been National Front, after March 1952, the proportions were reversed.<ref>Comment of Hussein Fateh, \"the anticommunist leader of the defunct Comrade's party\": Panjah ''Saleh-e Naft-i Iran'' Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' (1982), p.320</ref></blockquote>\n\nAyatollah [[Abol-Ghasem Kashani]], who later switched sides and supported the Shah, \"sent a public letter to the pro-Tudeh organizations thanking them for their invaluable contribution\" during the uprising toward Mosaddeq's victory.<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' (1982), p.320</ref>\n\nMosaddeq capitalized on the uprising to establish emergency rule, which allowed him to bypass the Majles, and also to institute socialist reforms.<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' by Ervand Abrahamian, (Princeton University Press, 1982), p.323</ref> With the Soviets not wanting to back or \"shore up\" Tudeh, and Truman refusing demands to overthrow Mossadegh from [[Clement Attlee]] and [[Winston Churchill]], it would take the inauguration of Dwight Eisenhower to change the tune, greenlighting the coup operation.<ref>Wahid Azal, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/08/29/the-banality-of-evil-and-the-ivory-tower-masterminds-of-the-1953-coup-detat-in-iran/ The Banality of Evil and the Ivory Tower Masterminds of the 1953 Coup d\u2019Etat in Iran], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 29 August 2016.</ref><ref>Gary Leupp, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2005/07/06/accusing-ahmadinejad/ Accusing Ahmadinejad], 6 July 2005.</ref>\n\n====1953 coup====\nDuring this time the US government became more and more frustrated with Mosaddeq and the stalemate over negotiations with the UK government on control and compensation, with the American ambassador even questioning Mosaddeq's \"mental stability\".<ref>Byrne, writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p. 222</ref> At the same time the [[cold war]] struggle continued to dominate foreign policy thinking in the west.  Soviet tanks crushed an anti-communist [[Uprising of 1953 in East Germany|uprising of strikes and protests in East Germany]] in June 1953.<ref>\"Books And Arts: How to change a regime in 30 days; Iran\", ''The Economist''. London: 16 August 2003. Vol. 368, Iss. 8337; pg. 74</ref><ref>Kinzer, Stephen, ''All the Shah's Men : An American Coup and the Roots of Middle East Terror'', John Wiley and Sons, 2003, p. 84</ref>\n\nAs Americans gave up hope on Mosaddeq, their propaganda and covert action campaign against the Tudeh, called TPBEDAMN, expanded to include him.<ref>Mark J. Gasiorowski,[http://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1162/JCWS_a_00393 The CIA's TPBEDAMN: Operation and the 1953 Coup in Iran], Journal of Cold War Studies, Vol. 15: Issue. 4: Pages. 4-24. Issue publication date: October 2013.</ref> In 1953, American CIA and British intelligence agents, began plotting to overthrow Mosaddeq in a [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]], in large part because of their fear that \"rising internal tensions and continued deterioration ... might lead to a breakdown of government authority and open the way for at least a gradual assumption of control by Tudeh,\" just as a local communist party had led a [[Czechoslovak coup d'\u00e9tat of 1948|coup in Czechoslovakia]] in 1948, replacing a democratic regime and constitution with a pro-Soviet, one-party Communist government.<ref>Gasiorowski writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, pp. 230\u201331</ref>\n\nThe Tudeh also sensed a coup might be coming, and created \"vanguard cells\" that along with the TPMO, \"identified key military installation, army depots, and command and control centers in the capital\" Tehran \"to react violently to any coup attempt.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 116</ref> Recently released photographs by [[William Arthur Cram]] show that Tudeh organized huge demonstrations in August before the coup occurred.<ref>Saeed Kamali Dehghan, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/iran-blog/gallery/2015/dec/16/unseen-images-of-the-1953-iran-coup-in-pictures Unseen images of 1953 Iran Coup - in pictures], ''The Guardian'', 16 December 2015.</ref>\n\nThe plotters first attempt involved persuading the shah to issue an edict dismissing Mosaddeq and replacing him with retired General [[Fazlollah Zahedi]], while arresting Mosaddeq and taking over other possible centers of opposition. On 15 August the plot was uncovered by Tudeh supporters in the military, and a contingent sent to arrest Mosaddeq were intercepted and arrested themselves. Colonel Mohammad Ali Mobasherri, was a member of the TPMO's (secret) three-man secretariat, but also an active member of Tehran Military Governor, the center of the coup operation. Major Hehdi Homaouni served in the shah's Imperial Guard and discovered and reported the August plot to the party.<ref>Behrooz, p. 117</ref> In a recent set of documents released by the [[National Security Archive]], which noted pro-Shah demonstrators sacked pro-Tudeh and pro-Mossadegh establishments, it was noted that British and American intelligence agents infiltrated Tudeh so it could blunt Mossadegh. These documents also noted that Eisenhower and Truman differed in their assessments of Mossadegh, with Eisenhower feeling he could not as effectively counter Tudeh as Truman and the CIA in August 1953 downplaying \"the likelihood of a Tudeh overthrow attempt\" but fears the Tudeh taking power in a more long-term fashion.<ref>[http://nsarchive.gwu.edu/NSAEBB/NSAEBB126/ Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran], ed. by Mark J. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, [[National Security Archive]], 2004.</ref>\n\nThe coup attempt created a backlash against its perpetrators, including the shah. The already anti-monarchical Tudeh supporters were radicalized and on the morning of 17 August \"an angry crowd began to attack symbols of the monarchy\" and demanded its abolition.  Mosaddeq, who was aware of Western fears of the Tudeh and who had worked to limit the power of the shah but had \"never suggested he was in favor of abolishing the constitutional monarchy,\" saw these attacks as a challenge, as removing the shah would violate the constitution.<ref>Behrooz, p. 119, 120</ref> The next day his regime ordering the military into the streets, and \"up to 600 mid and low-level Tudeh activists were arrested in Tehran alone.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 120</ref> With its network \"severely damaging\" the party reversed course once again, and \"ordered a demobilization\" of its preparations to fight a coup.<ref>Behrooz, p. 121</ref><ref>Rostam Pourzal, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2008/08/21/the-left-and-iran/ The Left and Iran], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 21 August 2008.</ref>\n\nTaking advantage of the quiet, the CIA and its Iranian allies struck again, and on 19 August the [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] replaced Mosaddeq with Zahedi. The coup was a major event in Third World and 20th Century history and there is debate as to how much of the blame for the overthrow can be traced to bribes paid by the CIA and how much to domestic dissatisfaction with Mossadeq.<ref>Nasr, Vali, ''The Shia Revival'', Norton, (2005), p. 124</ref><ref>Mackay, Sandra, ''The Iranians'', Plume (1997), pp. 203\u201304</ref><ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' by Ervand Abrahamian, Princeton University Press, 1982, pp. 276\u201377</ref> Whatever the motivations, [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] thereafter assumed dictatorial powers and banned most political groups, including Mossadegh's National Front, which along with the Tudeh Party, continued to function underground.\n\n====Crackdown following coup====\nThe mass arrests, destruction of its organization and execution of some 40\u201350 leaders following the coup has been said to have \"destroyed\" the Tudeh.<ref name=\"Abrahamian, Ervand p.122\" /> Between 1953 and 1957, Iranian security forces using \"brute force, together with the breaking of the cryptographic code \u2013 probably with CIA know-how \u2013 \u2026 tracked down 4,121 party members.\" This constituted the whole Tudeh underground and \"more than half the party membership\". Tudeh infiltration of the military by the TPMO<ref>Office of the Military Governor of Teheran: Black Book on Tudeh Officers Organization. 1956. {{ISBN|978-3-8442-7813-2}}. [http://www.epubli.de/shop/buch/Black-Book-on-Tudeh-Officers-Organization-Teymour-Bakhtiar-9783844278132/33792]</ref> totaled 477 members in the armed forces, \"22 colonels, 69 majors, 100 captains, 193 lieutenants, 19 noncommissioned officers, and 63 military cadets.\" Ervand Abrahamian notes that none of these were in the \"crucial tank divisions around Tehran\" that could have been used for a coup d'\u00e9tat and which the Shah had screened carefully. \"Ironically, a Tudeh colonel had been in charge of the Shah's personal security \u2013 as well as that of Vice President Richard Nixon when he visited Iran. The Tudeh had the opportunity to assassinate the Shah and the U.S. vice president but not to launch a coup.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p. 92</ref> [[Maziar Behrooz]] is more optimistic about the party's chances of stopping the coup, saying that while \"most of the Tudeh officers were in non-combat posts,\" they \"were in a position to access and distribute weapons. In their memoirs, TPMO high- and middle-ranking members have confirmed their ability to distribute weapons and even to assassinate key Iranian leaders of the coup. Hence, with a disciplined party membership, backed by military officers with access to weapons, the Tudeh had a strong hand.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 106</ref>\n\nWith the TPMO decimated, the Tudeh network was compromised as the TPMO had \"acted as a shield for the party\" and helped preserve it immediately after Mosaddeq's overthrow. \"Many high- and middle-ranking Tudeh leaders were arrested or forced to flee the country. The arrest and execution of [[Khosro Roozbeh]] in 1957-8 signaled the end of this process.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 124</ref>\n\n====Tudeh verdict====\nAfter the fact, the party engaged in self-criticism of its policies toward Mosaddeq at its Fourth Plenum held in Moscow in July 1957. They found them \"sectarian and leftist\" and not to recognizing \"the progressive nature\" of the oil nationalization movement.{{clarify|date=January 2013}}<ref>Behrooz, p. 123</ref>\n\n===Late 1950s and 1960s===\nThe [[Sino\u2013Soviet split]] caused some splintering of the party in the early 1960s, with at least one Maoist group breaking away.<ref>*\"In the early 1960s, moreover the Tudeh was further weakened by defections. With the eruption of the Sino-Soviet dispute, three Tudeh leaders left the party and formed a party called the Organization of Marxist-Leninists. At the same time, some members of the party's youth section left and formed the Revolutionary Organization of the Tudeh Party.\" [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3012310?seq=3 Iran in Revolution: The Opposition Forces], Ervand Abrahamian</ref> In the mid 1960s, the [[U.S. State Department]] estimated the party membership to be approximately 1500.<ref>Benjamin, Roger W.; Kautsky, John H.. ''[https://www.jstor.org/stable/1953329 Communism and Economic Development]'', in The [[American Political Science Review]], Vol. 62, No. 1. (Mar. 1968), pp. 122.</ref>\n\nIn 1965, the party faced a second division between the mainstream of the organization and the splinter faction, which advocated violent struggle against the government by arming the tribes of southern Iran. This faction caused a great deal of damage and three years passed before the unity of the party was restored. The remnants of this faction are known as the [[Labour Party of Iran]].\n\nIn 1966, several party members, including [[Ali Khavari]] and [[Parviz Hekmatjoo]] of the Central Committee, and [[Asef Razmdideh]] and [[Saber Mohammadzadeh]], were arrested and sentenced to death. This sparked international outcry and hunger strikes in Europe which forced the government to reduce the sentences to life imprisonment. These events created much international sympathy for the worker's struggle in Iran and helped unify the party after the split. The Tudeh Party from this point on becomes established as one of the strongest underground movements and helps to pave the way for the forthcoming [[Iranian Revolution]] of 1979.\n\n===Iranian Revolution of 1979===\nIn the early 1970s, the Iranian [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla]] movement began in northern Iran in the province of [[Mazandaran]]. The 1970s also witnessed the birth of widespread worker's strikes and demonstrations, and university campuses became a hotbed of revolutionary activity. In 1973, Tudeh released a brochure titled \"Oil from Iran and imperialist oil monopolies,\" likely advocating for oil nationalization.<ref>Brochure of the Iranian Tudeh Party, \"[http://www.iisg.nl/collections/crises/bro5647-4.php Oil from Iran and imperialist oil monopolies],\" Safari, Hamid: Impiryalism-i naftkhar. Strassfurt, Tudeh Publishing Centre [1973]. Call number: Bro 5647/4.</ref> The Tudeh Party drastically increased its activities, recruiting many youth and organizing regional committees, supporting the [[Islamic Revolution]] when others on the [[Left-wing politics|left]] opposed it.<ref name=Tripathi>Deepak Tripathi, \"[http://www.counterpunch.org/2011/12/13/iran-the-islamic-revolution-and-the-language-of-war/ Iran, the Islamic Revolution and the Language of War],\" ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 13 December 2011.</ref><ref>Gary Leupp, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2003/09/05/shiites-humiliate-bush/ Shiites Humiliate Bush], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 5 September 2003.</ref><ref>Ron Jacobs, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2004/12/28/the-resistance-and-the-west-s-anti-war-movement/ The Resistance and the West\u2019s Anti-War Movement], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 28 December 2004.</ref>\n\n===Islamic Republic===\nDuring the revolution, many political prisoners were freed and the Tudeh Party and other leftist groups were able to participate in the presidential and parliamentary elections for the first time in many years. However, the majority of seats in the Majlis were won by the [[Islamic Republican Party]] of [[Mohammad Beheshti|Ayatollah Beheshti]] and leftist and nationalist organizations were forced out of the loop. The newly elected President, [[Abolhassan Banisadr]], who had originally been close with [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], also became increasingly frustrated with the developments that had been taking place and opposed the domination of the clergy and the religious factions in Iranian politics. In addition, the party denounced Amnesty International's call to end the summary executions and called it \"blatant interference in Iranian affairs\".<ref name=mmm>{{cite journal|last=Milani|first=Mohsen M.|title=Harvest of Shame: Tudeh and the Bazargan Government|journal=Middle Eastern Studies|date=April 1993|volume=29|issue=2|pages=307\u2013320|jstor=4283563|doi=10.1080/00263209308700950}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the Majlis, dominated by the Islamic Republican Party, forced Bani Sadr out of office, which initiated a wave of protests and demonstrations from all segments of the populace. Bani Sadr later fled the country. Armed revolutionary committees loyal to Khomeini (which came to be known as the ''[[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps|Pasdaran]]'') arrested many thousands of youth and activists from both nationalist and leftist groups, many of whom were later tried by [[Lajevardi]], who was known as the ''Hanging Judge'', and executed.\n\nAt this point in the history of the Tudeh Party, the [[Christians|Christian]] and [[Azeris]] within the population were prominent.<ref>Michele Penner Angris, ''Party Building in the Modern Middle East'' (US: University of Washington Press, 2011), 71.</ref>\n\n====Suppression====\nWhile other leftist parties opposed the Islamist forces at this time, and were suppressed as a result, Tudeh Party leadership as well as the [[Organization of Iranian People's Fedaian (Majority)|Fadaian Aksariat]] decided to oppose politically with the new clerical theocratic regime and support the crackdown on the militant armed opposition. This may have been to try to take advantage of the lack of competition from the many now suppressed rival leftist groups, or to follow the pro-Tehran line of the Soviet Union.{{citation needed|date=April 2008}}\n\nIn 1982, however, the Tudeh broke ranks. The Islamist government of Iran had closed down the Tudeh newspaper, and purged Tudeh members from government ministries. According to the [[Mitrokhin Archive]], [[Vladimir Kuzichkin]], a [[KGB]] officer stationed in Tehran, had defected to the British in 1982. [[MI6]] used this information and shared the information with the [[CIA]]. Their information was then shared with the Iranian government by the CIA, which was secretly courting Iran, as part of the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair]].<ref>{{cite book|authorlink1=John Tower|last1=Tower|first1=John|authorlink2=Edmund Muskie|last2=Muskie|first2=Edmund|authorlink3=Brent Scowcroft|last3=Scowcroft|first3=Brent|title=[[Tower Commission|Report of the President's Special Review Board]]|publisher=[[Bantam Books]]|year=1987|p=[https://archive.org/details/towercommission00unit/page/104 104]|isbn=9780553269680|quote=In 1983, the U.S. helped bring to the attention of Tehran the threat inherent in the extensive infiltration of the government by the communist Tudeh Party and Soviet or pro-Soviet cadres in the country. Using this information, the Khomeini government took measures, including mass executions, that virtually eliminated the pro-Soviet infrastructure in Iran.}} Available online [https://archive.org/stream/TowerCommission/President%27s%20Special%20Review%20Board%20%28%22Tower%20Commission%22%29#page/n67/mode/2up here.]</ref><ref name=assassination />\n\nQuite quickly the government arrested and imprisoned its leadership and later more than 10,000 members of the party. During February 1983, the leaders of the Tudeh Party were arrested and the Party disbanded, leaving Iran effectively a one-party state.<ref>Momen, Moojan, ''An Introduction to Shi'i Islam'', Yale University Press, 1985, p. 297</ref> The Tudeh arrests revealed that once again the party had managed to find supporters among the armed forces, as a number of officers, prominent among them [[Admiral]] [[Bahram Afzali]], commander of the [[Islamic Republic of Iran Navy|Iranian navy]], were arrested.<ref name=\"p.129\">Maziar Behrooz, ''Rebels with a Cause'', (2000), [https://books.google.com/books?id=ouuRaF5Ug1IC&printsec=frontcover#PPA129,M1 p. 129]</ref> These arrests ended the alliance between the Tudeh Party and the ruling clergy of Iran and it collapsed, even as the Soviets worked with the Iranians to build up their nuclear capabilities.<ref name=Tripathi /><ref>Ron Jacobs, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2015/08/05/talking-points-on-the-iran-nuke-deal/ Talking points on the Iran nuke deal], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 5 August 2015.</ref> Even with this agreement, the Iranian government saw the Soviets as \"atheistic devils\" and the Soviets did not like the government because it had suppressed the Tudeh.\n\nInternational media, such as [[United Press International|UPI]], reported that along with the banning of the Tudeh party, 18 Soviet diplomats were expelled from the country for \"blatant interference.\"<ref>Peyman Pezhman, \"[http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/05/04/Iran-Wednesday-outlawed-the-communist-Tudeh-Party-for-plotting/5014420868800/ Iran outlawed the communist Tudeh party for plotting],\" [[UPI]], 4 May 1983.</ref> At the same time, Tudeh was accused of working on behalf of \"foreign powers,\" with the suppression praised by Khomeini.\n\nFrom 1 May 1983 to May 1984 almost all the Tudeh leadership appeared in videos, first individually and then jointly in an October 1983 \"roundtable discussion,\" confessing to \"treason\", \"subversion\", \"horrendous crimes\", praising Islam and proclaiming Islamic government's superiority over atheistic Marxism\u2013Leninism.<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p. 177</ref> British officials supported Iran's crackdown and joked about the state torture techniques used to extract the confessions. British officials were pleased by the repression not primarily because they were concerned about Soviet influence in the country, since they knew that Iran was quite independent of that, but because they wanted to curry favor with the Iranian regime.<ref>The Daily Maverick, 21 January 2020, [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-21-how-britain-helped-irans-islamic-regime-destroy-the-left-wing-opposition/ \"How Britain Helped Iran\u2019s Islamic Regime Destroy the Left-Wing Opposition\"]</ref>\n\nIn May 1984 [[Ehsan Tabari]], appeared on television. A man with \"50 years of leftist experiences\" told viewers he had read \"great Islamic thinkers\" such as [[Morteza Motahhari|Ayatollah Motahhari]] in prison following the 1982 crackdown and had now come\n<blockquote>to repudiate the works he had written over the past 40 years. He now realized that his entire life's work was 'defective', 'damaging', and 'totally spurious' because it had all been based on unreliable thinkers \u2013 [[Freemasonry|Freemasons]] nourished by the [[Pahlavi dynasty|Pahlavis]]; [[Secularism|secularists]] such as [[Ahmad Kasravi]]; Western [[Liberalism|liberals]] and [[Marxist]]s linked to '[[imperialism]]' and '[[Zionism]]' \u2026<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'', (1999), p. 204</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn his recantation Tabari made frequent references to religion, the [[Twelve Imams]] and Islamic thinkers and \"praised Islam for its `great spiritual strength.`\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), pp. 204\u201305</ref>\n\nThe suspicions of outside observers that the confession was not given freely were reinforced by the absence of Taqi Keymanash and \"13 other members\" of the Tudeh central committee, who died during prison interrogation.<ref>United Nations (Economic and Social Council) Situation of Human Rights in the Islamic Republic of Iran (New York, November 1990), p.53. quoted in Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p.191</ref> The rapid disintegration of the Tudeh at the hands of the state, and the confessions of its leaders led opposition and remaining party members to seek answers. Explanations ranged from ideological capitulation to the use of [[Stalinism|Stalinist]] methods of trial. The remnant of the party outside the country resorted to strange explanations that special drugs created by the [[CIA]] and [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI-6]] were used. The simplest explanation came several years after the television recantations, from a prison visit by a [[United Nations]]' human rights representative (Galindo Pohl) to Iran. The Tudeh Party General Secretary [[Noureddin Kianouri]] was reported to have told the representative that he and his wife had been tortured to give false confessions. As evidence, he held up his badly set broken arm. Pohl added that Maryam Firuz had difficulty hearing, swallowing food, and sitting down because of beatings suffered eight years earlier at the hands of the Shah's secret police.<ref name=\"p.129\" /><ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p.223</ref> Kianouri later wrote an open letter to the Ayatollah detailing his mistreatment.<ref name=\"Afshar\">Haleh Afshar, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/mar/31/iran \"Maryam Firouz\"], Obituary, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 31 March 2008</ref>\n\nAs a result of these purges, a great number of party members left the country into exile. As the party represented the \"Soviet view of a preferred leftist movement\" that holds a pro-Soviet ideological line and responds to Soviet foreign policy in a supportive manner, the [[Soviet Union]] was likely disappointed at the development.<ref>Foundation for Constitutional Government in Iran, \"Soviet presence in Iran: the case of the Tudeh Party\" (1985), p. 2, 3, 7.</ref> It is likely many hundreds Tudeh prisoners were killed during the [[1988 executions of Iranian political prisoners]] when thousands of [[People's Mujahedin of Iran|Mojahedin]] and leftist prisoners were killed.<ref>[http://www.executedtoday.com/2017/02/25/1984-ten-members-of-the-tudeh-party/ 1984: Ten Members of the Tudeh Party], ExecutedToday.com, 25 February 2017.</ref> One report lists 90 Tudeh killed in just some blocks of [[Evin Prison|Evin]] and [[Gohardasht Prison|Gohar Dasht prisons]].\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{{see also|Tudeh fraction}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Election\n!Seats won \n|-\n|1943\n| [[Iranian legislative election, 1943\u20131944|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|9|136|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n|1947 \n| [[1947 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|2|136|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\"|''{{small|Banned in 1949 election}}''\n|-\n|1952 \n| [[1952 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|0|79|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\"|''{{small|Did not contest between 1953 and 1978 due to being banned}}''\n|-\n|1979 \n| [[1979 Iranian Constitutional Convention election|Constitutional Assembly]]\n| {{composition bar compact|0|73|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n|1980 \n| [[1980 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|0|270|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\"|''{{small|Banned since 1983}}''\n|-\n|}\n\n== Estimated membership ==\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|-\n!Year\n!Members\n!Ref\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1942||2,087 {{small|(towards September)}}||<ref>{{citation|title=Did the Soviets play a role in founding the Tudehparty in Iran?|author=Cosroe Chaqueri|url=https://monderusse.revues.org/pdf/22|date=1 April 1999|publisher=\u00c9ditions de l\u2019EHESS|journal=Cahiers du Monde Russe|volume=40|number=3|doi=10.4000/monderusse.22|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n|-\n|6,000||<ref name=\"IBTR\">{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0}}</ref>{{rp|284}}\n|-\n|1944||25,800||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|293}}\n|-\n|1945||69,000||<ref name=\"R\">{{cite book|title=Political Thought and Political History: Studies in Memory of Elie Kedourie|first=Moshe|last=Gammer|date=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135774851|page=144}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1946||50,000 {{small|core members}} + 100,000 {{small|affiliates}}||<ref>{{cite book|title=Social Movements in Egypt and Iran|first=Tara|last=Povey|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781137379009|page=51}}</ref>\n|-\n|80,000||<ref>{{cite journal|title=Iran Finds a Party System: The Institutionalization of \"Iran Novin\"|journal=Middle East Journal|volume=27|number=4|year=Autumn 1973|pages=439\u2013455|publisher=Middle East Institute|author=Marvin G. Weinbaum {{subscription}}|jstor=4325140}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1947||50,000\u2013200,000||<ref name=\"UU\">{{cite thesis|type=BA thesis|title=Leftists as a Political Opposition in Iran|author=Amanda N. Jarvis|url=http://cdmbuntu.lib.utah.edu/utils/getfile/collection/etd3/id/3605/filename/3604.pdf|date=2015|publisher=University of Utah}}</ref>\n|-\n|275,000 {{small|including affiliated labor unions' membership}}||<ref name=\"UU\"/>\n|-\n|1949||25,000||<ref name=\"R\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Social Origins of the Iranian Revolution|first=Misagh|last=Parsa|date=1989|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=9780813514123|page=40}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1952||20,000||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|320}}\n|-\n||50,000 {{small|including sympathizers and affiliated membership}}||<ref>{{cite book|author=Sepehr Zabih|title=The Communist Movement in Iran|year=1966|url=https://archive.org/details/communistmovemen0000zabi|url-access=registration|publisher=University of California Press|page=176}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1953||15,000\u201320,000||<ref>{{cite book|title=The Soviet Union and Revolutionary Iran|first=Aryeh|last=Yodfat|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-61058-2|page=19}}</ref>\n|-\n|25,000 + 300,000 {{small|sympathizers}}||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|321}}\n|-\n|1965||3,000||<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hiro|first1=Dilip|title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals)|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=1135043817|page=202}}</ref>\n|-\n|1967||\u2264 1,000||<ref>{{citation|title=World Strength of the Communist Party Organizations, Issues 19-21, United States. Dept. of State. Intelligence report 4489 R-|publisher=United States. Department of State. Office of Intelligence Research and Analysis, United States. Department of State. Bureau of Intelligence and Research|year=1967|page=111}}</ref>\n|-\n|1977||5,000 ||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|457}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1979||1,500 + 400 {{small|exiled in [[East Germany]]}}||<ref name=\"cia\"/>\n|-\n|7,000 {{small|armed in [[Tehran]]}} ||<ref>{{Citation|last1=Ward|first1=Steven R.|year =2014|title=Immortal, Updated Edition: A Military History of Iran and Its Armed Forces|publisher=Georgetown University Press|page=226|isbn=9781626160651}}</ref>\n|-\n|1980||5,000||<ref name=\"cia\">{{citation|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP81B00401R000500110043-1.pdf|date=1 April 1980|title=Iran: Recent Tudeh Party Activity|id=CIA-RDP81B00401R000500110043-1|type=Intelligence Memorandum|work=Central Intelligence Agency}}</ref>\n|-\n|1983||\u2264 5,000 ||<ref>{{cite book|year=1985|author=United States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign Affairs, Library of Congress. Congressional Research Service|title=The Soviet Union in the third world, 1980-85: an imperial burden on political asset?|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=151}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Current status ==\nDespite repression, the party has managed to survive. Though since the [[Iranian Revolution]] the party is officially banned in Iran and individuals found to be affiliated with communist or [[socialist]] groups risk imprisonment, active members have remained and it continues to operate as an underground political organization there. This was mentioned in an [[Amnesty International]] report on [[political prisoners]] in Iran.<ref>Soheil Asefi, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2013/08/23/betraying-khavaran/ Betraying Khavaran], [[CounterPunch]], 23 August 2013.</ref>\n\nToday, the party leadership is mainly based in exile, as is the new Central Committee, elected in 1992. The party has taken positions against [[privatization]], criticizes the electoral system in the country, and \"anti-labor\" legislation.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3502-1025-25-1-1-1&usg=ALkJrhhUvWP7PYfXElKUyKG9b1wP8WddlQ PRIVATIZATION STILL MADE DISASTER! INCREASE THE IMPACT OF DEREGULATION AND PRIVATIZATION WORK, THE BRINGING JOBS TO WORKERS], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3499-1024-11-2-8&usg=ALkJrhjVZWaE0muNcYSvdjq1hTo5xownXQ TRUE FREEDOM, IN THE FACE OF ELECTORAL SHOWING GUARDIANSHIP GOVERNMENT CAN MAKE A DIFFERENCE!], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-31-04/3491-1024-11-2-1&usg=ALkJrhgOSqZF7l6-G1gw1bW1EhWMm2X5eA Anti-worker bill proposed in Iran], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-31-04/3494-1024-11-2-4&usg=ALkJrhiWgPyrXr65hTcPA_AaCMAJ3dV-0w Anti-labor forces unite in Iran], 2017.</ref> In 2017, the party supported [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] as a leftist force in France, commemorated the [[Russian Revolution]], pledged solidarity with the [[Venezuelan Communist Party]], and criticized [[Iranian reformists]] for betraying their ideals.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-37-25/3498-1024-11-2-7&usg=ALkJrhhEPwKAjFteaXkdDFDmXpbJGxAfHQ FRENCH PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION: THE BRILLIANT SUCCESS OF THE COMMUNIST PARTY CAMPAIGN], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3497-1024-11-2-7&usg=ALkJrhh9FPu0nlGwvZ9NTdddrvuJHZPxpA THE CENTENARY OF THE OCTOBER SOCIALIST REVOLUTION 2017 - 1917: \"ONE STEP FORWARD, TWO STEPS BACK\"], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-37-25/3496-1024-11-2-6&usg=ALkJrhicI81wa_Zd_H827ABk0tOccmgTlA Solidarity with the Venezuelan Communist Party], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3435-1019-2-12-12&usg=ALkJrhhwpMBKKDKRd535U1TwayPwMDQQdA \"RECONCILIATION\" WITH \"REPENT\" POSSIBLE! POLITICAL BANKRUPTCY AND COWARDICE \"REFORMERS\" DEFENDERS OF VELAYAT-E FAQIH REGIME], 2017.</ref> Additionally, the party condemned [[2017 Shayrat missile strike|the missile attacks on Syria]] in April 2017 by [[Donald Trump]], the only element of the Iranian opposition to do so, and has many wide-ranging party anthems on their website.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3477-1023-28-1-2&usg=ALkJrhgfkyTPBfr_l9i9Q_1310a3LDCedQ Domestic reactions to attack America], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-38-16&usg=ALkJrhj7SQfOJYvYmWTbHS20uokxpSOJBA Party Hymns], 2017.</ref> In 2020, the party condemned the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|Trump Adminstration's airstrike]] which killed [[Qasem Soleimani]], while simultaneously critiquing the Iranian regime for intervening in both Iraq and Lebanon.<ref>{{cite web |title=The urgent need to intensify efforts to preserve peace in the region and confront the adventurous and dangerous policies of US imperialism! |url=https://www.tudehpartyiran.org/en/news/4657-statement-of-the-central-committee-of-the-tudeh-party-of-iran-the-urgent-need-to-intensify-efforts-to-preserve-peace-in-the-region-and-confront-the-adventurous-and-dangerous-policies-of-us-imperialism |website=Tudeh Party of Iran |publisher=Central Committee of the Tudeh Party of Iran |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|#\n!rowspan=2|Name\n!colspan=2|Tenure\n!rowspan=2|Title\n!rowspan=2|Ref\n|-\n!From\n!To\n|-\n|1\n|[[Soleiman Eskandari]]\n|1941\n|1944\n|Chairman\n|<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/281 281, 292]|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/281}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2\n|[[Iraj Eskandari]]\n|rowspan=3|1944\n|rowspan=3|1948\n|rowspan=3|General-Secretaries<br />{{small|(Shared)}}\n|rowspan=3|<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/297 297]|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/297}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Mohammad Bahrami]]\n|-\n|[[Noureddin Alamouti]]\n|-\n|3\n|[[Reza Radmanesh]]\n|1948\n|1969\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/313 313]|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/313}}</ref>\n|-\n|\u2013\n|[[Mohammad Bahrami]]\n|1949\n|1953\n|Acting First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|last1=Maziar |first1=Behrooz|year=2000|title=Rebels With A Cause: The Failure of the Left in Iran|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=1860646301|page=11}}</ref>\n|-\n|4\n|[[Iraj Eskandari]]\n|1969\n|1979\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|title=ESKANDAR\u012a, \u012aRAJ|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]|date=15 December 1998|orig-year=19 January 2012|publisher=Bibliotheca Persica Press|location=New York City|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/eskandari-iraj|volume= VIII|last1=Chaqueri|first1=Cosroe|editor-last=Yarshater|editor-first=Ehsan|editor-link=Ehsan Yarshater|access-date=12 September 2017|series=Fasc. 6|pages=604\u2013606}}</ref>\n|-\n|5\n|[[Noureddin Kianouri]]\n|1979\n|1984\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n|-\n|\u2013\n|rowspan=2|[[Ali Khavari]]\n|1983\n|1984\n|Acting First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Sepehr Zabir|title=The Left in Contemporary Iran (RLE Iran D)|date=2012|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-136-81263-7|page=206}}</ref>\n|-\n|6\n|1984\n|2004\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hiro|first1=Dilip|title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals)|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=1135043817|page=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iran|Politics|Communism}}\n* [[Political parties in Iran]]\n* [[Constitutionalist movement of Gilan]]\n* [[Soviet Republic of Gilan]]\n* ''[[Iran is not just Tehran]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}} {{in lang|fa|en|de}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H8b_usgKnz4 Party anthem]\n{{Iranian exiled parties}}\n{{Middle East communist parties}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tudeh Party Of Iran}}\n[[Category:Tudeh Party of Iran| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Tudeh|places in Iran|Tudeh, Iran (disambiguation){{!}}Tudeh, Iran}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Tudeh Party of Iran\n| logo = Tudeh.PNG\n| leader1_title = International Secretary\n| leader1_name = Navid Shomali<ref name=\"MS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/a-f8cb-Tudeh-75-years-fighting-for-Irans-working-class |title=Tudeh: 75 Years Fighting For Iran\u2019s Working Class |date=8 October 2016 |access-date=11 March 2017 |work=[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]}}</ref>\n| leader2_title = Spokesperson\n| leader2_name = Mohammad Omidvar<ref name=\"MS\"/>\n| founders = [[The Fifty-Three]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1941|10|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"MS\"/>\n| banned = {{start date and age|1949|2|5|df=y}} (by [[Pahlavi dynasty]])<br>{{start date and age|1983|2|df=y}} (by [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Islamic Republic]])\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Marxism-Leninism]]\n| international = [[International Meeting of Communist and Workers' Parties|IMCWP]]<br>[[International Communist Seminar|ICS]] (defunct)\n| national = [[United Front of Progressive Parties|UFPP]] (1946\u20131948)<ref>{{cite book |last=Abrahamian |first=Ervand |year=1982 |title=Iran Between Two Revolutions |isbn=0-691-10134-5 |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/300 300] |url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/300 }}</ref>\n| newspaper = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Rahbar (newspaper)|Rahbar]]'' (1942\u20131945)\n* ''[[Khavar-e no]]'' (1943\u20131945)\n}}\n| predecessor = [[Communist Party of Persia]]\n| position = [[Left-wing]]<ref>{{citation|author=Touraj Atabaki|title=Azerbaijan: Ethnicity and the Struggle for Power in Iran|page=137|year=2000|publisher=I.B.Tauris}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Berlin, Germany]]<br />[[London, England]]<br>[[Leipzig]], [[East Germany|GDR]] (1949\u20131979)<br>[[Tehran]], [[Iran]] (1943\u20131983)\n| website = {{ConditionalURL}}\n| colorcode = {{Tudeh Party of Iran/meta/color}}\n| anthem = ''Anthem for Tudeh''<br />(composed by [[Parviz Mahmoud]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Meftahi|first=Ida|year=2016|title=Gender and Dance in Modern Iran: Biopolitics on Stage|isbn=9781317620624|publisher=Routledge|page=57}}</ref>\n| youth_wing = [[Tudeh Youth]]\n| womens_wing = [[Democratic Organization of Women]]\n| wing1_title = Military wing\n| wing1 = [[Tudeh Military Network|Officers' Organization]]\n| wing2_title = Parliamentary wing\n| wing2 = [[Tudeh fraction]]\n| wing3_title = Worker wing\n| wing3 = [[Central Council of United Trade Unions]]\n| country = Iran\n}}\nThe '''Tudeh Party of Iran''' ({{lang-fa-at|\u062d\u0632\u0628 \u062a\u0648\u062f\u06c0 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646|\u1e24ezb-e T\u016bde-ye \u012ar\u0101n|lit=Party of the Masses of Iran}}) is an [[Iran]]ian [[communist party]]. Formed in 1941, with Soleiman Mohsen Eskandari as its head, it had considerable influence in its early years and played an important role during [[Mohammad Mosaddegh]]'s campaign to nationalize the [[Anglo-Persian Oil Company]] and his term as prime minister.<ref>Tudeh News, [https://web.archive.org/web/20121019002919/http://tudehpartyiran.org/TN%20247-oct-2007.pdf Statement of the Central Committee of the Tudeh Party of Iran], 2007.</ref> The crackdown that followed the 1953 coup against Mosaddegh is said to have \"destroyed\" the party,<ref name=\"Abrahamian, Ervand p.122\">Abrahamian, Ervand, ''A History of Modern Iran'', p.122</ref><ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'', (1999), p.92</ref> although a remnant persisted. The party still exists, but has remained much weaker as a result of its banning in Iran and mass arrests by the [[Iranian Revolution|Islamic Republic]] in 1982, as well as the [[1988 executions of Iranian political prisoners|executions of political prisoners in 1988]].\n\nTudeh identified itself as the historical offshoot of the [[Communist Party of Persia]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vahabzadeh|first1=Peyman|title=Guerrilla Odyssey: Modernization, Secularism, Democracy, and the Fadai Period of National Liberation In Iran, 1971\u20131979|date=2010|publisher=Syracuse University Press|page=182|isbn=9780815651475}}</ref>\n==Definition==\nThe party has generally been described as \"communist\" by historians (for example: \"The Tudeh Party was a classical pro-[[Soviet Union]] communist party, but wrapped itself at the time in [[nationalism]] to be more attractive to Iranians\"<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/tehranbureau/2011/06/the-nationalist-religious-movement-part-1-patriots-and-mosaddeghists.html#ixzz1Qn0vJaLs The Nationalist-Religious Movement | Part 1: Patriots and Mosaddeghists] by MUHAMMAD SAHIMI Tehran Bureau in Los Angeles| 28 Jun 2011</ref>), but is sometimes described simply as \"leftist\" or even \"left-leaning\" by more sympathetic sources.<ref>''US Foreign Policy in Perspective: Clients, enemies and empire'' by David Sylvan and Stephen Majeski, Routledge, 2009, p.85</ref> Various academic sources have described the party as \"[[Stalinism|Stalinist]]\".<ref>\n* {{cite book |author=Stephanie Cronin |title=Reformers and Revolutionaries in Modern Iran: New Perspectives on the Iranian Left |publisher=Routledge |series=Routledge/BIPS Persian Studies Series |year=2013 |isbn=1134328907 |pages=42\u201343}}\n* {{cite book |authors=Samih K. Farsoun, Mehrdad Mashayekhi |title=Iran: Political Culture in the Islamic Republic |year=2005 |publisher=Routledge |page=68 |quote=Thus the Tudeh Party introduced the Stalinist version of Marxism into Iran. As was discussed before, in the late 1950s the Third Worldist ideology and its socialist variant appeared in Iran, basically through the impact of the Chinese, Cuban and Vietnamese Revolutions}}\n* {{cite book |author=Tadd Fern\u00e9e |year=2014 |title=Enlightenment and Violence: Modernity and Nation-Making |publisher=SAGE |page=318 |quote=Yet, when the Soviet Union demanded its oil concession the following year the Tudeh Party extended full support on ideological grounds. The Tudeh Party evolved towards a Stalinist pro-Moscow Party, ultimately losing much public support. International political pressures transformed the Tudeh Party into the local evangelical force of the Stalinist faith by 1949.}}\n* {{cite book |author=Sepehr Zabir |year=2012 |title=The Left in Contemporary Iran (RLE Iran D) |publisher=Taylor & Francis |page=198 |quote=At the end of 1984 the party returned to a rigid Stalinist interpretation of post-Second World War developments in Soviet-Iranian relations...}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Communist Parties|expanded=Asia}}\n\n===Birth of the communist movement in Iran===\nThe history of the [[communist]] movement in Iran dates back to the late 19th century, when [[Marxism]] first became introduced to the nation's intellectual and working classes as a result of the rapid growth of industry and the subsequent transformation of the country's economy from a [[feudalistic]] system into a [[capitalistic]] one. Being close to the Soviet Union and the [[Caucasus]], northern Iran became the primary center of underground Marxist and [[social democrat]] political activity, and many such groups came into being over the years.\n\nThe [[Communist Party of Iran (1920)|Communist Party of Iran]] was founded in June 1920 in [[Bandar-e Anzali]], in the province of [[Gilan]], as a result of the first congress of Iranian social democrats. [[Haydar Khan e Amo-oghli|Heidar Amou Oghly]], who was one of the leaders of the [[Constitutional Revolution of Iran]], became the secretary-general of the new party. At the same time, [[Mirza Koochak Khan|Mirza Koochak Khan Jangali]], another major leader of the Constitutional Revolution and also leader of the revolutionary [[Jungle Movement of Gilan|Jangali]] (Foresters Movement), established the [[Soviet Republic of Gilan]] with the assistance of the [[Red Army]] of the Soviet Union.<ref>H. RamHormozi, ''Averting An Iranian Geopolitical Crisis: A Tale of Power Play for Dominance Between Colonial Powers, Tribal and Government Actors in the Pre and Post World War One Era'' (Victoria, BC, Canada: Friesen Press, 2016), 274.</ref><ref>Arutiun Airapetian and Marcelo Gryckiewicz, ''Transcaucasian Banknotes'' (BoD \u2013 Books on Demand, 2009), 190.</ref><ref>The [[United Kingdom|British]], who were a dominant influence in the [[Qajar dynasty|Qajar]] court of [[Tehran]], reportedly sent agents to infiltrate the Foresters Movement in a carefully prepared plot.</ref>\n\nWith the defeat of both the newly formed Soviet Republic of Gilan and the Communist Party, Communist and social democrat activity once again went underground. In the early 1920s the Qajar dynasty finally collapsed, and [[Reza Shah]] ascended to the throne in 1925, establishing the [[Pahlavi dynasty]]. The new Shah introduced many reforms, such as limiting the power of the [[Shi'a]] clergy, but also in turn established an [[authoritarian]] dictatorship.\n\nIn 1929\u201330, the party organized strikes in an [[Isfahan]] textile mill, the [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]] railways, [[Mashhad]] carpet workshops, and most importantly, in the British-owned oil industry. The government cracked down heavily and some 200 communists were arrested; 38 were incarcerated in [[Qasr Prison]] in Tehran. \"Seven died there - all from natural causes.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2010}} Along with the [[Purge of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Stalin purges]], which took a heavy toll from Iranian communist exiles living in the Soviet Union, these arrests meant the Communist Party of Iran \"ceased to exist for all practical purposes outside the walls of Qasr.\"<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Tortured Confessions: Prisons and Public Recantations in Modern Iran'' by Ervand Abrahamian, (University of California Press, 1999) p. 28\u201329</ref>\n\n===Foundation of the Tudeh Party===\nThe British-Soviet [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[Persian Corridor|invasion]] of 1941\u201342 resulted in the end of Reza Shah's reign and his forced exile to [[South Africa]]. Many political prisoners were subsequently released and under this new atmosphere, [[nationalist]] and [[socialist]] groups once again flourished. [[Iraj Iskandari]] and his closest colleagues decided to form a [[Marxist\u2013Leninist]] party appealing to the broad masses.<ref>Abrahamian, ''History of Modern Iran'' (2008) p. 107</ref> They founded the Tudeh party on 29 September 1941, electing [[Soleiman Mohsen Eskandari]] as chairman.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3312-2016-10-04-06-51-45&usg=ALkJrhihJ3cxamgvL1C8NuCMT9sGqG7fCA DOCUMENT CENTRAL COMMITTEE OF THE TUDEH PARTY OF IRAN ON THE OCCASION OF 75TH ANNIVERSARY OF THE TUDEH PARTY OF IRAN], 2016</ref>\n\nInitially the party was intended to be \"a [[Liberalism|liberal]] rather than a radical party\", with a platform stressing the importance of \"constitutional\" and \"individual rights\", protecting \"democracy\" and \"judicial integrity\" from [[fascism]], [[imperialism]] and [[militarism]]. \"At Soleiman Eskandari's urging\", the party initially attempted to appeal to non-secular masses by barring women from membership, organizing [[Day of Ashura|Moharram processions]], and designating \"a special prayer room in its main clubhouse.\" This orientation did not last and the party moved \"rapidly to the left\" within months of its founding.<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'' (1999), pp. 77\u201378</ref>\n\n===Early peak===\n{{see also|Coalition government of Ahmad Qavam}}\nIn 1944, the party entered the 14th [[Majlis of Iran|Majlis]] elections and eight of its candidates were elected. It also established the secret [[Tudeh Party Military Organization of Iran]], or TPMO (''Sazman-e Nezami-ye Hezb-e Tudeh-ye Iran'') made up of officers in the military. The TPMO provided the party with intelligence and information from the military to protect it from the security forces and give it military strength, though historians believe the party had no plan at that time to use the TPMO to stage a coup.<ref name=\"Behrooz103\" />\n\nAt the same time, Tudeh took a strong stand in favor of women's rights, starting in 1943. This included advocating for equal pay for equal work, two months of maternity leave for female workers and otherwise standing for women's social rights, working with those who had been fighting for these goals for years and were [[socialist]].<ref>Women and Islam: Women's movements in Muslim societies, ed. Haideh Moghissi, p. 92-94.</ref>\nEven so, issues of [[reproduction]], [[sexuality]], and other elements within family life were not discussed.\n\nFrom this point on the party grew immensely and became a major force in Iranian politics. By early 1945, the party had managed to create the first mass organization in Iran's history. Police records later revealed it had an estimated 2,200 hard-core members \u2013 700 of them in [[Tehran]] \u2013 \"10,000s of sympathizers in its youth and women's organizations, and 100,000s of sympathizers in its labor and craft unions.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999) p. 81</ref> Its main newspaper, ''[[Rahbar (newspaper)|Rahbar]]'' (Leader), boasted a circulation of more than 100,000 \u2013 triple that of the \"semi-official newspaper\" ''[[Ettela'at]].'' British ambassador [[Reader Bullard]] called it the only coherent political force in the country, and the ''[[New York Times]]'' reckoned it and its allies could win as much as 40% of the vote in a fair election.<ref>''Ettela'at'', 24 September 1979, quoted in Abrahamian, ''History of Modern Iran'' (2008) pp. 108\u201309</ref>\n\nThis period has been called the height of the party's intellectual influence which came in large part from the prestige and propaganda of the [[Soviet Union]] as \"the world's most progressive nation.\" Few intellectuals \"dared oppose\" the party \"even if they did not join.\" Marking the end of the \"near hegemony of the party over intellectual life\" in Iran was the resignation from the party of celebrated writer [[Jalal Al-e-Ahmad]] circa 1948 to form a [[socialist]] splinter group \u2013[[Third Force (Iran)|Third Force]]\u2013 in protest against the Tudeh's \"nakedly pro-Soviet\" policies.<ref>Mottahedeh, Roy, ''The Mantle of the Prophet: Religion and Politics in Iran'', One World, Oxford, 1985, 2000, p. 290</ref>\n\nTarnishing the appeal of the Tudeh in the next two years 1944\u201346 were Soviet demands for a [[petroleum]] concession in northern Iran and the Soviet sponsoring of ethnic revolts in [[Iranian Kurdistan|Kurdestan]] and [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]]. Despite the fact that Tudeh deputies in the [[Majles of Iran#Pre-Revolution Majlis \u2013 National Consultative Assembly|Majles]] had previously vigorously demanded the [[nationalization]] of the whole petroleum industry, the Tudeh party supported granting the Soviet petroleum industry in Iran its wishes on grounds of \"socialist solidarity\", \"internationalism,\" and \"anti-imperialism.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'' (1999) p. 82</ref>\n\n====International Cold War context====\nDuring this time the rest of the international communist movement was also thriving. The communist world expanded dramatically in the decade following [[World War II]] with [[Eastern Bloc|Eastern Europe]], [[Chinese Civil War|China]], [[Division of Korea|North Korea]], and [[First Indochina War|Vietnam]] all becoming states dominated by their respective communist parties, usually via military victory. In the United States, Iran was seen as the holder of reserves of petroleum with \"vital strategic\" value to western countries,<ref>Byrne, p. 213</ref> and as part of \"a Northern Tier\" of countries (along with Greece and Turkey) that constituted a geopolitical \"first line of defense\" for the [[Mediterranean]] and for [[Asia]],<ref>Byrne, p. 214</ref>  To counter the activities of the USSR, the CIA established [[Operation TPBEDAMN]] in the late 1940s, funded at $1 million a year. It prepared both \"disguised (`gray` propaganda) or deliberately misrepresented [[black propaganda]]\" in the form of \"newspaper articles, cartoons, leaflets, and books\" which it translated into Persian, most of which \"portrayed the Soviet Union and the Tudeh as anti-Iranian or anti-Islamic, described the harsh reality of life in the Soviet Union, or explained the Tudeh's close relationship with the Soviets and its popular-front strategy.\"<ref>Gasiorowski writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark J. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, [[Syracuse University Press]], 2004, p. 243</ref> In addition it paid \"right-wing nationalist organizations\" and some [[Shia]] religious figures. Its agents provoked \"violent acts\" and blamed them on the communists, and hired \"thugs to break up Tudeh rallies.\"<ref>Byrne writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.217</ref> Nonetheless the party was able to fill the streets of Tehran and Abadan \"with tens of thousands of enthusiastic demonstrators\" for [[International Workers' Day|May Day]] in 1946.<ref>Kinzer, ''All the Shah's Men'', 2003, p. 65</ref>\n\n===1949 crackdown===\nIn February 1949 there was an attempt on the life of Shah [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]].  The party was blamed by the government and banned. The government \"confiscated its assets, dissolved affiliated organizations, especially the Central Council and rounded up some 200 leaders and cadres.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999) p.84</ref>\n\nThe party continued to function underground however and by 1950 it had organized its supporters under the banner of the Iran Society for Peace (''Jam'iyat-e Irani-ye Havadar-e Solh'') and was publishing three daily papers, ''Razm'', ''Mardom'', and ''Besui-ye Ayandeh.''<ref name=\"Behrooz103\">Behrooz writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.103</ref> In December 1950, the TPMO, its military organization, managed \"to arrange for escape of key members of the party leadership who had been in jail since early 1949.\"<ref name=\"Behrooz103\"/>\n\nSuch suppression was assisted by conservatives detesting the Tudeh Party, which was later outlawed and allied with Mossadegh.<ref name=\"Michele Penner Angris 2011\">Michele Penner Angris, Party Building in the Modern Middle East (US: University of Washington Press, 2011),\n131.</ref> One Iranian conservative newspaper even editorialized:\n\n<blockquote> the Tudeh Party, with its santonic doctrine of class struggles, has incited ignorant workers to violate the sacred right of private property and inflict social anarchy upon the center of the country. This uprising proves that Tudeh is an enemy of private property, of Iran, and of Islam. If the government does not stamp out Tudeh, the local revolt will inevitably spread into a general revolution.</blockquote>\n\n===Mosaddeq era, his overthrow and aftermath===\n\nThe party played an important role both directly and indirectly during the pivotal era of Iranian history that began with the 1951 [[nationalization]] of the British [[Anglo Iranian Oil Company]] (AIOC), and ending with the 1953 overthrow of [[Mohammad Mosaddeq]] by a [[CIA]]-led [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]].  The party's policy \"fluctuated,\" first attacking Mosaddeq as `an agent of American imperialism,` then giving him some support during and after the July 1952 uprising.  On August 15 a coup attempt against Mosaddeq was thwarted thanks in part to information uncovered by the Tudeh TPMO military network, but two days later party militants inadvertently helped destabilized the government by staging demonstrations to pressure Mosaddeq to declare Iran a democratic republic. As this would have overturned Iran's constitutional monarchy, Mosaddeq reacted by calling out troops to suppress the demonstrators. The party then demobilized late the next day making it unavailable to fight the coup the day after.<ref name=\"Behrooz121\">Behrooz writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.121</ref>  By 1957 the TPMO was crushed and thousands of party members had been arrested.<ref name=assassination>Doug Noble, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2012/07/19/assassination-nation/ Assassination Nation], [[CounterPunch]], 2012.</ref>\n\n====Oil nationalization====\n[[File:Tudeh leaders Soviet party Congress.jpg|thumb|300px|Senior members of Tudeh in 1955 (left to right): [[Reza Rousta|Rousta]], [[Fereydoun Keshavarz|Keshavarz]], [[Reza Radmanesh|Radmanesh]], [[Iraj Eskandari|Eskandari]] and [[Abdolsamad Kambakhsh|Kambakhsh]]]]\nFollowing World War II, Iranian public support was growing for nationalization of the British Anglo Iranian Oil Company (AIOC)<ref>Saikal, Amin, ''The Rise and Fall of the Shah'', (Princeton University Press, 1980), p.42. Note: AIOC later became [[British Petroleum]] (BP)</ref> whose profits had greatly exceeded its royalty payments to the Iranian government.\n\nIn 1951, [[Mohammad Mosaddeq]], head of the [[nationalist]] movement known as the [[National Front of Iran]], led parliament in the nationalization of AIOC, and shortly after was appointed [[prime minister]] by the Shah. Mosaddeq oversaw the takeover of British oil facilities and rising economic difficulty and polarization in Iran as the AIOC withdrew its employees and retaliated with a boycott of Iranian oil.<ref>Saikal, ''The Rise and Fall of the Shah'', (1980), p.43-4</ref>\n\nIn early April 1951 the Tudeh revealing its \"true strength\" by launched strikes and riots protesting low wages and bad housing in oil industry and delays in nationalization of the oil industry.<ref name=\"Michele Penner Angris 2011\" /> There were \"street demonstrations and sympathy strikes in [[Tehran]], [[Isfahan]], and the northern cities.\" Police opened fire on demonstrators. A result was \"panic\" in Iran's parliament at the power of Marxist forces in Iran.<ref>\"Abrahamian, 1982, p.266\"</ref> With this, it is clear that not only was Mossadegh not a communist but Tudeh did not control the government or want to overthrow him even as was establishing a broad public base.<ref>Ron Jacobs, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2013/02/15/the-coup-of-coups/ The Coup of Coups], [[CounterPunch]], Feb. 15, 2013.</ref><ref>Vijay Prashad, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/01/iran-and-us/ Iran and Us], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', July 1, 2009.</ref>\n\nDuring this period the Tudeh followed a \"leftist\" rather than \"[[Popular front#The Comintern's Popular Front policy 1934\u20131939|popular front]]\" strategy, refusing to ally with Mosaddeq. Despite the fact that Mosaddeq had introduced a new policy of tolerance toward the party,<ref>Azimi writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.72</ref> that both the Tudeh and Mosaddeq had worked for nationalization of the AIOC,<ref>Hussein Fateh, \"the anticommunist leader of the defunct Comrade's party\": Panjah ''Saleh-e Naft-i Iran'' Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' (1982), p.320</ref> and that expropriation of [[capitalist]] Western-owned resource extracting corporations by [[developing countries|poor countries]] was central to [[Marxism-Leninism|Marxist-Leninist]] doctrine, the party vigorously and relentlessly opposed Mosaddeq and his program.  In a June 1950 article in its daily ''Mardom'' it described the effects of Mosaddeq's policy thusly:\n\n<blockquote>Already we can be sure that revisions in the southern oil contract will not be in favor of our people and will only result in the consolidation of England's position in our country. ... The solution of the oil question is related to the victory of our party, that is, the people of Iran.<ref name=\"Behrooz108\">Behrooz writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p.108</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn July 16, 1952, Mosaddeq resigned after the shah refused to accept his nomination for War Minister. Mosaddeq appealed to the general public for support, but Tudeh press continued to attack him, describing his differences with the shah \"as merely one between different factions of a reactionary ruling elite.\"<ref name=\"Behrooz, p.109\">Behrooz, p.109</ref> It was only after the explosion of popular support for Mosaddeq in the street that \"many rank-and-file\" Tudeh party members \"could see first hand Mosaddeq's popularity\",<ref name=\"Behrooz, p.109\" /> and came to his aid.\n\nAccording to one observer:\n<blockquote>although diverse elements participated in the July uprising, the impartial observer must confess that the Tudeh played an important part\u2014perhaps even the most important part. ... If in the rallies before March 1952 one-third of the demonstrators had been Tudeh and two-thirds had been National Front, after March 1952, the proportions were reversed.<ref>Comment of Hussein Fateh, \"the anticommunist leader of the defunct Comrade's party\": Panjah ''Saleh-e Naft-i Iran'' Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' (1982), p.320</ref></blockquote>\n\nAyatollah [[Abol-Ghasem Kashani]], who later switched sides and supported the Shah, \"sent a public letter to the pro-Tudeh organizations thanking them for their invaluable contribution\" during the uprising toward Mosaddeq's victory.<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' (1982), p.320</ref>\n\nMosaddeq capitalized on the uprising to establish emergency rule, which allowed him to bypass the Majles, and also to institute socialist reforms.<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' by Ervand Abrahamian, (Princeton University Press, 1982), p.323</ref> With the Soviets not wanting to back or \"shore up\" Tudeh, and Truman refusing demands to overthrow Mossadegh from [[Clement Attlee]] and [[Winston Churchill]], it would take the inauguration of Dwight Eisenhower to change the tune, greenlighting the coup operation.<ref>Wahid Azal, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/08/29/the-banality-of-evil-and-the-ivory-tower-masterminds-of-the-1953-coup-detat-in-iran/ The Banality of Evil and the Ivory Tower Masterminds of the 1953 Coup d\u2019Etat in Iran], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', Aug. 29, 2016.</ref><ref>Gary Leupp, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2005/07/06/accusing-ahmadinejad/ Accusing Ahmadinejad], July 6, 2005.</ref>\n\n====1953 coup====\nDuring this time the US government became more and more frustrated with Mosaddeq and the stalemate over negotiations with the UK government on control and compensation, with the American ambassador even questioning Mosaddeq's \"mental stability\".<ref>Byrne, writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, p. 222</ref> At the same time the [[cold war]] struggle continued to dominate foreign policy thinking in the west.  Soviet tanks crushed an anti-communist [[Uprising of 1953 in East Germany|uprising of strikes and protests in East Germany]] in June 1953.<ref>\"Books And Arts: How to change a regime in 30 days; Iran\", ''The Economist''. London: Aug 16, 2003. Vol. 368, Iss. 8337; pg. 74</ref><ref>Kinzer, Stephen, ''All the Shah's Men : An American Coup and the Roots of Middle East Terror'', John Wiley and Sons, 2003, p. 84</ref>\n\nAs Americans gave up hope on Mosaddeq, their propaganda and covert action campaign against the Tudeh, called TPBEDAMN, expanded to include him.<ref>Mark J. Gasiorowski,[http://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1162/JCWS_a_00393 The CIA's TPBEDAMN: Operation and the 1953 Coup in Iran], Journal of Cold War Studies, Vol. 15: Issue. 4: Pages. 4-24. Issue publication date: October 2013.</ref> In 1953, American CIA and British intelligence agents, began plotting to overthrow Mosaddeq in a [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]], in large part because of their fear that \"rising internal tensions and continued deterioration ... might lead to a breakdown of government authority and open the way for at least a gradual assumption of control by Tudeh,\" just as a local communist party had led a [[Czechoslovak coup d'\u00e9tat of 1948|coup in Czechoslovakia]] in 1948, replacing a democratic regime and constitution with a pro-Soviet, one-party Communist government.<ref>Gasiorowski writing in ''Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran'', Edited by Mark j. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, Syracuse University Press, 2004, pp. 230\u201331</ref>\n\nThe Tudeh also sensed a coup might be coming, and created \"vanguard cells\" that along with the TPMO, \"identified key military installation, army depots, and command and control centers in the capital\" Tehran \"to react violently to any coup attempt.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 116</ref> Recently released photographs by [[William Arthur Cram]] show that Tudeh organized huge demonstrations in August before the coup occurred.<ref>Saeed Kamali Dehghan, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/iran-blog/gallery/2015/dec/16/unseen-images-of-the-1953-iran-coup-in-pictures Unseen images of 1953 Iran Coup - in pictures], ''The Guardian'', Dec. 16, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe plotters first attempt involved persuading the shah to issue an edict dismissing Mosaddeq and replacing him with retired General [[Fazlollah Zahedi]], while arresting Mosaddeq and taking over other possible centers of opposition. On August 15 the plot was uncovered by Tudeh supporters in the military, and a contingent sent to arrest Mosaddeq were intercepted and arrested themselves. Colonel Mohammad Ali Mobasherri, was a member of the TPMO's (secret) three-man secretariat, but also an active member of Tehran Military Governor, the center of the coup operation. Major Hehdi Homaouni served in the shah's Imperial Guard and discovered and reported the August plot to the party.<ref>Behrooz, p. 117</ref> In a recent set of documents released by the [[National Security Archive]], which noted pro-Shah demonstrators sacked pro-Tudeh and pro-Mossadegh establishments, it was noted that British and American intelligence agents infiltrated Tudeh so it could blunt Mossadegh. These documents also noted that Eisenhower and Truman differed in their assessments of Mossadegh, with Eisenhower feeling he could not as effectively counter Tudeh as Truman and the CIA in August 1953 downplaying \"the likelihood of a Tudeh overthrow attempt\" but fears the Tudeh taking power in a more long-term fashion.<ref>[http://nsarchive.gwu.edu/NSAEBB/NSAEBB126/ Mohammad Mosaddeq and the 1953 Coup in Iran], ed. by Mark J. Gasiorowski and Malcolm Byrne, [[National Security Archive]], 2004.</ref>\n\nThe coup attempt created a backlash against its perpetrators, including the shah. The already anti-monarchical Tudeh supporters were radicalized and on the morning of August 17 \"an angry crowd began to attack symbols of the monarchy\" and demanded its abolition.  Mosaddeq, who was aware of Western fears of the Tudeh and who had worked to limit the power of the shah but had \"never suggested he was in favor of abolishing the constitutional monarchy,\" saw these attacks as a challenge, as removing the shah would violate the constitution.<ref>Behrooz, p. 119, 120</ref> The next day his regime ordering the military into the streets, and \"up to 600 mid and low-level Tudeh activists were arrested in Tehran alone.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 120</ref> With its network \"severely damaging\" the party reversed course once again, and \"ordered a demobilization\" of its preparations to fight a coup.<ref>Behrooz, p. 121</ref><ref>Rostam Pourzal, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2008/08/21/the-left-and-iran/ The Left and Iran], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', Aug. 21, 2008.</ref>\n\nTaking advantage of the quiet, the CIA and its Iranian allies struck again, and on August 19 the [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] replaced Mosaddeq with Zahedi. The coup was a major event in Third World and 20th Century history and there is debate as to how much of the blame for the overthrow can be traced to bribes paid by the CIA and how much to domestic dissatisfaction with Mossadeq.<ref>Nasr, Vali, ''The Shia Revival'', Norton, (2005), p. 124</ref><ref>Mackay, Sandra, ''The Iranians'', Plume (1997), pp. 203\u201304</ref><ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Iran Between Two Revolutions'' by Ervand Abrahamian, Princeton University Press, 1982, pp. 276\u201377</ref> Whatever the motivations, [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] thereafter assumed dictatorial powers and banned most political groups, including Mossadegh's National Front, which along with the Tudeh Party, continued to function underground.\n\n====Crackdown following coup====\nThe mass arrests, destruction of its organization and execution of some 40\u201350 leaders following the coup has been said to have \"destroyed\" the Tudeh.<ref name=\"Abrahamian, Ervand p.122\" /> Between 1953 and 1957, Iranian security forces using \"brute force, together with the breaking of the cryptographic code \u2013 probably with CIA know-how \u2013 \u2026 tracked down 4,121 party members.\" This constituted the whole Tudeh underground and \"more than half the party membership\". Tudeh infiltration of the military by the TPMO<ref>Office of the Military Governor of Teheran: Black Book on Tudeh Officers Organization. 1956. {{ISBN|978-3-8442-7813-2}}. [http://www.epubli.de/shop/buch/Black-Book-on-Tudeh-Officers-Organization-Teymour-Bakhtiar-9783844278132/33792]</ref> totaled 477 members in the armed forces, \"22 colonels, 69 majors, 100 captains, 193 lieutenants, 19 noncommissioned officers, and 63 military cadets.\" Ervand Abrahamian notes that none of these were in the \"crucial tank divisions around Tehran\" that could have been used for a coup d'\u00e9tat and which the Shah had screened carefully. \"Ironically, a Tudeh colonel had been in charge of the Shah's personal security \u2013 as well as that of Vice President Richard Nixon when he visited Iran. The Tudeh had the opportunity to assassinate the Shah and the U.S. vice president but not to launch a coup.\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p. 92</ref> [[Maziar Behrooz]] is more optimistic about the party's chances of stopping the coup, saying that while \"most of the Tudeh officers were in non-combat posts,\" they \"were in a position to access and distribute weapons. In their memoirs, TPMO high- and middle-ranking members have confirmed their ability to distribute weapons and even to assassinate key Iranian leaders of the coup. Hence, with a disciplined party membership, backed by military officers with access to weapons, the Tudeh had a strong hand.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 106</ref>\n\nWith the TPMO decimated, the Tudeh network was compromised as the TPMO had \"acted as a shield for the party\" and helped preserve it immediately after Mosaddeq's overthrow. \"Many high- and middle-ranking Tudeh leaders were arrested or forced to flee the country. The arrest and execution of [[Khosro Roozbeh]] in 1957-8 signaled the end of this process.\"<ref>Behrooz, p. 124</ref>\n\n====Tudeh verdict====\nAfter the fact, the party engaged in self-criticism of its policies toward Mosaddeq at its Fourth Plenum held in Moscow in July 1957. They found them \"sectarian and leftist\" and not to recognizing \"the progressive nature\" of the oil nationalization movement.{{clarify|date=January 2013}}<ref>Behrooz, p. 123</ref>\n\n===Late 1950s and 1960s===\nThe [[Sino\u2013Soviet split]] caused some splintering of the party in the early 1960s, with at least one Maoist group breaking away.<ref>*\"In the early 1960s, moreover the Tudeh was further weakened by defections. With the eruption of the Sino-Soviet dispute, three Tudeh leaders left the party and formed a party called the Organization of Marxist-Leninists. At the same time, some members of the party's youth section left and formed the Revolutionary Organization of the Tudeh Party.\" [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3012310?seq=3 Iran in Revolution: The Opposition Forces], Ervand Abrahamian</ref> In the mid 1960s, the [[U.S. State Department]] estimated the party membership to be approximately 1500.<ref>Benjamin, Roger W.; Kautsky, John H.. ''[https://www.jstor.org/stable/1953329 Communism and Economic Development]'', in The [[American Political Science Review]], Vol. 62, No. 1. (Mar., 1968), pp. 122.</ref>\n\nIn 1965, the party faced a second division between the mainstream of the organization and the splinter faction, which advocated violent struggle against the government by arming the tribes of southern Iran. This faction caused a great deal of damage and three years passed before the unity of the party was restored. The remnants of this faction are known as the [[Labour Party of Iran]].\n\nIn 1966, several party members, including [[Ali Khavari]] and [[Parviz Hekmatjoo]] of the Central Committee, and [[Asef Razmdideh]] and [[Saber Mohammadzadeh]], were arrested and sentenced to death. This sparked international outcry and hunger strikes in Europe which forced the government to reduce the sentences to life imprisonment. These events created much international sympathy for the worker's struggle in Iran and helped unify the party after the split. The Tudeh Party from this point on becomes established as one of the strongest underground movements and helps to pave the way for the forthcoming [[Iranian Revolution]] of 1979.\n\n===Iranian Revolution of 1979===\nIn the early 1970s, the Iranian [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla]] movement began in northern Iran in the province of [[Mazandaran]]. The 1970s also witnessed the birth of widespread worker's strikes and demonstrations, and university campuses became a hotbed of revolutionary activity. In 1973, Tudeh released a brochure titled \"Oil from Iran and imperialist oil monopolies,\" likely advocating for oil nationalization.<ref>Brochure of the Iranian Tudeh Party, \"[http://www.iisg.nl/collections/crises/bro5647-4.php Oil from Iran and imperialist oil monopolies],\" Safari, Hamid: Impiryalism-i naftkhar. Strassfurt, Tudeh Publishing Centre [1973]. Call number: Bro 5647/4.</ref> The Tudeh Party drastically increased its activities, recruiting many youth and organizing regional committees, supporting the [[Islamic Revolution]] when others on the [[Left-wing politics|left]] opposed it.<ref name=Tripathi>Deepak Tripathi, \"[http://www.counterpunch.org/2011/12/13/iran-the-islamic-revolution-and-the-language-of-war/ Iran, the Islamic Revolution and the Language of War],\" ''[[CounterPunch]]'', Dec. 13, 2011.</ref><ref>Gary Leupp, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2003/09/05/shiites-humiliate-bush/ Shiites Humiliate Bush], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', Sept. 5, 2003.</ref><ref>Ron Jacobs, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2004/12/28/the-resistance-and-the-west-s-anti-war-movement/ The Resistance and the West\u2019s Anti-War Movement], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', Dec. 28, 2004.</ref>\n\n===Islamic Republic===\nDuring the revolution, many political prisoners were freed and the Tudeh Party and other leftist groups were able to participate in the presidential and parliamentary elections for the first time in many years. However, the majority of seats in the Majlis were won by the [[Islamic Republican Party]] of [[Mohammad Beheshti|Ayatollah Beheshti]] and leftist and nationalist organizations were forced out of the loop. The newly elected President, [[Abolhassan Banisadr]], who had originally been close with [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], also became increasingly frustrated with the developments that had been taking place and opposed the domination of the clergy and the religious factions in Iranian politics. In addition, the party denounced Amnesty International's call to end the summary executions and called it \"blatant interference in Iranian affairs\".<ref name=mmm>{{cite journal|last=Milani|first=Mohsen M.|title=Harvest of Shame: Tudeh and the Bazargan Government|journal=Middle Eastern Studies|date=April 1993|volume=29|issue=2|pages=307\u2013320|jstor=4283563|doi=10.1080/00263209308700950}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the Majlis, dominated by the Islamic Republican Party, forced Bani Sadr out of office, which initiated a wave of protests and demonstrations from all segments of the populace. Bani Sadr later fled the country. Armed revolutionary committees loyal to Khomeini (which came to be known as the ''[[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps|Pasdaran]]'') arrested many thousands of youth and activists from both nationalist and leftist groups, many of whom were later tried by [[Lajevardi]], who was known as the ''Hanging Judge'', and executed.\n\nAt this point in the history of the Tudeh Party, the [[Christians|Christian]] and [[Azeris]] within the population were prominent.<ref>Michele Penner Angris, ''Party Building in the Modern Middle East'' (US: University of Washington Press, 2011), 71.</ref>\n\n====Suppression====\nWhile other leftist parties opposed the Islamist forces at this time, and were suppressed as a result, Tudeh Party leadership as well as the [[Organization of Iranian People's Fedaian (Majority)|Fadaian Aksariat]] decided to oppose politically with the new clerical theocratic regime and support the crackdown on the militant armed opposition. This may have been to try to take advantage of the lack of competition from the many now suppressed rival leftist groups, or to follow the pro-Tehran line of the Soviet Union.{{citation needed|date=April 2008}}\n\nIn 1982, however, the Tudeh broke ranks. The Islamist government of Iran had closed down the Tudeh newspaper, and purged Tudeh members from government ministries. According to the [[Mitrokhin Archive]], [[Vladimir Kuzichkin]], a [[KGB]] officer stationed in Tehran, had defected to the British in 1982. [[MI6]] used this information and shared the information with the [[CIA]]. Their information was then shared with the Iranian government by the CIA, which was secretly courting Iran, as part of the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair]].<ref>{{cite book|authorlink1=John Tower|last1=Tower|first1=John|authorlink2=Edmund Muskie|last2=Muskie|first2=Edmund|authorlink3=Brent Scowcroft|last3=Scowcroft|first3=Brent|title=[[Tower Commission|Report of the President's Special Review Board]]|publisher=[[Bantam Books]]|year=1987|p=[https://archive.org/details/towercommission00unit/page/104 104]|isbn=9780553269680|quote=In 1983, the U.S. helped bring to the attention of Tehran the threat inherent in the extensive infiltration of the government by the communist Tudeh Party and Soviet or pro-Soviet cadres in the country. Using this information, the Khomeini government took measures, including mass executions, that virtually eliminated the pro-Soviet infrastructure in Iran.}} Available online [https://archive.org/stream/TowerCommission/President%27s%20Special%20Review%20Board%20%28%22Tower%20Commission%22%29#page/n67/mode/2up here.]</ref><ref name=assassination />\n\nQuite quickly the government arrested and imprisoned its leadership and later more than 10,000 members of the party. During February 1983, the leaders of the Tudeh Party were arrested and the Party disbanded, leaving Iran effectively a one-party state.<ref>Momen, Moojan, ''An Introduction to Shi'i Islam'', Yale University Press, 1985, p. 297</ref> The Tudeh arrests revealed that once again the party had managed to find supporters among the armed forces, as a number of officers, prominent among them [[Admiral]] [[Bahram Afzali]], commander of the [[Islamic Republic of Iran Navy|Iranian navy]], were arrested.<ref name=\"p.129\">Maziar Behrooz, ''Rebels with a Cause'', (2000), [https://books.google.com/books?id=ouuRaF5Ug1IC&printsec=frontcover#PPA129,M1 p. 129]</ref> These arrests ended the alliance between the Tudeh Party and the ruling clergy of Iran and it collapsed, even as the Soviets worked with the Iranians to build up their nuclear capabilities.<ref name=Tripathi /><ref>Ron Jacobs, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2015/08/05/talking-points-on-the-iran-nuke-deal/ Talking points on the Iran nuke deal], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', Aug. 5, 2015.</ref> Even with this agreement, the Iranian government saw the Soviets as \"atheistic devils\" and the Soviets did not like the government because it had suppressed the Tudeh.\n\nInternational media, such as [[United Press International|UPI]], reported that along with the banning of the Tudeh party, 18 Soviet diplomats were expelled from the country for \"blatant interference.\"<ref>Peyman Pezhman, \"[http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/05/04/Iran-Wednesday-outlawed-the-communist-Tudeh-Party-for-plotting/5014420868800/ Iran outlawed the communist Tudeh party for plotting],\" [[UPI]], May 4, 1983.</ref> At the same time, Tudeh was accused of working on behalf of \"foreign powers,\" with the suppression praised by Khomeini.\n\nFrom 1 May 1983 to May 1984 almost all the Tudeh leadership appeared in videos, first individually and then jointly in an October 1983 \"roundtable discussion,\" confessing to \"treason\", \"subversion\", \"horrendous crimes\", praising Islam and proclaiming Islamic government's superiority over atheistic Marxism\u2013Leninism.<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p. 177</ref> British officials supported Iran's crackdown and joked about the state torture techniques used to extract the confessions. British officials were pleased by the repression not primarily because they were concerned about Soviet influence in the country, since they knew that Iran was quite independent of that, but because they wanted to curry favor with the Iranian regime.<ref>The Daily Maverick, 21 Jan. 2020, [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-21-how-britain-helped-irans-islamic-regime-destroy-the-left-wing-opposition/ \"How Britain Helped Iran\u2019s Islamic Regime Destroy the Left-Wing Opposition\"]</ref>\n\nIn May 1984 [[Ehsan Tabari]], appeared on television. A man with \"50 years of leftist experiences\" told viewers he had read \"great Islamic thinkers\" such as [[Morteza Motahhari|Ayatollah Motahhari]] in prison following the 1982 crackdown and had now come\n<blockquote>to repudiate the works he had written over the past 40 years. He now realized that his entire life's work was 'defective', 'damaging', and 'totally spurious' because it had all been based on unreliable thinkers \u2013 [[Freemasonry|Freemasons]] nourished by the [[Pahlavi dynasty|Pahlavis]]; [[Secularism|secularists]] such as [[Ahmad Kasravi]]; Western [[Liberalism|liberals]] and [[Marxist]]s linked to '[[imperialism]]' and '[[Zionism]]' \u2026<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'', (1999), p. 204</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn his recantation Tabari made frequent references to religion, the [[Twelve Imams]] and Islamic thinkers and \"praised Islam for its `great spiritual strength.`\"<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), pp. 204\u201305</ref>\n\nThe suspicions of outside observers that the confession was not given freely were reinforced by the absence of Taqi Keymanash and \"13 other members\" of the Tudeh central committee, who died during prison interrogation.<ref>United Nations (Economic and Social Council) Situation of Human Rights in the Islamic Republic of Iran (New York, November 1990), p.53. quoted in Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p.191</ref> The rapid disintegration of the Tudeh at the hands of the state, and the confessions of its leaders led opposition and remaining party members to seek answers. Explanations ranged from ideological capitulation to the use of [[Stalinism|Stalinist]] methods of trial. The remnant of the party outside the country resorted to strange explanations that special drugs created by the [[CIA]] and [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI-6]] were used. The simplest explanation came several years after the television recantations, from a prison visit by a [[United Nations]]' human rights representative (Galindo Pohl) to Iran. The Tudeh Party General Secretary [[Noureddin Kianouri]] was reported to have told the representative that he and his wife had been tortured to give false confessions. As evidence, he held up his badly set broken arm. Pohl added that Maryam Firuz had difficulty hearing, swallowing food, and sitting down because of beatings suffered eight years earlier at the hands of the Shah's secret police.<ref name=\"p.129\" /><ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions,'' (1999), p.223</ref> Kianouri later wrote an open letter to the Ayatollah detailing his mistreatment.<ref name=\"Afshar\">Haleh Afshar, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/mar/31/iran \"Maryam Firouz\"], Obituary, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 31 March 2008</ref>\n\nAs a result of these purges, a great number of party members left the country into exile. As the party represented the \"Soviet view of a preferred leftist movement\" that holds a pro-Soviet ideological line and responds to Soviet foreign policy in a supportive manner, the [[Soviet Union]] was likely disappointed at the development.<ref>Foundation for Constitutional Government in Iran, \"Soviet presence in Iran: the case of the Tudeh Party\" (1985), p. 2, 3, 7.</ref> It is likely many hundreds Tudeh prisoners were killed during the [[1988 executions of Iranian political prisoners]] when thousands of [[People's Mujahedin of Iran|Mojahedin]] and leftist prisoners were killed.<ref>[http://www.executedtoday.com/2017/02/25/1984-ten-members-of-the-tudeh-party/ 1984: Ten Members of the Tudeh Party], ExecutedToday.com, Feb. 25, 2017.</ref> One report lists 90 Tudeh killed in just some blocks of [[Evin Prison|Evin]] and [[Gohardasht Prison|Gohar Dasht prisons]].\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{{see also|Tudeh fraction}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Election\n!Seats won \n|-\n|1943\n| [[Iranian legislative election, 1943\u20131944|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|9|136|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n|1947 \n| [[1947 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|2|136|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\"|''{{small|Banned in 1949 election}}''\n|-\n|1952 \n| [[1952 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|0|79|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\"|''{{small|Did not contest between 1953 and 1978 due to being banned}}''\n|-\n|1979 \n| [[1979 Iranian Constitutional Convention election|Constitutional Assembly]]\n| {{composition bar compact|0|73|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n|1980 \n| [[1980 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]]\n| {{composition bar compact|0|270|hex=red|per=1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\"|''{{small|Banned since 1983}}''\n|-\n|}\n\n== Estimated membership ==\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|-\n!Year\n!Members\n!Ref\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1942||2,087 {{small|(towards September)}}||<ref>{{citation|title=Did the Soviets play a role in founding the Tudehparty in Iran?|author=Cosroe Chaqueri|url=https://monderusse.revues.org/pdf/22|date=1 April 1999|publisher=\u00c9ditions de l\u2019EHESS|journal=Cahiers du Monde Russe|volume=40|number=3|doi=10.4000/monderusse.22|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n|-\n|6,000||<ref name=\"IBTR\">{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0}}</ref>{{rp|284}}\n|-\n|1944||25,800||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|293}}\n|-\n|1945||69,000||<ref name=\"R\">{{cite book|title=Political Thought and Political History: Studies in Memory of Elie Kedourie|first=Moshe|last=Gammer|date=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135774851|page=144}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1946||50,000 {{small|core members}} + 100,000 {{small|affiliates}}||<ref>{{cite book|title=Social Movements in Egypt and Iran|first=Tara|last=Povey|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781137379009|page=51}}</ref>\n|-\n|80,000||<ref>{{cite journal|title=Iran Finds a Party System: The Institutionalization of \"Iran Novin\"|journal=Middle East Journal|volume=27|number=4|year=Autumn 1973|pages=439\u2013455|publisher=Middle East Institute|author=Marvin G. Weinbaum {{subscription}}|jstor=4325140}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1947||50,000\u2013200,000||<ref name=\"UU\">{{cite thesis|type=BA thesis|title=Leftists as a Political Opposition in Iran|author=Amanda N. Jarvis|url=http://cdmbuntu.lib.utah.edu/utils/getfile/collection/etd3/id/3605/filename/3604.pdf|date=2015|publisher=University of Utah}}</ref>\n|-\n|275,000 {{small|including affiliated labor unions' membership}}||<ref name=\"UU\"/>\n|-\n|1949||25,000||<ref name=\"R\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Social Origins of the Iranian Revolution|first=Misagh|last=Parsa|date=1989|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=9780813514123|page=40}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1952||20,000||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|320}}\n|-\n||50,000 {{small|including sympathizers and affiliated membership}}||<ref>{{cite book|author=Sepehr Zabih|title=The Communist Movement in Iran|year=1966|url=https://archive.org/details/communistmovemen0000zabi|url-access=registration|publisher=University of California Press|page=176}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1953||15,000\u201320,000||<ref>{{cite book|title=The Soviet Union and Revolutionary Iran|first=Aryeh|last=Yodfat|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-61058-2|page=19}}</ref>\n|-\n|25,000 + 300,000 {{small|sympathizers}}||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|321}}\n|-\n|1965||3,000||<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hiro|first1=Dilip|title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals)|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=1135043817|page=202}}</ref>\n|-\n|1967||\u2264 1,000||<ref>{{citation|title=World Strength of the Communist Party Organizations, Issues 19-21, United States. Dept. of State. Intelligence report 4489 R-|publisher=United States. Department of State. Office of Intelligence Research and Analysis, United States. Department of State. Bureau of Intelligence and Research|year=1967|page=111}}</ref>\n|-\n|1977||5,000 ||<ref name=\"IBTR\"/>{{rp|457}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1979||1,500 + 400 {{small|exiled in [[East Germany]]}}||<ref name=\"cia\"/>\n|-\n|7,000 {{small|armed in [[Tehran]]}} ||<ref>{{Citation|last1=Ward|first1=Steven R.|year =2014|title=Immortal, Updated Edition: A Military History of Iran and Its Armed Forces|publisher=Georgetown University Press|page=226|isbn=9781626160651}}</ref>\n|-\n|1980||5,000||<ref name=\"cia\">{{citation|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP81B00401R000500110043-1.pdf|date=1 April 1980|title=Iran: Recent Tudeh Party Activity|id=CIA-RDP81B00401R000500110043-1|type=Intelligence Memorandum|work=Central Intelligence Agency}}</ref>\n|-\n|1983||\u2264 5,000 ||<ref>{{cite book|year=1985|author=United States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign Affairs, Library of Congress. Congressional Research Service|title=The Soviet Union in the third world, 1980-85: an imperial burden on political asset?|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=151}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Current status ==\nDespite repression, the party has managed to survive. Though since the [[Iranian Revolution]] the party is officially banned in Iran and individuals found to be affiliated with communist or [[socialist]] groups risk imprisonment, active members have remained and it continues to operate as an underground political organization there. This was mentioned in an [[Amnesty International]] report on [[political prisoners]] in Iran.<ref>Soheil Asefi, [http://www.counterpunch.org/2013/08/23/betraying-khavaran/ Betraying Khavaran], [[CounterPunch]], Aug. 23, 2013.</ref>\n\nToday, the party leadership is mainly based in exile, as is the new Central Committee, elected in 1992. The party has taken positions against [[privatization]], criticizes the electoral system in the country, and \"anti-labor\" legislation.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3502-1025-25-1-1-1&usg=ALkJrhhUvWP7PYfXElKUyKG9b1wP8WddlQ PRIVATIZATION STILL MADE DISASTER! INCREASE THE IMPACT OF DEREGULATION AND PRIVATIZATION WORK, THE BRINGING JOBS TO WORKERS], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3499-1024-11-2-8&usg=ALkJrhjVZWaE0muNcYSvdjq1hTo5xownXQ TRUE FREEDOM, IN THE FACE OF ELECTORAL SHOWING GUARDIANSHIP GOVERNMENT CAN MAKE A DIFFERENCE!], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-31-04/3491-1024-11-2-1&usg=ALkJrhgOSqZF7l6-G1gw1bW1EhWMm2X5eA Anti-worker bill proposed in Iran], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-31-04/3494-1024-11-2-4&usg=ALkJrhiWgPyrXr65hTcPA_AaCMAJ3dV-0w Anti-labor forces unite in Iran], 2017.</ref> In 2017, the party supported [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] as a leftist force in France, commemorated the [[Russian Revolution]], pledged solidarity with the [[Venezuelan Communist Party]], and criticized [[Iranian reformists]] for betraying their ideals.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-37-25/3498-1024-11-2-7&usg=ALkJrhhEPwKAjFteaXkdDFDmXpbJGxAfHQ FRENCH PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION: THE BRILLIANT SUCCESS OF THE COMMUNIST PARTY CAMPAIGN], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3497-1024-11-2-7&usg=ALkJrhh9FPu0nlGwvZ9NTdddrvuJHZPxpA THE CENTENARY OF THE OCTOBER SOCIALIST REVOLUTION 2017 - 1917: \"ONE STEP FORWARD, TWO STEPS BACK\"], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-37-25/3496-1024-11-2-6&usg=ALkJrhicI81wa_Zd_H827ABk0tOccmgTlA Solidarity with the Venezuelan Communist Party], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3435-1019-2-12-12&usg=ALkJrhhwpMBKKDKRd535U1TwayPwMDQQdA \"RECONCILIATION\" WITH \"REPENT\" POSSIBLE! POLITICAL BANKRUPTCY AND COWARDICE \"REFORMERS\" DEFENDERS OF VELAYAT-E FAQIH REGIME], 2017.</ref> Additionally, the party condemned [[2017 Shayrat missile strike|the missile attacks on Syria]] in April 2017 by [[Donald Trump]], the only element of the Iranian opposition to do so, and has many wide-ranging party anthems on their website.<ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-11-28-19-45-55/3477-1023-28-1-2&usg=ALkJrhgfkyTPBfr_l9i9Q_1310a3LDCedQ Domestic reactions to attack America], 2017.</ref><ref>Tudeh Party, [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=auto&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.tudehpartyiran.org/2013-12-03-22-38-16&usg=ALkJrhj7SQfOJYvYmWTbHS20uokxpSOJBA Party Hymns], 2017.</ref> In 2020, the party condemned the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|Trump Adminstration's airstrike]] which killed [[Qasem Soleimani]], while simultaneously critiquing the Iranian regime for intervening in both Iraq and Lebanon.<ref>{{cite web |title=The urgent need to intensify efforts to preserve peace in the region and confront the adventurous and dangerous policies of US imperialism! |url=https://www.tudehpartyiran.org/en/news/4657-statement-of-the-central-committee-of-the-tudeh-party-of-iran-the-urgent-need-to-intensify-efforts-to-preserve-peace-in-the-region-and-confront-the-adventurous-and-dangerous-policies-of-us-imperialism |website=Tudeh Party of Iran |publisher=Central Committee of the Tudeh Party of Iran |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|#\n!rowspan=2|Name\n!colspan=2|Tenure\n!rowspan=2|Title\n!rowspan=2|Ref\n|-\n!From\n!To\n|-\n|1\n|[[Soleiman Eskandari]]\n|1941\n|1944\n|Chairman\n|<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/281 281, 292]|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/281}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2\n|[[Iraj Eskandari]]\n|rowspan=3|1944\n|rowspan=3|1948\n|rowspan=3|General-Secretaries<br />{{small|(Shared)}}\n|rowspan=3|<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/297 297]|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/297}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Mohammad Bahrami]]\n|-\n|[[Noureddin Alamouti]]\n|-\n|3\n|[[Reza Radmanesh]]\n|1948\n|1969\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/313 313]|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/313}}</ref>\n|-\n|\u2013\n|[[Mohammad Bahrami]]\n|1949\n|1953\n|Acting First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|last1=Maziar |first1=Behrooz|year=2000|title=Rebels With A Cause: The Failure of the Left in Iran|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=1860646301|page=11}}</ref>\n|-\n|4\n|[[Iraj Eskandari]]\n|1969\n|1979\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|title=ESKANDAR\u012a, \u012aRAJ|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]|date=December 15, 1998|orig-year=January 19, 2012|publisher=Bibliotheca Persica Press|location=New York City|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/eskandari-iraj|volume= VIII|last1=Chaqueri|first1=Cosroe|editor-last=Yarshater|editor-first=Ehsan|editor-link=Ehsan Yarshater|access-date=September 12, 2017|series=Fasc. 6|pages=604\u2013606}}</ref>\n|-\n|5\n|[[Noureddin Kianouri]]\n|1979\n|1984\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n|-\n|\u2013\n|rowspan=2|[[Ali Khavari]]\n|1983\n|1984\n|Acting First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|author=Sepehr Zabir|title=The Left in Contemporary Iran (RLE Iran D)|date=2012|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-136-81263-7|page=206}}</ref>\n|-\n|6\n|1984\n|2004\n|First-Secretary\n|<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hiro|first1=Dilip|title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals)|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=1135043817|page=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iran|Politics|Communism}}\n* [[Political parties in Iran]]\n* [[Constitutionalist movement of Gilan]]\n* [[Soviet Republic of Gilan]]\n* ''[[Iran is not just Tehran]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}} {{in lang|fa|en|de}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H8b_usgKnz4 Party anthem]\n{{Iranian exiled parties}}\n{{Middle East communist parties}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tudeh Party Of Iran}}\n[[Category:Tudeh Party of Iran| ]]\n", "name_user": "CentreLeftRight", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tudeh_Party_of_Iran"}
{"title_page": "Jax Taylor", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jax Taylor\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1979|07|11}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shelby Township, Michigan]], U.S.\n| education          = \n| occupation         = Television personality, actor, model, beer cheese magnate\n| television         = ''[[Vanderpump Rules]]''\n| spouse             = Laura Leigh\n| website            = \n| imagesize          = \n| birthname          = Jason Michael Cauchi\n| height             = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}\n| haircolor          = Pink\n| eyecolor           = Black\n| agency             = Neon Model Management\n}}\n\n'''Jason Michael Cauchi''' (born July 11, 1979), known professionally as '''Jax Taylor''' is an American television personality, model, and actor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5470001/|title=Jax Taylor|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-08-03}}</ref> He currently stars on the [[Bravo (U.S. TV channel)|Bravo]] reality television series ''[[Vanderpump Rules]]''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTaylor was born in [[Shelby Charter Township, Michigan]] on July 11, 1979, to Marie and Ronald Cauchi.<ref name=\":0\" /> His mother is an Australian, and his father is Maltese. He has a sister, Jenny Lynn. He was raised Catholic and attended church until he was 19 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://melmagazine.com/en-us/story/a-conversation-with-jax-taylor-reality-tvs-most-notorious-bad-boy|title=A Conversation With Jax Taylor, Reality TV\u2019s Most Notorious Bad Boy - MEL Magazine|date=2017-11-30|work=MEL Magazine|access-date=2018-11-03|language=en-US}}</ref>  In 1998, he graduated from [[Eisenhower High School (Michigan)|Eisenhower High School]] in Shelby Township, Michigan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/vanderpump-rules/photos/before-they-worked-at-sur-jax-taylor|title=Before They Worked at Sur: Jax Taylor|date=2015-01-04|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en-US}}</ref> He attended [[Michigan State University]] and community college, but dropped out of school to enter the [[United States Navy|Navy]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/the-daily-dish/jax-taylor-was-in-the-navy-details|title=Why Didn't Jax Taylor's Navy Training Help Him During that Near-Death Experience in Big Bear?|date=2018-03-01|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-09-06|language=en-US}}</ref> He was in the Navy for 6 months, 4 days and was trained at a base in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2016/03/jax-taylor-vanderpump-rules-villain-interview|title=The Villain of 'Vanderpump Rules'|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thisainthell.us/blog/?p=85719|title=\u2018Sharknado 4\u2019 Actor Accused of Stolen Valor|date=2019-03-19|website=This ain't Hell, but you can see it from here|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2002 to 2010, Taylor worked as a model in Europe and lived in [[Miami]] in an apartment with four other male models, including [[Channing Tatum]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a25378755/vanderpump-rules-jax-taylor-weight-loss-transformation/|title='Vanderpump Rules' Star Jax Taylor Opens Up About His Pre-Wedding Weight Loss|last=Reslen|first=Eileen|date=2018-12-17|website=Men's Health|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref> Taylor signed with [[Ford Models]] in New York City.<ref name=\":3\" /> He has appeared on several magazine editorials and front covers, including [[Trump (magazine)|''Trump Magazine,'']] ''[[VMan|V Man]]'', ''[[GQ|GQ Japan]]'', ''[[Men's Health|Men\u2019s Health]]'',  ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[944 Magazine]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[Instinct (magazine)|Instinct]]'', ''[[Cosmogirl|CosmoGirl]]'' and ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]].''<ref name=\":1\" /> He has also starred in campaigns for [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[Macy's]], [[J. C. Penney|JC Pennys]], [[Old Navy]], [[Nordstrom]], [[Kohl's]], [[Skechers|Sketchers]], [[Paul Mitchell (hairdresser)|Paul Mitchell]], [[AussieBum]], [[2(x)ist|2<sup>(x)</sup>ist]], [[Taco Bell]] and [[Abercrombie & Fitch]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.modelmayhem.com/jaxtaylor|title=Jax Taylor|website=www.modelmayhem.com|access-date=2018-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://people.com/tv/vanderpump-rules-before-they-were-stars/#jax-taylor|title=See the Cast of Vanderpump Rules Before They Were Stars|work=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, he resumed his modelling career by starring in a Jack Victor campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bravotv.com/vanderpump-rules/lookbook/jax-taylor-modeling-return-jack-victor-ad-nordstrom|title=You May Just Run into Jax Taylor on Your Next Trip to This Popular Department Store|last=|first=|date=2018-08-16|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe started working at [[Lisa Vanderpump]]'s restaurants SUR and Villa Blanca, which earned him a spot on the reality television series ''[[Vanderpump Rules]]'' in 2013, following the lives of the SUR and Villa Blanca servers. Taylor and Brittany Cartwright got their own spin-off television series ''[[Vanderpump Rules: Jax And Brittany Take Kentucky|Vanderpump Rules: Jax and Brittany Take Kentucky]]'', which followed the couple's visit to Cartwright's hometown in Kentucky.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/vanderpump-rules-jax-and-brittany-take-kentucky|title=Vanderpump Rules Jax and Brittany Take Kentucky|date=2017-07-25|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2014, Taylor collaborated with XCALIBUR BRAND to create a shoe and sweater collection titled Jax Taylor by XCALIBUR BRAND.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/24831-vanderpump-rules-star-jax-taylors-shoe-line-is-what-rob-kardashians-sock-line-has-needed-all|title=Jax + Rob K. = Footwear Match Made In Heaven|last=Rohwedder|first=Kristie|work=Bustle|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/27970-vanderpump-rules-jax-taylor-landed-a-clothing-line-simply-by-wearing-the-right-shoes|title=What Would Stassi Say?|last=Rohwedder|first=Kristie|work=Bustle|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref> In 2014, Taylor also created a fitness application.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/16468-vanderpump-rules-secrets-revealed-jax-makes-a-workout-app-scheana-ariana-scream-in-a-freezer|title=Someone Wears Only a Sock On 'Vanderpump'|last=Rohwedder|first=Kristie|work=Bustle|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe began dating Brittany Cartwright in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://people.com/tv/vanderpump-rules-jax-taylor-brittany-cartwright-engaged/|title=Vanderpump Rules Stars Jax Taylor and Brittany Cartwright Are Engaged \u2013\u2013 See the Ring!|work=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref> The couple got engaged in [[Malibu, California]] on June 7, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/the-daily-dish/go-inside-the-moment-jax-taylor-proposed-to-brittany-cartwright-engagement-photos|title=Go Inside the Moment Jax Taylor Proposed to Brittany Cartwright|date=2018-06-11|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Taylor and Cartwright reside in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/home/inside-jax-taylor-brittany-cartwrights-los-angeles-home/|title=Inside Vanderpump Rules Couple Jax Taylor and Brittany Cartwright\u2019s Los Angeles Love Nest|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> The couple wed on June 29, 2019 in Kentucky.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Desperate Housewives]]''\n| Hot Guy 2 in Dance Club \n| Episode: \"Look Into Their Eyes and You See What They Know\"\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Dexter (TV series)|Dexter]]''\n|Uncredited extra\n|Episode: \"This Is the Way the World Ends\"\n|-\n|2012\u20132014\n|''[[The Real Housewives of Beverly Hills]]''\n|Himself\n|6 episodes\n|-\n|2013\u2013present\n|''[[Vanderpump Rules]]''\n|Himself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|2015\u20132018\n|''[[Watch What Happens: Live]]'' \n|Himself / Guest\n|11 episodes\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Sharknado: The 4th Awakens]]''\n|Guardsman #2\n|Television film\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Then and Now with Andy Cohen]]''\n|Himself\n|Episodes: \"2003\" and \"1990\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Vanderpump Rules: Jax And Brittany Take Kentucky|Vanderpump Rules: Jax and Brittany Take Kentucky]]''\n|Himself\n|TV Mini-Series; 6 episodes\n|-\n|2019\n|''Basically Stassi''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Stassi and Beau Go Toe to Toe with Jax and Brittany\"\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|5470001}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Jax}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:Male models from Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jax Taylor\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1979|07|11}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shelby Township, Michigan]], U.S.\n| education          = \n| occupation         = Television personality, actor, model\n| television         = ''[[Vanderpump Rules]]''\n| spouse             = Laura Leigh\n| website            = \n| imagesize          = \n| birthname          = Jason Michael Cauchi\n| height             = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}\n| haircolor          = Pink\n| eyecolor           = Black\n| agency             = Neon Model Management\n}}\n\n'''Jason Michael Cauchi''' (born July 11, 1979), known professionally as '''Jax Taylor''' is an American television personality, model, and actor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5470001/|title=Jax Taylor|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-08-03}}</ref> He currently stars on the [[Bravo (U.S. TV channel)|Bravo]] reality television series ''[[Vanderpump Rules]]''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTaylor was born in [[Shelby Charter Township, Michigan]] on July 11, 1979, to Marie and Ronald Cauchi.<ref name=\":0\" /> His mother is an Australian, and his father is Maltese. He has a sister, Jenny Lynn. He was raised Catholic and attended church until he was 19 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://melmagazine.com/en-us/story/a-conversation-with-jax-taylor-reality-tvs-most-notorious-bad-boy|title=A Conversation With Jax Taylor, Reality TV\u2019s Most Notorious Bad Boy - MEL Magazine|date=2017-11-30|work=MEL Magazine|access-date=2018-11-03|language=en-US}}</ref>  In 1998, he graduated from [[Eisenhower High School (Michigan)|Eisenhower High School]] in Shelby Township, Michigan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/vanderpump-rules/photos/before-they-worked-at-sur-jax-taylor|title=Before They Worked at Sur: Jax Taylor|date=2015-01-04|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en-US}}</ref> He attended [[Michigan State University]] and community college, but dropped out of school to enter the [[United States Navy|Navy]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/the-daily-dish/jax-taylor-was-in-the-navy-details|title=Why Didn't Jax Taylor's Navy Training Help Him During that Near-Death Experience in Big Bear?|date=2018-03-01|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-09-06|language=en-US}}</ref> He was in the Navy for 6 months, 4 days and was trained at a base in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2016/03/jax-taylor-vanderpump-rules-villain-interview|title=The Villain of 'Vanderpump Rules'|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thisainthell.us/blog/?p=85719|title=\u2018Sharknado 4\u2019 Actor Accused of Stolen Valor|date=2019-03-19|website=This ain't Hell, but you can see it from here|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2002 to 2010, Taylor worked as a model in Europe and lived in [[Miami]] in an apartment with four other male models, including [[Channing Tatum]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a25378755/vanderpump-rules-jax-taylor-weight-loss-transformation/|title='Vanderpump Rules' Star Jax Taylor Opens Up About His Pre-Wedding Weight Loss|last=Reslen|first=Eileen|date=2018-12-17|website=Men's Health|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref> Taylor signed with [[Ford Models]] in New York City.<ref name=\":3\" /> He has appeared on several magazine editorials and front covers, including [[Trump (magazine)|''Trump Magazine,'']] ''[[VMan|V Man]]'', ''[[GQ|GQ Japan]]'', ''[[Men's Health|Men\u2019s Health]]'',  ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[944 Magazine]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[Instinct (magazine)|Instinct]]'', ''[[Cosmogirl|CosmoGirl]]'' and ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]].''<ref name=\":1\" /> He has also starred in campaigns for [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[Macy's]], [[J. C. Penney|JC Pennys]], [[Old Navy]], [[Nordstrom]], [[Kohl's]], [[Skechers|Sketchers]], [[Paul Mitchell (hairdresser)|Paul Mitchell]], [[AussieBum]], [[2(x)ist|2<sup>(x)</sup>ist]], [[Taco Bell]] and [[Abercrombie & Fitch]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.modelmayhem.com/jaxtaylor|title=Jax Taylor|website=www.modelmayhem.com|access-date=2018-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://people.com/tv/vanderpump-rules-before-they-were-stars/#jax-taylor|title=See the Cast of Vanderpump Rules Before They Were Stars|work=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, he resumed his modelling career by starring in a Jack Victor campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bravotv.com/vanderpump-rules/lookbook/jax-taylor-modeling-return-jack-victor-ad-nordstrom|title=You May Just Run into Jax Taylor on Your Next Trip to This Popular Department Store|last=|first=|date=2018-08-16|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe started working at [[Lisa Vanderpump]]'s restaurants SUR and Villa Blanca, which earned him a spot on the reality television series ''[[Vanderpump Rules]]'' in 2013, following the lives of the SUR and Villa Blanca servers. Taylor and Brittany Cartwright got their own spin-off television series ''[[Vanderpump Rules: Jax And Brittany Take Kentucky|Vanderpump Rules: Jax and Brittany Take Kentucky]]'', which followed the couple's visit to Cartwright's hometown in Kentucky.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/vanderpump-rules-jax-and-brittany-take-kentucky|title=Vanderpump Rules Jax and Brittany Take Kentucky|date=2017-07-25|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2014, Taylor collaborated with XCALIBUR BRAND to create a shoe and sweater collection titled Jax Taylor by XCALIBUR BRAND.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/24831-vanderpump-rules-star-jax-taylors-shoe-line-is-what-rob-kardashians-sock-line-has-needed-all|title=Jax + Rob K. = Footwear Match Made In Heaven|last=Rohwedder|first=Kristie|work=Bustle|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/27970-vanderpump-rules-jax-taylor-landed-a-clothing-line-simply-by-wearing-the-right-shoes|title=What Would Stassi Say?|last=Rohwedder|first=Kristie|work=Bustle|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref> In 2014, Taylor also created a fitness application.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/16468-vanderpump-rules-secrets-revealed-jax-makes-a-workout-app-scheana-ariana-scream-in-a-freezer|title=Someone Wears Only a Sock On 'Vanderpump'|last=Rohwedder|first=Kristie|work=Bustle|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe began dating Brittany Cartwright in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://people.com/tv/vanderpump-rules-jax-taylor-brittany-cartwright-engaged/|title=Vanderpump Rules Stars Jax Taylor and Brittany Cartwright Are Engaged \u2013\u2013 See the Ring!|work=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref> The couple got engaged in [[Malibu, California]] on June 7, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravotv.com/the-daily-dish/go-inside-the-moment-jax-taylor-proposed-to-brittany-cartwright-engagement-photos|title=Go Inside the Moment Jax Taylor Proposed to Brittany Cartwright|date=2018-06-11|work=Bravo TV Official Site|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Taylor and Cartwright reside in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/home/inside-jax-taylor-brittany-cartwrights-los-angeles-home/|title=Inside Vanderpump Rules Couple Jax Taylor and Brittany Cartwright\u2019s Los Angeles Love Nest|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> The couple wed on June 29, 2019 in Kentucky.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Desperate Housewives]]''\n| Hot Guy 2 in Dance Club \n| Episode: \"Look Into Their Eyes and You See What They Know\"\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Dexter (TV series)|Dexter]]''\n|Uncredited extra\n|Episode: \"This Is the Way the World Ends\"\n|-\n|2012\u20132014\n|''[[The Real Housewives of Beverly Hills]]''\n|Himself\n|6 episodes\n|-\n|2013\u2013present\n|''[[Vanderpump Rules]]''\n|Himself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|2015\u20132018\n|''[[Watch What Happens: Live]]'' \n|Himself / Guest\n|11 episodes\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Sharknado: The 4th Awakens]]''\n|Guardsman #2\n|Television film\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Then and Now with Andy Cohen]]''\n|Himself\n|Episodes: \"2003\" and \"1990\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Vanderpump Rules: Jax And Brittany Take Kentucky|Vanderpump Rules: Jax and Brittany Take Kentucky]]''\n|Himself\n|TV Mini-Series; 6 episodes\n|-\n|2019\n|''Basically Stassi''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Stassi and Beau Go Toe to Toe with Jax and Brittany\"\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|5470001}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Jax}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:Male models from Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "96.250.81.2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed occupation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jax_Taylor"}
{"title_page": "Oleg Losev", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = Oleg Losev<br>\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u041b\u043e\u0441\u0435\u0432\n| image                   = Oleg losev.jpg\n| image_size             = 153px\n| birth_date              = 10 May 1903\n| birth_place             = [[Tver]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date              = {{d-da|22 January 1942|10 May 1903}}\n| death_place             = [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[Russian SFSR]]\n| residence               = [[Nizhny Novgorod]], [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]]\n| citizenship             = [[Russia]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| ethnicity               =\n| field                   = [[Physics]], [[electrical engineering]]\n| work_institution        = [[Nizhniy-Novgorod Radio Laboratory]] (NRL), Central Radio Laboratory (TSRL, Leningrad), Leningrad Physicotechnical Institute, First Leningrad Medical Institute\n| occupation              = physicist, inventor\n| known_for               = [[Invention]]s, [[radio]], [[Light-emitting diode|LEDs]]\n}}\n\n[[File:\u0412\u0430\u043a\u0443\u0443\u043c-\u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d \u043b\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0440 \u0426\u0420\u041b 1930.jpg|thumb|Employees of the Central Radio Laboratory, Leningrad, 1930.  Losev is in fourth row, third from left.]]\n\n'''Oleg Vladimirovich Losev''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0433 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u043e\u0301\u0441\u0435\u0432}}, sometimes spelled Lossev or Lossew in English) (10 May 1903 \u2013 22 January 1942) was a Russian [[scientist]] and [[inventor]]<ref name=\"ssd2004\">\n{{cite journal\n |last         = \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\n |first        = M. A.\n |year         = 2004\n |script-title = ru:\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u043e\u0441\u0435\u0432 \u2013 \u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\n |trans-title  = Oleg Vladimirovich Losev \u2013 Pioneer of Semiconductor Electronics\n |language     = Russian\n |journal      = \u0424\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0430 [Solid State Physics]\n |volume       = 46\n |issue        = 1\n |pages        = 5\u20139\n |accessdate   = 2008-01-01\n |url          = http://www.ioffe.ru/journals/ftt/2004/01/p5-9.pdf\n |url-status      = dead\n |archiveurl   = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928010711/http://www.ioffe.ru/journals/ftt/2004/01/p5-9.pdf\n |archivedate  = 2007-09-28\n}} An English translation [https://link.springer.com/article/10.1134/1.1641908#page-1     M. A. Novikov (January 2004) \"Oleg Vladimirovich Losev: Pioneer of Semiconductor Electronics,\" ''Physics of the Solid State'', vol. 46, no. 1, page 1-4] is on the Springer archive</ref> who made significant discoveries in the field of [[p-n junction|semiconductor junctions]].\n\nAlthough he was never able to complete a formal education and never held a research position, Losev conducted some of the earliest research into [[semiconductor]]s, publishing 43 papers and receiving 16 \"author's certificates\" (the Soviet version of patents) for his discoveries.<ref name=\"Graham\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Graham\n | first1 = Loren \n | title  = Lonely Ideas: Can Russia Compete?\n | publisher = MIT Press\n | date   = 2013\n | location = \n | pages  = 62\u201363\n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=UciqAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&dq=%22oleg+losev\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-0262019798\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Zheludev\">{{cite journal\n |first       = Nikolay\n |last        = Zheludev\n |date        = April 2007\n |title       = The life and times of the LED \u2013 a 100-year history\n |journal     = [[Nature Photonics]]\n |volume      = 1\n |issue       = 4\n |pages       = 189\u2013192\n |doi         = 10.1038/nphoton.2007.34\n |accessdate  = 2007-04-11\n |url         = http://www.orc.soton.ac.uk/fileadmin/downloads/100_years_of_optoelectronics__2_.pdf\n |bibcode     = 2007NaPho...1..189Z\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170331083710/http://www.orc.soton.ac.uk/fileadmin/downloads/100_years_of_optoelectronics__2_.pdf\n |archivedate = 2017-03-31\n}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\">{{cite book   \n  | last = Ben-Menahem\n  | first = Ari \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Historical Encyclopedia of Natural and Mathematical Sciences, Vol. 1\n  | publisher = Springer\n  | date = 2009\n  | location = \n  | page = 3588\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=9tUrarQYhKMC&pg=PA3588&dq=losev+%22negative+resistance%22#v=onepage&q=losev%20%22negative%20resistance%22&f=false\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-3540688310}}</ref>   He observed light emission from carborundum point-contact junctions, the first [[light-emitting diode]] (LED), did the first research on them, proposed the first correct theory of how they worked, and used them in practical applications such as [[electroluminescence]].<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\" /><ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite book   \n  | last = Lee\n  | first = Thomas H.\n  | title = The Design of CMOS Radio-Frequency Integrated Circuits, 2nd Ed.\n  | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n  | date = 2004\n  | location = UK\n  | pages = 20\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=io1hL48OqBsC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=%22negative+resistance\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-0521835398}}</ref>  He explored [[negative resistance]] in semiconductor junctions, and was first to use them practically for amplification, building the first solid-state [[amplifier]]s, [[electronic oscillator]]s, and [[superheterodyne]] radio receivers, 25 years before the invention of the [[transistor]].<ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" /> However his achievements were overlooked, and languished unknown for half a century before being recognized in the late 20th and early 21st century.\n\n==Career and personal life==\nLosev was born into a noble family in [[Tver]], Russia.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />  His father was a retired captain in the Tsarist Imperial Army, who worked in the office of [[Tverskoy Vagonostroitelniy Zavod]] (Tversky Wagon Works), a local rolling stock factory.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" /> Losev graduated from secondary school in 1920.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />\n\nAt this time in Russian history, three years after the [[Bolshevik Revolution]], during the upheaval of the [[Russian Civil War]], an upper-class family background was a bar to higher education and career advancement.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Losev went to work as a technician at the recently established [[Nizhny Novgorod Radio Laboratory]] (NNRL), the new Soviet government's first radio science laboratory, located in [[Nizhny Novgorod]], where he worked under {{Interlanguage link multi|Vladimir Lebedinsky|ru|3=\u041b\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}}.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Although he managed to attend a few classes, he remained throughout his life a self-taught scientist who never got to complete a college education, never had the support of a collaborator or research team, and never held a position higher than technician.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Nevertheless, he managed to conduct original research.  His interests focused on the point-contact [[crystal detector]] (cat's whisker detector), which was used as a [[demodulator]] in the first early radio receivers, [[crystal radio]]s, before powered [[vacuum tube]] radios were developed in World War 1.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" />  These crude [[semiconductor diode]]s were the first [[semiconductor]] electronic devices, and although they were widely used, almost nothing was known about how they worked.  Losev became one of the world's first semiconductor physicists.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />\n\nWhen Nizhny Novgorod was shut down in 1928, he transferred along with many of the research staff to the Central Radio Laboratory (CRL) in Leningrad ([[St. Petersburg]]).<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />  At the invitation of director [[Abram Ioffe]], from 1929 to 1933 he conducted research at the [[Ioffe Institute|Ioffe Physical-Technical Institute]].<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  He was eventually awarded a PhD from the Institute in 1938 without completing a formal thesis, but it came too late to benefit his career.<ref name=\"Graham\" />  After much hardship, in 1937 Losev was forced to take a position as a technician at the physics department of the Leningrad First Medical Institute (now the [[First Pavlov State Medical University of St. Peterburg]])<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /> which did not support his research interests, where he continued until 1942.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" />   Losev died of starvation in 1942, at the age of 38, along with many other civilians, during the [[Siege of Leningrad]] by the Germans during World War 2.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  It is not known where he was buried.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />\n\n==Light-emitting diodes==\nIn radio receivers, crystal detectors were often forward-biased with DC current from a battery to make them more sensitive rectifiers.   In the course of investigating biased junctions as a technician at Nizhny Novgorod, Losev noticed that when direct current was passed through a [[silicon carbide]] (carborundum) point contact junction, a spot of greenish light was given off at the contact point.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Losev had constructed a [[light-emitting diode]] (LED).<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Although this effect had been noticed in 1907 by British Marconi engineer [[Henry Joseph Round]], he had just published a brief two paragraph note on it.<ref name=\"Round\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Round\n  | first = Henry J.\n  | title = A note on carborundum\n  | journal = Electrical World\n  | volume = 49\n  | issue = 6\n  | pages = 309\n  |date=9 February 1907 \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TAZRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA309#v=onepage&q&f=false\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = September 1, 2014}}</ref>   Losev was the first to investigate the effect, propose a theory of how it worked, and envision practical applications.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  In 1927, Losev published details in a Russian journal.<ref name=\"Losev1927\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Losev\n  | first = O. V.\n  | title = \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u044f\u0449\u0438\u0439\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0438 \n  |trans-title=Luminous carborundum detector and detection with crystals\n  | journal = \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 (Wireless Telegraphy and Telephony)\n  | volume = 5\n  | issue = 44\n  | pages = 485\u2013494\n  | date = 1927\n  | url = \n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = }} English version published as {{cite journal\n | last   = Lossev\n | first  = O. V.\n |date=November 1928\n | title  = Luminous carborundum detector and detection effect and oscillations with crystals\n | journal = [[Philosophical Magazine]]\n | series=Series 7\n | volume = 5\n | issue = 39\n | pages = 1024\u20131044\n | pmid =\n | doi = 10.1080/14786441108564683\n }}</ref>\n\nLosev did extensive research into the mechanism of light emission.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"Schubert\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Schubert\n | first1 = E. Fred \n | title  = Light-emitting Diodes\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n | date   = 2003\n | location = \n | pages  = 2\u20133\n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=hI8JpVW5KToC&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=%22Losev+carborundum\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-0521533515\n }}</ref>  At the time, the prevailing theory of point contact junctions was that they worked by a thermoelectric effect,<ref name=\"Lee\" /> possibly due to microscopic electric arcs.  Losev measured rates of evaporation of benzine from the crystal surface and found it was not accelerated when light was emitted, concluding that the luminescence was a \"cold\" light not caused by thermal effects.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"Schubert\" />  He theorized correctly that the explanation of the light emission was in the new science of [[quantum mechanics]],<ref name=\"Lee\" /> speculating that it was the inverse of the [[photoelectric effect]] discovered by [[Albert Einstein]] in 1905.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  He wrote to Einstein about it, but did not receive a reply.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />\n\nIn the period of 1924 and 1941, he published a number of articles detailing the function of a solid-state light source that he developed, which would generate light by [[electroluminescence]].<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Losev1927\" />  Silicon carbide is an [[indirect bandgap]] [[semiconductor]] and so was very inefficient as a light-emitting diode, much less efficient than the direct bandgap semiconductor materials used in modern LEDs, such as [[gallium nitride]]. No one saw a use for these weak green lights except Losev.\n\nIn 1951, [[Kurt Lehovec]] et al. published a paper in ''[[Physical Review]]''. Losev's papers were cited but his name appeared as Lossew.<ref name=\"Lehovec\">{{cite journal\n | author = K. Lehovec, C.A. Accardo and E. Jamgochian\n | date = 1951-08-01\n | title = Injected light emission of silicon carbide crystals\n | journal = [[Physical Review]]\n | volume = 83\n | issue = 3\n | pages = 603\u2013608\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRev.83.603\n | accessdate =\n | url =\n |bibcode = 1951PhRv...83..603L }}\n</ref>\n\nIn the April 2007 issue of ''[[Nature Photonics]]'', [[Nikolay Zheludev]] gives credit to Losev for inventing the [[LED]].<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Simonite\">\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.newscientist.com/blog/technology/2007/04/led-older-than-we-thought.html\n| title =  The LED \u2013 older than we thought\n| accessdate = 2007-04-11\n| author = Tom Simonite\n| date = 2007-04-11\n| publisher = New Scientist Blogs\n}}\n</ref>\nSpecifically, Losev patented the \"Light Relay\"<ref>Soviet patent #12191 granted in 1929.<br/>{{cite patent\n| country       = su\n| number        = 00012191\n| title         = \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0435\n| pubdate       = 31.12.1929\n| inventor      = Losev O.V.\n| url           = http://patents.su/2-12191-svetovoe-rele.html\n}}</ref> and foresaw its use in telecommunications.\n\n==Solid-state electronics==\n[[Image:Crystodyne zincite oscillator - top.png|thumb|upright=1.4|\"Crystodyne\" zinc oxide [[electronic oscillator]] constructed by [[Hugo Gernsback]] in 1924 to Losev's instructions.  The zinc oxide point contact diode which serves as the active device is labeled (9).  These devices were the first semiconductor oscillators. ]]\n\nWhen a DC bias voltage was applied to a [[cat's whisker detector]], in order to increase its sensitivity as a detector in a [[crystal radio]], it occasionally broke into spontaneous [[oscillation]], producing a radio frequency alternating current.  This was a [[negative resistance]] effect, and had been noticed around 1909 by researchers such as [[William Henry Eccles]]<ref name=\"Grebennikov\">{{cite book\n  | last = Grebennikov\n  | first = Andrei \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = RF and Microwave Transmitter Design\n  | publisher = John Wiley & Sons\n  | date = 2011\n  | location = \n  | page = 4\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=nGLdHfULzhYC&pg=PA4&dq=%22negative+resistance%22++%22crystal+detector%22#v=onepage&q=%22negative%20resistance%22%20%20%22crystal%20detector%22&f=false\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-0470520994}}</ref><ref name=\"Pickard\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Pickard\n  | first = Greenleaf W.\n  | title = The Discovery of the Oscillating Crystal\n  | journal = Radio News\n  | volume = 6\n  | issue = 7\n  | page = 1166\n  |date=January 1925 \n  | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-News/20s/Radio-News-1925-01-R.pdf\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = July 15, 2014}}</ref>  and [[Greenleaf Whittier Pickard|G. W. Pickard]].<ref name=\"Pickard\" /><ref name=\"QST\">{{cite journal\n  | title = Strays\n  | journal = QST Magazine\n  | volume = 6\n  | issue = \n  | page = 44\n  | date = March 1920\n  | url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/March_1920_QST.djvu/page40-791px-March_1920_QST.djvu.jpg\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = March 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"White\">{{cite web\n  | last = White\n  | first = Thomas H.\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Section 14 \u2013 Expanded Audio and Vacuum Tube Development (1917\u20131924)\n  | work = United States Early Radio History\n  | publisher = earlyradiohistory.us\n  | date = 2003\n  | url = https://earlyradiohistory.us/sec014.htm#part020\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = September 23, 2012}}</ref> but not much attention had been paid to it.  In 1923 Losev began to research these \"oscillating crystals\" and discovered that biased [[zincite]] ([[zinc oxide]]) crystals could [[amplifier|amplify]] a signal.<ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\" /><ref name=\"White\" /><ref name=\"Losev1925\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Losev\n  | first = O. V.\n  | title = Oscillating Crystals\n  | journal = Radio News\n  | volume = 6\n  | issue = 7\n  | pages = 1167, 1287\n  |date=January 1925 \n  | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-News/20s/Radio-News-1925-01-R.pdf\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = July 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Gabel\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Gabel\n  | first = Victor\n  | title = The Crystal as a Generator and Amplifier\n  | journal = The Wireless World and Radio Review\n  | volume = 15\n  | issue = \n  | pages = 2\u20135\n  | date = October 1, 1924\n  | url = http://www.hpfriedrichs.com/downloads-lib/xtalgen.pdf\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = March 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Gernsback\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Gernsback\n  | first = Hugo\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = A Sensational Radio Invention\n  | journal = Radio News\n  | volume = \n  | issue = \n  | page = 291\n  | date = September 1924\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=2rQ1AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA291&lpg=PA291#v=onepage&q&f=false \n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = January 1, 2020}} and \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=2rQ1AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA294&lpg=PA294#v=onepage&q&f=false \"The Crystodyne Principle\"], (September 1924), ''Radio News'', pp. 294\u2013295, 431.</ref><ref name=\"Lee2\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=io1hL48OqBsC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20     Lee, Thomas H. (2004) The Design of CMOS Radio-Frequency Integrated Circuits, 2nd Ed., p. 20]</ref>  Losev was the first to exploit negative resistance diodes practically; he realized that they could serve as simpler, cheaper replacements for [[vacuum tube]]s.<ref name=\"ssd2004\"/> He used these junctions to build solid-state versions of [[electronic amplifier|amplifiers]], [[oscillator]]s, and TRF and [[regenerative radio receiver]]s, at frequencies up to 5&nbsp;MHz, 25 years before the transistor.<ref name=\"Lee2\"/> He even built a [[superheterodyne receiver]].<ref name=\"Lee2\"/>  However his achievements were overlooked because of the success of [[vacuum tube]] technology. The Soviet authorities did not support him, and zincite crystals were hard to come by because they had to be imported from the United States. After ten years he abandoned research into this technology (dubbed \"Crystodyne\" by [[Hugo Gernsback]]),<ref name=\"Gernsback\" /> and it was forgotten.<ref name=\"Lee2\" />\n\nNegative resistance in diodes was rediscovered in 1956 in the [[tunnel diode]], and today negative resistance diodes like the [[Gunn diode]] and [[IMPATT diode]] are used in microwave oscillators and amplifiers and are some of the most widely used sources of [[microwave]]s.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oleg Losev}}\n*[http://russianpatentsblog.patentsfromru.com/2007/04/12/youd-better-not-ignore-russian-prior-art-search-says-new-scientist-magazine/ Facsimile of \"Light Relay\" and other Oleg Losev's patents] \u2013 from [[Russian Patents blog]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Losev, Oleg Vladimirovich}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Russian physicists]]\n[[Category:Russian inventors]]\n[[Category:Light-emitting diode pioneers]]\n[[Category:Russian electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:Soviet physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century physicists]]\n[[Category:People from Tver]]\n[[Category:20th-century inventors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = Oleg Losev<br>\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u041b\u043e\u0441\u0435\u0432\n| image                   = Oleg losev.jpg\n| image_size             = 153px\n| birth_date              = 10 May 1903\n| birth_place             = [[Tver]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date              = {{d-da|22 January 1942|10 May 1903}}\n| death_place             = [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[Russian SFSR]]\n| residence               = [[Nizhny Novgorod]], [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]]\n| citizenship             = [[Russia]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| ethnicity               =\n| field                   = [[Physics]], [[electrical engineering]]\n| work_institution        = [[Nizhniy-Novgorod Radio Laboratory]] (NRL), Central Radio Laboratory (TSRL, Leningrad), Leningrad Physicotechnical Institute, First Leningrad Medical Institute\n| occupation              = physicist, inventor\n| known_for               = [[Invention]]s, [[radio]], [[Light-emitting diode|LEDs]]\n}}\n\n[[File:\u0412\u0430\u043a\u0443\u0443\u043c-\u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d \u043b\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0440 \u0426\u0420\u041b 1930.jpg|thumb|Employees of the Central Radio Laboratory, Leningrad, 1930.  Losev is in fourth row, third from left.]]\n\n'''Oleg Vladimirovich Losev''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0433 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u043e\u0301\u0441\u0435\u0432}}, sometimes spelled Lossev or Lossew in English) (10 May 1903 \u2013 22 January 1942) was a Russian [[scientist]] and [[inventor]],<ref name=\"ssd2004\">\n{{cite journal\n |last         = \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\n |first        = M. A.\n |year         = 2004\n |script-title = ru:\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u043e\u0441\u0435\u0432 \u2013 \u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\n |trans-title  = Oleg Vladimirovich Losev \u2013 Pioneer of Semiconductor Electronics\n |language     = Russian\n |journal      = \u0424\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0430 [Solid State Physics]\n |volume       = 46\n |issue        = 1\n |pages        = 5\u20139\n |accessdate   = 2008-01-01\n |url          = http://www.ioffe.ru/journals/ftt/2004/01/p5-9.pdf\n |url-status      = dead\n |archiveurl   = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928010711/http://www.ioffe.ru/journals/ftt/2004/01/p5-9.pdf\n |archivedate  = 2007-09-28\n}} An English translation [https://link.springer.com/article/10.1134/1.1641908#page-1     M. A. Novikov (January 2004) \"Oleg Vladimirovich Losev: Pioneer of Semiconductor Electronics,\" ''Physics of the Solid State'', vol. 46, no. 1, page 1-4] is on the Springer archive</ref> who made significant discoveries in the field of [[p-n junction|semiconductor junctions]].\n\nAlthough he was never able to complete a formal education and never held a research position, Losev conducted some of the earliest research into [[semiconductor]]s, publishing 43 papers and receiving 16 \"author's certificates\" (the Soviet version of patents) for his discoveries.<ref name=\"Graham\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Graham\n | first1 = Loren \n | title  = Lonely Ideas: Can Russia Compete?\n | publisher = MIT Press\n | date   = 2013\n | location = \n | pages  = 62\u201363\n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=UciqAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&dq=%22oleg+losev\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-0262019798\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Zheludev\">{{cite journal\n |first       = Nikolay\n |last        = Zheludev\n |date        = April 2007\n |title       = The life and times of the LED \u2013 a 100-year history\n |journal     = [[Nature Photonics]]\n |volume      = 1\n |issue       = 4\n |pages       = 189\u2013192\n |doi         = 10.1038/nphoton.2007.34\n |accessdate  = 2007-04-11\n |url         = http://www.orc.soton.ac.uk/fileadmin/downloads/100_years_of_optoelectronics__2_.pdf\n |bibcode     = 2007NaPho...1..189Z\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170331083710/http://www.orc.soton.ac.uk/fileadmin/downloads/100_years_of_optoelectronics__2_.pdf\n |archivedate = 2017-03-31\n}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\">{{cite book   \n  | last = Ben-Menahem\n  | first = Ari \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Historical Encyclopedia of Natural and Mathematical Sciences, Vol. 1\n  | publisher = Springer\n  | date = 2009\n  | location = \n  | page = 3588\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=9tUrarQYhKMC&pg=PA3588&dq=losev+%22negative+resistance%22#v=onepage&q=losev%20%22negative%20resistance%22&f=false\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-3540688310}}</ref>   He observed light emission from carborundum point-contact junctions, the first [[light-emitting diode]] (LED), did the first research on them, proposed the first correct theory of how they worked, and used them in practical applications such as [[electroluminescence]].<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\" /><ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite book   \n  | last = Lee\n  | first = Thomas H.\n  | title = The Design of CMOS Radio-Frequency Integrated Circuits, 2nd Ed.\n  | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n  | date = 2004\n  | location = UK\n  | pages = 20\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=io1hL48OqBsC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=%22negative+resistance\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-0521835398}}</ref>  He explored [[negative resistance]] in semiconductor junctions, and was first to use them practically for amplification, building the first solid-state [[amplifier]]s, [[electronic oscillator]]s, and [[superheterodyne]] radio receivers, 25 years before the invention of the [[transistor]].<ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" /> However his achievements were overlooked, and languished unknown for half a century before being recognized in the late 20th and early 21st century.\n\n==Career and personal life==\nLosev was born into a noble family in [[Tver]], Russia.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />  His father was a retired captain in the Tsarist Imperial Army, who worked in the office of [[Tverskoy Vagonostroitelniy Zavod]] (Tversky Wagon Works), a local rolling stock factory.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" /> Losev graduated from secondary school in 1920.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />\n\nAt this time in Russian history, three years after the [[Bolshevik Revolution]], during the upheaval of the [[Russian Civil War]], an upper-class family background was a bar to higher education and career advancement.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Losev went to work as a technician at the recently established [[Nizhny Novgorod Radio Laboratory]] (NNRL), the new Soviet government's first radio science laboratory, located in [[Nizhny Novgorod]], where he worked under {{Interlanguage link multi|Vladimir Lebedinsky|ru|3=\u041b\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}}.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Although he managed to attend a few classes, he remained throughout his life a self-taught scientist who never got to complete a college education, never had the support of a collaborator or research team, and never held a position higher than technician.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Nevertheless, he managed to conduct original research.  His interests focused on the point-contact [[crystal detector]] (cat's whisker detector), which was used as a [[demodulator]] in the first early radio receivers, [[crystal radio]]s, before powered [[vacuum tube]] radios were developed in World War 1.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" />  These crude [[semiconductor diode]]s were the first [[semiconductor]] electronic devices, and although they were widely used, almost nothing was known about how they worked.  Losev became one of the world's first semiconductor physicists.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />\n\nWhen Nizhny Novgorod was shut down in 1928, he transferred along with many of the research staff to the Central Radio Laboratory (CRL) in Leningrad ([[St. Petersburg]]).<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />  At the invitation of director [[Abram Ioffe]], from 1929 to 1933 he conducted research at the [[Ioffe Institute|Ioffe Physical-Technical Institute]].<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  He was eventually awarded a PhD from the Institute in 1938 without completing a formal thesis, but it came too late to benefit his career.<ref name=\"Graham\" />  After much hardship, in 1937 Losev was forced to take a position as a technician at the physics department of the Leningrad First Medical Institute (now the [[First Pavlov State Medical University of St. Peterburg]])<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /> which did not support his research interests, where he continued until 1942.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" />   Losev died of starvation in 1942, at the age of 38, along with many other civilians, during the [[Siege of Leningrad]] by the Germans during World War 2.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" /><ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  It is not known where he was buried.<ref name=\"ssd2004\" />\n\n==Light-emitting diodes==\nIn radio receivers, crystal detectors were often forward-biased with DC current from a battery to make them more sensitive rectifiers.   In the course of investigating biased junctions as a technician at Nizhny Novgorod, Losev noticed that when direct current was passed through a [[silicon carbide]] (carborundum) point contact junction, a spot of greenish light was given off at the contact point.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Losev had constructed a [[light-emitting diode]] (LED).<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  Although this effect had been noticed in 1907 by British Marconi engineer [[Henry Joseph Round]], he had just published a brief two paragraph note on it.<ref name=\"Round\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Round\n  | first = Henry J.\n  | title = A note on carborundum\n  | journal = Electrical World\n  | volume = 49\n  | issue = 6\n  | pages = 309\n  |date=9 February 1907 \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TAZRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA309#v=onepage&q&f=false\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = September 1, 2014}}</ref>   Losev was the first to investigate the effect, propose a theory of how it worked, and envision practical applications.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  In 1927, Losev published details in a Russian journal.<ref name=\"Losev1927\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Losev\n  | first = O. V.\n  | title = \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u044f\u0449\u0438\u0439\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0438 \n  |trans-title=Luminous carborundum detector and detection with crystals\n  | journal = \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 (Wireless Telegraphy and Telephony)\n  | volume = 5\n  | issue = 44\n  | pages = 485\u2013494\n  | date = 1927\n  | url = \n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = }} English version published as {{cite journal\n | last   = Lossev\n | first  = O. V.\n |date=November 1928\n | title  = Luminous carborundum detector and detection effect and oscillations with crystals\n | journal = [[Philosophical Magazine]]\n | series=Series 7\n | volume = 5\n | issue = 39\n | pages = 1024\u20131044\n | pmid =\n | doi = 10.1080/14786441108564683\n }}</ref>\n\nLosev did extensive research into the mechanism of light emission.<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"Schubert\">{{cite book\n | last1  = Schubert\n | first1 = E. Fred \n | title  = Light-emitting Diodes\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n | date   = 2003\n | location = \n | pages  = 2\u20133\n | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=hI8JpVW5KToC&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=%22Losev+carborundum\n | doi    = \n | id     = \n | isbn   = 978-0521533515\n }}</ref>  At the time, the prevailing theory of point contact junctions was that they worked by a thermoelectric effect,<ref name=\"Lee\" /> possibly due to microscopic electric arcs.  Losev measured rates of evaporation of benzine from the crystal surface and found it was not accelerated when light was emitted, concluding that the luminescence was a \"cold\" light not caused by thermal effects.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"Schubert\" />  He theorized correctly that the explanation of the light emission was in the new science of [[quantum mechanics]],<ref name=\"Lee\" /> speculating that it was the inverse of the [[photoelectric effect]] discovered by [[Albert Einstein]] in 1905.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />  He wrote to Einstein about it, but did not receive a reply.<ref name=\"Graham\" /><ref name=\"Zheludev\" />\n\nIn the period of 1924 and 1941, he published a number of articles detailing the function of a solid-state light source that he developed, which would generate light by [[electroluminescence]].<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Losev1927\" />  Silicon carbide is an [[indirect bandgap]] [[semiconductor]] and so was very inefficient as a light-emitting diode, much less efficient than the direct bandgap semiconductor materials used in modern LEDs, such as [[gallium nitride]]. No one saw a use for these weak green lights except Losev.\n\nIn 1951, [[Kurt Lehovec]] et al. published a paper in ''[[Physical Review]]''. Losev's papers were cited but his name appeared as Lossew.<ref name=\"Lehovec\">{{cite journal\n | author = K. Lehovec, C.A. Accardo and E. Jamgochian\n | date = 1951-08-01\n | title = Injected light emission of silicon carbide crystals\n | journal = [[Physical Review]]\n | volume = 83\n | issue = 3\n | pages = 603\u2013608\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRev.83.603\n | accessdate =\n | url =\n |bibcode = 1951PhRv...83..603L }}\n</ref>\n\nIn the April 2007 issue of ''[[Nature Photonics]]'', [[Nikolay Zheludev]] gives credit to Losev for inventing the [[LED]].<ref name=\"Zheludev\" /><ref name=\"Simonite\">\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.newscientist.com/blog/technology/2007/04/led-older-than-we-thought.html\n| title =  The LED \u2013 older than we thought\n| accessdate = 2007-04-11\n| author = Tom Simonite\n| date = 2007-04-11\n| publisher = New Scientist Blogs\n}}\n</ref>\nSpecifically, Losev patented the \"Light Relay\"<ref>Soviet patent #12191 granted in 1929.<br/>{{cite patent\n| country       = su\n| number        = 00012191\n| title         = \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0435\n| pubdate       = 31.12.1929\n| inventor      = Losev O.V.\n| url           = http://patents.su/2-12191-svetovoe-rele.html\n}}</ref> and foresaw its use in telecommunications.\n\n==Solid-state electronics==\n[[Image:Crystodyne zincite oscillator - top.png|thumb|upright=1.4|\"Crystodyne\" zinc oxide [[electronic oscillator]] constructed by [[Hugo Gernsback]] in 1924 to Losev's instructions.  The zinc oxide point contact diode which serves as the active device is labeled (9).  These devices were the first semiconductor oscillators. ]]\n\nWhen a DC bias voltage was applied to a [[cat's whisker detector]], in order to increase its sensitivity as a detector in a [[crystal radio]], it occasionally broke into spontaneous [[oscillation]], producing a radio frequency alternating current.  This was a [[negative resistance]] effect, and had been noticed around 1909 by researchers such as [[William Henry Eccles]]<ref name=\"Grebennikov\">{{cite book\n  | last = Grebennikov\n  | first = Andrei \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = RF and Microwave Transmitter Design\n  | publisher = John Wiley & Sons\n  | date = 2011\n  | location = \n  | page = 4\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=nGLdHfULzhYC&pg=PA4&dq=%22negative+resistance%22++%22crystal+detector%22#v=onepage&q=%22negative%20resistance%22%20%20%22crystal%20detector%22&f=false\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-0470520994}}</ref><ref name=\"Pickard\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Pickard\n  | first = Greenleaf W.\n  | title = The Discovery of the Oscillating Crystal\n  | journal = Radio News\n  | volume = 6\n  | issue = 7\n  | page = 1166\n  |date=January 1925 \n  | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-News/20s/Radio-News-1925-01-R.pdf\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = July 15, 2014}}</ref>  and [[Greenleaf Whittier Pickard|G. W. Pickard]].<ref name=\"Pickard\" /><ref name=\"QST\">{{cite journal\n  | title = Strays\n  | journal = QST Magazine\n  | volume = 6\n  | issue = \n  | page = 44\n  | date = March 1920\n  | url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/March_1920_QST.djvu/page40-791px-March_1920_QST.djvu.jpg\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = March 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"White\">{{cite web\n  | last = White\n  | first = Thomas H.\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Section 14 \u2013 Expanded Audio and Vacuum Tube Development (1917\u20131924)\n  | work = United States Early Radio History\n  | publisher = earlyradiohistory.us\n  | date = 2003\n  | url = https://earlyradiohistory.us/sec014.htm#part020\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = September 23, 2012}}</ref> but not much attention had been paid to it.  In 1923 Losev began to research these \"oscillating crystals\" and discovered that biased [[zincite]] ([[zinc oxide]]) crystals could [[amplifier|amplify]] a signal.<ref name=\"Ben-Menahem\" /><ref name=\"White\" /><ref name=\"Losev1925\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Losev\n  | first = O. V.\n  | title = Oscillating Crystals\n  | journal = Radio News\n  | volume = 6\n  | issue = 7\n  | pages = 1167, 1287\n  |date=January 1925 \n  | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-News/20s/Radio-News-1925-01-R.pdf\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = July 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Gabel\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Gabel\n  | first = Victor\n  | title = The Crystal as a Generator and Amplifier\n  | journal = The Wireless World and Radio Review\n  | volume = 15\n  | issue = \n  | pages = 2\u20135\n  | date = October 1, 1924\n  | url = http://www.hpfriedrichs.com/downloads-lib/xtalgen.pdf\n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = March 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Gernsback\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Gernsback\n  | first = Hugo\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = A Sensational Radio Invention\n  | journal = Radio News\n  | volume = \n  | issue = \n  | page = 291\n  | date = September 1924\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=2rQ1AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA291&lpg=PA291#v=onepage&q&f=false \n  | issn = \n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = January 1, 2020}} and \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=2rQ1AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA294&lpg=PA294#v=onepage&q&f=false \"The Crystodyne Principle\"], (September 1924), ''Radio News'', pp. 294\u2013295, 431.</ref><ref name=\"Lee2\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=io1hL48OqBsC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20     Lee, Thomas H. (2004) The Design of CMOS Radio-Frequency Integrated Circuits, 2nd Ed., p. 20]</ref>  Losev was the first to exploit negative resistance diodes practically; he realized that they could serve as simpler, cheaper replacements for [[vacuum tube]]s.<ref name=\"ssd2004\"/> He used these junctions to build solid-state versions of [[electronic amplifier|amplifiers]], [[oscillator]]s, and TRF and [[regenerative radio receiver]]s, at frequencies up to 5&nbsp;MHz, 25 years before the transistor.<ref name=\"Lee2\"/> He even built a [[superheterodyne receiver]].<ref name=\"Lee2\"/>  However his achievements were overlooked because of the success of [[vacuum tube]] technology. The Soviet authorities did not support him, and zincite crystals were hard to come by because they had to be imported from the United States. After ten years he abandoned research into this technology (dubbed \"Crystodyne\" by [[Hugo Gernsback]]),<ref name=\"Gernsback\" /> and it was forgotten.<ref name=\"Lee2\" />\n\nNegative resistance in diodes was rediscovered in 1956 in the [[tunnel diode]], and today negative resistance diodes like the [[Gunn diode]] and [[IMPATT diode]] are used in microwave oscillators and amplifiers and are some of the most widely used sources of [[microwave]]s.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oleg Losev}}\n*[http://russianpatentsblog.patentsfromru.com/2007/04/12/youd-better-not-ignore-russian-prior-art-search-says-new-scientist-magazine/ Facsimile of \"Light Relay\" and other Oleg Losev's patents] \u2013 from [[Russian Patents blog]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Losev, Oleg Vladimirovich}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Russian physicists]]\n[[Category:Russian inventors]]\n[[Category:Light-emitting diode pioneers]]\n[[Category:Russian electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:Soviet physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century physicists]]\n[[Category:People from Tver]]\n[[Category:20th-century inventors]]\n", "name_user": "Ikjbagl", "label": "safe", "comment": "removing unnecessary comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oleg_Losev"}
{"title_page": "Ptychadena subpunctata", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| status = LC | status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn |authors= IUCN SSC Amphibian Specialist Group|title= ''Ptychadena subpunctata'' |year= 2013|page= e.T58527A18402011 |accessdate= 17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| taxon = Ptychadena subpunctata\n| authority = ([[Jose Vicente Barboza du Bocage|Bocage]], 1866)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\n'''''Ptychadena subpunctata''''' is a species of [[frog]] in the family [[Ptychadenidae]].\nIt is found in [[Angola]], [[Botswana]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Namibia]], [[Zambia]], and [[Zimbabwe]].\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are dry [[savanna]], moist savanna, [[river]]s, [[swamp]]s, freshwater [[lake]]s, and freshwater [[marsh]]es.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ptychadena}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2246210}}\n\n[[Category:Ptychadena]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:Amphibians described in 1866]]\n\n\n{{amphibian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| status = LC | status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn |authors= |title= '''' |year= 2016|page= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n| taxon = Ptychadena subpunctata\n| authority = ([[Jose Vicente Barboza du Bocage|Bocage]], 1866)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\n'''''Ptychadena subpunctata''''' is a species of [[frog]] in the family [[Ptychadenidae]].\nIt is found in [[Angola]], [[Botswana]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Namibia]], [[Zambia]], and [[Zimbabwe]].\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are dry [[savanna]], moist savanna, [[river]]s, [[swamp]]s, freshwater [[lake]]s, and freshwater [[marsh]]es.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Poynton, J.C. & Channing, A. 2004.  [https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/58527/all Ptychadena subpunctata].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ]  Downloaded on 23 July 2007.\n{{Ptychadena}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2246210}}\n\n[[Category:Ptychadena]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:Amphibians described in 1866]]\n\n\n{{amphibian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IUCN citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ptychadena_subpunctata"}
{"title_page": "Feminist Women's Health Center (Atlanta, Georgia)", "text_new": "The '''Feminist Women's Health Center''' of Atlanta is a [[Feminist Health Centers|feminist health center]] that provides comprehensive gynecological health care, engages in community outreach, and advocates for reproductive justice. Kwajelyn Jackson has been executive director since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/updates/kwajelyn-bio/|title=Kwajelyn Jackson, New Executive Director {{!}} Feminist Women's Health Center|last=Gole|first=Anushka|date=2018-05-18|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center (FWHC) was founded in 1977. Like many other feminist health centers, the Atlanta FWHC was born out of self-help groups, where women learned to examine their own cervixes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.feministcenter.org/about-fwhc/mission-history-values |title= History, Mission, and Values |publisher= Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta, GA |accessdate= May 6, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120528020000/http://www.feministcenter.org/about-fwhc/mission-history-values |archive-date= May 28, 2012 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nToday, the Atlanta Feminist Women's Health Center is one of several extant feminist health centers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhrealitycheck.org/blog/2009/12/21/interview-feminist-abortion-network|title=An Interview With the Feminist Abortion Network|author=Amie Newman|date=December 21, 2009|publisher=RH Reality Check|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> \n\n=== Early member of Federation of Feminist Women\u2019s Health Centers ===\nThe Atlanta Feminist Women's Health Center was a member clinic of the Federation of Feminist Women's Health Centers (FFWHC). The Federation of Feminist Women's Health Centers originated in Los Angeles, and subsequently member clinics opened throughout California and eventually other parts of the country, including Tallahassee, Florida and Atlanta, Georgia. [[Women's health movement in the United States|Women's health movement]] historian Sandra Morgen notes, \"Until the National Black Women's Health Project\u2026 in the 1980s, the FFWHC was the only multiple-site group in the larger women's health movement.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Into Our Own Hands: The Women's Health Movement in the United States, 1969-1990. |last= Morgen |first=Sandra |year=2002 |page= 99|publisher=Rutgers University Press |location=New Brunswick, NJ |isbn= 978-0813530710}}</ref> All member clinics provided abortion and gynecological health care, and worked together to \"espouse a unified ideology and identifiable politics.\"<ref>Morgen, 100.</ref>\n\nThe FFWHC member clinics stood out from others in the women's health movement because they adopted a more hierarchal model when other feminist clinics were operating as collectives. The debate and dispute over the FFWHC's mode of operation reached a point where some women's health centers refused to refer clients to FFWHC clinics for abortions. In 1990, [[Carol Downer]], founder of the Los Angeles FWHC and leader in the women's health movement, responded to the controversy: \"Most of the criticisms I've heard revolve around hierarchy\u2026 I might say it was the difference between being organized and disorganized\u2026 It's hard for me to understand why anyone who goes into a political arena doesn't want to be as organized as they can possibly be\u2026 if you really are serious about what you are doing. Because otherwise you are the mercy of these larger forces which are organized.\" <ref>Morgen, 104.</ref>\n\nA few years after moving their headquarters to Eugene, Oregon,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WUZWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=duoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3252,562948&dq=feminist+health+centers&hl=en |title= Feminist federation moving to Eugene |author= Joe Rojas-Burke|date= September 3, 1993 |pages= 1\u20134C |publisher= |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}\n</ref> the costs of operating the FFWHC offices proved too expensive. Although the member clinics stay in touch, they are no longer formally connected as a federation.<ref>Morgen, 105.</ref> However, most of these clinics, including the Atlanta FWHC, are now part of a new consortium of women's health care providers, the [[Feminist Abortion Network]].\n\n==Health Services==\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center offers a variety of sexual and reproductive health care programs, many of which are designed to reach historically underserved populations within the Atlanta community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gsusignal.com/news/atlanta-based-health-center-for-women-hosts-annual-fundraiser-1.1948349#.T6vLXJ9Ysug |title=Atlanta-based health center for women hosts annual fundraiser |author=Gaurav Bhatia |date=October 19, 2008 |publisher=The Signal: The Official Student Newspaper of Georgia State University |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> In addition to providing comprehensive gynecological services, the center also offers a donor insemination program and the Trans Health Initiative.\n\n=== Abortion care ===\nFWHC provides both surgical and medication abortions in their Atlanta clinic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/abortion-care/|title=Abortion Care|last=Barba|first=Pamela|date=2018-02-13|website=Feminist Women's Health Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In 2017 and 2018, FWHC served 3,867 patients with abortion care, including patients surviving trauma and dealing with fetal anomalies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Feminist_Center-Impact_Report_2017-2018-Digital.pdf|title=Impact Report 2017-2018|last=Feminist Women\u2019s Health Center|first=|date=2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n=== Sexual health and wellness ===\nFWHC offers affordable annual wellness exams, pregnancy testing, miscarriage care, birth control and emergency contraception options, sexually transmitted infection screening and treatment, and HIV testing and counseling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/sexual-health-and-wellness/|title=Sexual Health and Wellness|last=Barba|first=Pamela|date=2018-02-15|website=Feminist Women's Health Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In 2017 and 2018, FWHC provided these services to 1,074 patients.\u00a0<ref name=\":0\" />\n===Trans Health Initiative===\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center began offering health services to transmasculine individuals in 2000. The Trans Health Initiative was founded in the memory of Robert Eads, a partially transitioned [[trans man]] who died of ovarian cancer at the age of 53 after being denied medical care.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheissuesmagazine.com/2009summer/2009summer_Bader.php |title= Trans Health Care Is A Life and Death Matter |author= Eleanor J. Bader |date= Summer 2009 |publisher= On The Issues Magazine |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}\n</ref>\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center first offered low-cost gynecological services to trans men at the annual [[Southern Comfort Conference]], and continue to offer services at the conference as the Robert Eads Clinic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.feministcenter.org/health-wellness-services/trans-health-initiative/robert-eads-health-project-fair|title=Robert Eads Health Project Fair|publisher=Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta|accessdate=May 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528020508/http://www.feministcenter.org/health-wellness-services/trans-health-initiative/robert-eads-health-project-fair|archive-date=May 28, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Clinic saw more and more patients each year, and in June 2008, the FWHC began offering services to trans men year-round through the Trans Health Initiative.<ref>Bader.</ref>\n\nThe Trans Health Initiative serves clients throughout the Southeast. Many of the clinic's clients have traveled across state lines because there is no trans-friendly health care provider in their own state. In addition to providing their clients with non-judgmental health care, the Trans Health Initiative is also working to educate the medical community about transgender health.<ref>Bader.</ref>\n\n===Donor Insemination===\n\nThe donor insemination program began at the Feminist Women's Health Center in 1988. The program began because most infertility specialists in the southern United States were only willing to offer their services to married women, leaving single heterosexual women and lesbians alike unable to access fertility treatments.<ref>{{cite news|author=Maureen Downey|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19900307&id=mbAeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oc4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6663,2631777|title=Clinic Helps Unmarried Southerners Have Babies|date=March 7, 1990|newspaper=Herald-Tribune|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> When the FWHC began offering its donor insemination services, it was only one of about a dozen clinics in the entire country to offer these services. In a 1990 profile of the program, an employee of the center noted that only about 5% of the women seeking donor insemination were married, and about a third of the program's clients were lesbians.<ref>Downey.</ref> In 2012, about 90% of clients identified as lesbians. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thegavoice.com/community/inside-georgias-and-americas-gayby-boom/|title=Inside Georgia\u2019s (and America\u2019s) Gayby Boom|date=2012-11-09|website=Georgia Voice - Gay & LGBT Atlanta News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, with fertility services and clinics more widely available, FWHC ended the donor insemination program to refocus efforts and resources on other services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Feminist-Center-Timeline.pdf|title=Feminist Center Timeline|last=Feminist Women's Health Center|first=|date=2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== Legislative Advocacy ==\nFeminist Women\u2019s Health Center has formally advocated for legal access to abortion and healthcare at the local and state level for more than 20 years. FWHC engages a full-time lobbyist at the state Capitol, mobilizes community members for action alerts, coordinates advocacy days where volunteers can learn about the politics of reproductive justice and lobby their state legislators,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.feministcenter.org/advocacy/take-action/advocacy-days-at-the-state-capitol|title=Advocacy Days at the State Capitol|publisher=Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528013617/http://www.feministcenter.org/advocacy/take-action/advocacy-days-at-the-state-capitol|archive-date=May 28, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> and educates on laws relevant to reproductive justice and legislative process, including voter engagement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/legislative-advocacy-program/|title=Legislative Advocacy Program|last=Barba|first=Pamela|date=2018-02-15|website=Feminist Women's Health Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Lawsuit challenging Georgia abortion ban ===\nDuring the 2019-2020 legislative session, the Georgia House and Senate passed House Bill 481, fetal heartbeat bill to effectively ban abortion in the state, and one of the most restrictive anti-abortion measures in the United States. In May 2019,\u202f Governor [[Brian Kemp]] signed [[Georgia House Bill 481|HB 481]] to go into effect January 1, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legis.ga.gov/Legislation/en-US/display/20192020/HB/481|title=HB\u00a0481\u00a02019-2020 Regular Session|website=www.legis.ga.gov|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\nThat June, Feminist Women\u2019s Health Center partnered with the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], [[Center for Reproductive Rights]], [[Planned Parenthood]] and other reproductive justice organizations to file SisterSong v. Kemp in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia]] to challenge the constitutionality of the ban. Judge Steve C. Jones ruled in favor of the plaintiffs, granting an injunction preventing the ban from being enforced in January 2020, as the case continues to move through the courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/federal-judge-blocks-georgia-anti-abortion-law/yh1ttzbYdTcqiUT7OkyqkO/|title=Federal judge blocks Georgia anti-abortion law|last=Maya T. Prabhu|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Walk in My Shoes, Hear Our Voice ===\nOn March 12, 2012, the Feminist Women's Health Center organized a protest at the Georgia State Capitol, along with a wide range coalition partners that included ACLU \u2013 Georgia and [[SisterSong Women of Color Reproductive Justice Collective|SisterSong Reproductive Justice Collective.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hearourvoice.org/|title=Sponsors|publisher=HearOurVoice.org|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsatlanta.com/story/17137955/walk-in-my-shoes-hear-our-voice-protest-at-the-capitol|title='Walk in My Shoes, Hear Our Voice' Protest at the Capitol|author=Jennifer Banks|date=March 12, 2012|work=CBS Atlanta|publisher=WGCL-TV|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415152039/http://www.cbsatlanta.com/story/17137955/walk-in-my-shoes-hear-our-voice-protest-at-the-capitol|archive-date=April 15, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> The protest was in response to a spate of legislation that would restrict Georgia women's access to reproductive health care, ranging from religious exemptions for birth control coverage to a twenty-week abortion ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentmail.com/news/2012/mar/12/crowds-protest-ga-abortion-birth-control-bills/|title=Crowds protest Ga. abortion, birth control bills|author=Associated Press|date=March 12, 2012|publisher=Independent Mail of Anderson, SC|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126004921/http://www.independentmail.com/news/2012/mar/12/crowds-protest-ga-abortion-birth-control-bills/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsbtv.com/videos/news/protesters-rally-against-abortion-bill/vGXKt/|title=Protestors rally against abortion bill|date=March 12, 2012|publisher=WSBTV|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}\n</ref> Over five hundred people showed up to the protest,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hearourvoice.org/media-release-walk-in-my-shoes-hear-our-voice/|title=Media Release \u2013 Over 500 Georgians Marched @ Walk in My Shoes, Hear Our Voice|author=Jaime Chandra|date=March 12, 2012|publisher=HearOurVoice.org|accessdate=May 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-761439|title=Georgia Women Rock the State House|author=prplbuslady|date=March 13, 2012|publisher=CNN iReport|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> which was organized around the principles that women have a right to:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hearourvoice.org/organizing-principle/|title=Organizing Principle|author=SisterSong Reproductive Justice Collective|publisher=HearOurVoice.org|accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n* determine when and whether to have children,\n* have a healthy pregnancy and birth;\n* become a parent and parent with dignity, and\n* have safe and healthy relationships and families.\n\n==Community Engagement==\n\nLike other feminist health centers,<ref>Morgen, 237</ref> Feminist Women's Health Center recognizes that access to health care is closely linked with politics and other social factors. As a result, FWHC has a community engagement and advocacy department in addition to providing health care at their clinic. FWHC's community engagement transpires through a variety of programs. The clinic engages volunteers and hosts a reproductive justice book club, in addition to key programs, the Lifting Latinx Voices initiative and the Errin J. Vuley Fellows Program.\n\nThe Lifting Latinx Voices Initiative, a health outreach program that strives to empower and educate the Latinx community in addition to addressing health disparities that impact Latinx people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.feministcenter.org/community-education/lifting-latina-voices-initiative |title=Lifting Latina Voices Initiative |publisher=Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta |accessdate=May 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528020256/http://www.feministcenter.org/community-education/lifting-latina-voices-initiative |archive-date=May 28, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFGecjhavPM |title=Lifting Latina Voices |author=To2 Network |date=December 14, 2011 |publisher= YouTube |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Using the community leadership model of promotores de salud from Latin American countries, the initiative offers open and safe spaces to discuss reproductive health and address specific needs and barriers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.welcomingamerica.org/sites/default/files/WA_Health%20White%20Paper_D.pdf|title=Pursuing Health Equity through Welcoming Work|last=Mayer|first=M.|last2=Driver|first2=J.|date=2016|website=Welcoming America|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Errin J. Vuley Fellows Program was launched in 2017 to support community leaders in building skills and knowledge through a reproductive justice framework. Named for FWHC\u2019s first community engagement coordinator,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://atlantaprogressivenews.com/2009/11/19/errin-vuley-1974-2009-presente/|title=Errin Vuley, 1974-2009, Presente! {{!}} Atlanta Progressive News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> the fellowship focuses especially on Vuley\u2019s advocacy for abortion access, trans justice and racial justice. Through monthly workshops and retreats, fellows learn from each other and community organizations, setting them up for futures in movement work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aafront.org/black-history-month-interview-with-kwajelyn-jackson/|title=Black History Month Interview With Kwajelyn Jackson \u2022 Abortion Access Front|last=Blogger|first=LPJL|date=2019-02-15|website=Abortion Access Front|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Black Women\u2019s Health Imperative|Black Women's Health Imperative]], formerly the National Black Women's Health Project\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Feminist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Abortion-rights organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Health centers]]\n[[Category:Clinics in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Feminist Women's Health Center''' of Atlanta is a [[Feminist Health Centers|feminist health center]] that provides comprehensive gynecological health care, engages in community outreach, and advocates for reproductive justice. Kwajelyn Jackson has been executive director since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/updates/kwajelyn-bio/|title=Kwajelyn Jackson, New Executive Director {{!}} Feminist Women's Health Center|last=Gole|first=Anushka|date=2018-05-18|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center (FWHC) was founded in 1977. Like many other feminist health centers, the Atlanta FWHC was born out of self-help groups, where women learned to examine their own cervixes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.feministcenter.org/about-fwhc/mission-history-values |title= History, Mission, and Values |publisher= Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta, GA |accessdate= May 6, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120528020000/http://www.feministcenter.org/about-fwhc/mission-history-values |archive-date= May 28, 2012 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nToday, the Atlanta Feminist Women's Health Center is one of several extant feminist health centers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhrealitycheck.org/blog/2009/12/21/interview-feminist-abortion-network|title=An Interview With the Feminist Abortion Network|author=Amie Newman|date=December 21, 2009|publisher=RH Reality Check|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> \n\n=== Early member of Federation of Feminist Women\u2019s Health Centers ===\nThe Atlanta Feminist Women's Health Center was a member clinic of the Federation of Feminist Women's Health Centers (FFWHC). The Federation of Feminist Women's Health Centers originated in Los Angeles, and subsequently member clinics opened throughout California and eventually other parts of the country, including Tallahassee, Florida and Atlanta, Georgia. [[Women's health movement in the United States|Women's health movement]] historian Sandra Morgen notes, \"Until the National Black Women's Health Project\u2026 in the 1980s, the FFWHC was the only multiple-site group in the larger women's health movement.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Into Our Own Hands: The Women's Health Movement in the United States, 1969-1990. |last= Morgen |first=Sandra |year=2002 |page= 99|publisher=Rutgers University Press |location=New Brunswick, NJ |isbn= 978-0813530710}}</ref> All member clinics provided abortion and gynecological health care, and worked together to \"espouse a unified ideology and identifiable politics.\"<ref>Morgen, 100.</ref>\n\nThe FFWHC member clinics stood out from others in the women's health movement because they adopted a more hierarchal model when other feminist clinics were operating as collectives. The debate and dispute over the FFWHC's mode of operation reached a point where some women's health centers refused to refer clients to FFWHC clinics for abortions. In 1990, [[Carol Downer]], founder of the Los Angeles FWHC and leader in the women's health movement, responded to the controversy: \"Most of the criticisms I've heard revolve around hierarchy\u2026 I might say it was the difference between being organized and disorganized\u2026 It's hard for me to understand why anyone who goes into a political arena doesn't want to be as organized as they can possibly be\u2026 if you really are serious about what you are doing. Because otherwise you are the mercy of these larger forces which are organized.\" <ref>Morgen, 104.</ref>\n\nA few years after moving their headquarters to Eugene, Oregon,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WUZWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=duoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3252,562948&dq=feminist+health+centers&hl=en |title= Feminist federation moving to Eugene |author= Joe Rojas-Burke|date= September 3, 1993 |pages= 1\u20134C |publisher= |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}\n</ref> the costs of operating the FFWHC offices proved too expensive. Although the member clinics stay in touch, they are no longer formally connected as a federation.<ref>Morgen, 105.</ref> However, most of these clinics, including the Atlanta FWHC, are now part of a new consortium of women's health care providers, the [[Feminist Abortion Network]].\n\n==Health Services==\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center offers a variety of sexual and reproductive health care programs, many of which are designed to reach historically underserved populations within the Atlanta community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gsusignal.com/news/atlanta-based-health-center-for-women-hosts-annual-fundraiser-1.1948349#.T6vLXJ9Ysug |title=Atlanta-based health center for women hosts annual fundraiser |author=Gaurav Bhatia |date=October 19, 2008 |publisher=The Signal: The Official Student Newspaper of Georgia State University |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> In addition to providing comprehensive gynecological services, the center also offers a donor insemination program and the Trans Health Initiative.\n\n=== Abortion care ===\nFWHC provides both surgical and medication abortions in their Atlanta clinic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/abortion-care/|title=Abortion Care|last=Barba|first=Pamela|date=2018-02-13|website=Feminist Women's Health Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In 2017 and 2018, FWHC served 3,867 patients with abortion care, including patients surviving trauma and dealing with fetal anomalies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Feminist_Center-Impact_Report_2017-2018-Digital.pdf|title=Impact Report 2017-2018|last=Feminist Women\u2019s Health Center|first=|date=2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n=== Sexual health and wellness ===\nFWHC offers affordable annual wellness exams, pregnancy testing, miscarriage care, birth control and emergency contraception options, sexually transmitted infection screening and treatment, and HIV testing and counseling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/sexual-health-and-wellness/|title=Sexual Health and Wellness|last=Barba|first=Pamela|date=2018-02-15|website=Feminist Women's Health Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In 2017 and 2018, FWHC provided these services to 1,074 patients.\u00a0<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n===Donor Insemination===\n\nThe donor insemination program began at the Feminist Women's Health Center in 1988. The program began because most infertility specialists in the southern United States were only willing to offer their services to married women, leaving single heterosexual women and lesbians alike unable to access fertility treatments.<ref>{{cite news |title= Clinic Helps Unmarried Southerners Have Babies |author= Maureen Downey |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19900307&id=mbAeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oc4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6663,2631777 |newspaper= Herald-Tribune |date= March 7, 1990 |accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> When the FWHC began offering its donor insemination services, it was only one of about a dozen clinics in the entire country to offer these services. In a 1990 profile of the program, an employee of the center noted that only about 5% of the women seeking donor insemination were married, and about a third of the program's clients were lesbians.<ref>Downey.</ref> In 2012, about 90% of clients identified as lesbians. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thegavoice.com/community/inside-georgias-and-americas-gayby-boom/|title=Inside Georgia\u2019s (and America\u2019s) Gayby Boom|date=2012-11-09|website=Georgia Voice - Gay & LGBT Atlanta News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, with fertility services and clinics more widely available, FWHC ended the donor insemination program to refocus efforts and resources on other services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Feminist-Center-Timeline.pdf|title=Feminist Center Timeline|last=Feminist Women's Health Center|first=|date=2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n===Trans Health Initiative===\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center began offering health services to transmasculine individuals in 2000. The Trans Health Initiative was founded in the memory of Robert Eads, a partially transitioned [[trans man]] who died of ovarian cancer at the age of 53 after being denied medical care.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheissuesmagazine.com/2009summer/2009summer_Bader.php |title= Trans Health Care Is A Life and Death Matter |author= Eleanor J. Bader |date= Summer 2009 |publisher= On The Issues Magazine |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}\n</ref>\n\nThe Feminist Women's Health Center first offered low-cost gynecological services to trans men at the annual [[Southern Comfort Conference]], and continue to offer services at the conference as the Robert Eads Clinic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.feministcenter.org/health-wellness-services/trans-health-initiative/robert-eads-health-project-fair|title=Robert Eads Health Project Fair|publisher=Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta|accessdate=May 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528020508/http://www.feministcenter.org/health-wellness-services/trans-health-initiative/robert-eads-health-project-fair|archive-date=May 28, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Clinic saw more and more patients each year, and in June 2008, the FWHC began offering services to trans men year-round through the Trans Health Initiative.<ref>Bader.</ref>\n\nThe Trans Health Initiative serves clients throughout the Southeast. Many of the clinic's clients have traveled across state lines because there is no trans-friendly health care provider in their own state. In addition to providing their clients with non-judgmental health care, the Trans Health Initiative is also working to educate the medical community about transgender health.<ref>Bader.</ref>\n\n== Legislative Advocacy ==\nFeminist Women\u2019s Health Center has formally advocated for legal access to abortion and healthcare at the local and state level for more than 20 years. FWHC engages a full-time lobbyist at the state Capitol, mobilizes community members for action alerts, coordinates advocacy days where volunteers can learn about the politics of reproductive justice and lobby their state legislators,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.feministcenter.org/advocacy/take-action/advocacy-days-at-the-state-capitol|title=Advocacy Days at the State Capitol|publisher=Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528013617/http://www.feministcenter.org/advocacy/take-action/advocacy-days-at-the-state-capitol|archive-date=May 28, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> and educates on laws relevant to reproductive justice and legislative process, including voter engagement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministcenter.org/legislative-advocacy-program/|title=Legislative Advocacy Program|last=Barba|first=Pamela|date=2018-02-15|website=Feminist Women's Health Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Lawsuit challenging Georgia abortion ban ===\nDuring the 2019-2020 legislative session, the Georgia House and Senate passed House Bill 481, fetal heartbeat bill to effectively ban abortion in the state, and one of the most restrictive anti-abortion measures in the United States. In May 2019,\u202f Governor [[Brian Kemp]] signed [[Georgia House Bill 481|HB 481]] to go into effect January 1, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legis.ga.gov/Legislation/en-US/display/20192020/HB/481|title=HB\u00a0481\u00a02019-2020 Regular Session|website=www.legis.ga.gov|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\nThat June, Feminist Women\u2019s Health Center partnered with the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], [[Center for Reproductive Rights]], [[Planned Parenthood]] and other reproductive justice organizations to file SisterSong v. Kemp in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia]] to challenge the constitutionality of the ban. Judge Steve C. Jones ruled in favor of the plaintiffs, granting an injunction preventing the ban from being enforced in January 2020, as the case continues to move through the courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/federal-judge-blocks-georgia-anti-abortion-law/yh1ttzbYdTcqiUT7OkyqkO/|title=Federal judge blocks Georgia anti-abortion law|last=Maya T. Prabhu|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Walk in My Shoes, Hear Our Voice ===\nOn March 12, 2012, the Feminist Women's Health Center organized a protest at the Georgia State Capitol, along with a wide range coalition partners that included ACLU \u2013 Georgia and [[SisterSong Women of Color Reproductive Justice Collective|SisterSong Reproductive Justice Collective.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hearourvoice.org/|title=Sponsors|publisher=HearOurVoice.org|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsatlanta.com/story/17137955/walk-in-my-shoes-hear-our-voice-protest-at-the-capitol|title='Walk in My Shoes, Hear Our Voice' Protest at the Capitol|author=Jennifer Banks|date=March 12, 2012|work=CBS Atlanta|publisher=WGCL-TV|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415152039/http://www.cbsatlanta.com/story/17137955/walk-in-my-shoes-hear-our-voice-protest-at-the-capitol|archive-date=April 15, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> The protest was in response to a spate of legislation that would restrict Georgia women's access to reproductive health care, ranging from religious exemptions for birth control coverage to a twenty-week abortion ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentmail.com/news/2012/mar/12/crowds-protest-ga-abortion-birth-control-bills/|title=Crowds protest Ga. abortion, birth control bills|author=Associated Press|date=March 12, 2012|publisher=Independent Mail of Anderson, SC|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126004921/http://www.independentmail.com/news/2012/mar/12/crowds-protest-ga-abortion-birth-control-bills/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsbtv.com/videos/news/protesters-rally-against-abortion-bill/vGXKt/|title=Protestors rally against abortion bill|date=March 12, 2012|publisher=WSBTV|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}\n</ref> Over five hundred people showed up to the protest,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hearourvoice.org/media-release-walk-in-my-shoes-hear-our-voice/|title=Media Release \u2013 Over 500 Georgians Marched @ Walk in My Shoes, Hear Our Voice|author=Jaime Chandra|date=March 12, 2012|publisher=HearOurVoice.org|accessdate=May 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-761439|title=Georgia Women Rock the State House|author=prplbuslady|date=March 13, 2012|publisher=CNN iReport|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> which was organized around the principles that women have a right to:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hearourvoice.org/organizing-principle/|title=Organizing Principle|author=SisterSong Reproductive Justice Collective|publisher=HearOurVoice.org|accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n* determine when and whether to have children,\n* have a healthy pregnancy and birth;\n* become a parent and parent with dignity, and\n* have safe and healthy relationships and families.\n\n==Community Engagement==\n\nLike other feminist health centers,<ref>Morgen, 237</ref> Feminist Women's Health Center recognizes that access to health care is closely linked with politics and other social factors. As a result, FWHC has a community engagement and advocacy department in addition to providing health care at their clinic. FWHC's community engagement transpires through a variety of programs. The clinic engages volunteers and hosts a reproductive justice book club, in addition to key programs, the Lifting Latinx Voices initiative and the Errin J. Vuley Fellows Program.\n\nThe Lifting Latinx Voices Initiative, a health outreach program that strives to empower and educate the Latinx community in addition to addressing health disparities that impact Latinx people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.feministcenter.org/community-education/lifting-latina-voices-initiative |title=Lifting Latina Voices Initiative |publisher=Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta |accessdate=May 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528020256/http://www.feministcenter.org/community-education/lifting-latina-voices-initiative |archive-date=May 28, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFGecjhavPM |title=Lifting Latina Voices |author=To2 Network |date=December 14, 2011 |publisher= YouTube |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Using the community leadership model of promotores de salud from Latin American countries, the initiative offers open and safe spaces to discuss reproductive health and address specific needs and barriers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.welcomingamerica.org/sites/default/files/WA_Health%20White%20Paper_D.pdf|title=Pursuing Health Equity through Welcoming Work|last=Mayer|first=M.|last2=Driver|first2=J.|date=2016|website=Welcoming America|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Errin J. Vuley Fellows Program was launched in 2017 to support community leaders in building skills and knowledge through a reproductive justice framework. Named for FWHC\u2019s first community engagement coordinator,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://atlantaprogressivenews.com/2009/11/19/errin-vuley-1974-2009-presente/|title=Errin Vuley, 1974-2009, Presente! {{!}} Atlanta Progressive News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> the fellowship focuses especially on Vuley\u2019s advocacy for abortion access, trans justice and racial justice. Through monthly workshops and retreats, fellows learn from each other and community organizations, setting them up for futures in movement work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aafront.org/black-history-month-interview-with-kwajelyn-jackson/|title=Black History Month Interview With Kwajelyn Jackson \u2022 Abortion Access Front|last=Blogger|first=LPJL|date=2019-02-15|website=Abortion Access Front|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Black Women\u2019s Health Imperative|Black Women's Health Imperative]], formerly the National Black Women's Health Project\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Feminist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Abortion-rights organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Health centers]]\n[[Category:Clinics in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Bettitor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHealth Services:Reordered sub-sections to list active programs first", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feminist_Women%27s_Health_Center_(Atlanta,_Georgia)"}
{"title_page": "Montego Bay (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Montego Bay\n| cover      = Montego_Bay_-_Bobby_Bloom.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bobby Bloom]]\n| album      = The Bobby Bloom Album\n| B-side     = Try a Little Harder\n| released   = September 1970 <small>(U.S.)</small>\n| format     = 45 RPM 7\"\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = Pop, Soul, Calypso\n| length     = \n| label      = L&R Records\n| writer     = [[Jeff Barry]], Bobby Bloom\n| producer   = Jeff Barry\n| prev_title = Sign of the V\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = Make Me Happy\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n'''\"Montego Bay\"''' is a [[song]] [[songwriter|co-written]] and performed by [[Bobby Bloom]] about the [[Montego Bay|city in Jamaica of the same name]]. The song was a [[Top 40|Top 10]] [[hit record|hit]] for Bloom in the Fall of 1970 on both sides of the Atlantic. It reached #3 on the UK Singles Chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/montego-bay/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1970-08-29 |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref> #5 on the Canadian ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM 100]]'' Singles Chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.3723&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=msnvgu5v4a643al8ugim1ea684 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref> #7 on the Australian Go-Set Singles Chart and #8 on the US Billboard Hot 100. The song was [[songwriter|co-written]] and [[record producer|produced]] by [[Jeff Barry]]. In the master tape of the song, Bloom breaks into a chorus of \"[[Oh, What a Beautiful Mornin']]\" at the end of the recording, but the single version fades out before that. Apparently, that was done to avoid paying royalties for use of the [[Rodgers & Hammerstein]] song, though the full version does appear on the ''Bobby Bloom Album'' and has received frequent airplay. The song features a whistler, as well as Jamaican instruments to illustrate the section called \"Montego Bay,\" in a Calypso genre.\n\nBloom's recording of the song appeared in the 1997 film ''[[The Ice Storm (film)|The Ice Storm]].''\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n|-\n|Australia ([[Go-Set]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' Adult Contemporary<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.0156&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.0156.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.0156|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1980-05-17 |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.3723&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=msnvgu5v4a643al8ugim1ea684 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|14|song=Montego Bay|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}\n|-\n|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qsongid=2524#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 14 December 1970]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: