.biote.v17n1.50709 |publisher=Revista Colombiana de Biotecnolog\u00eda |language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Losada A.\">{{Cite journal |last=Losada A. |first=Pablo |date=2016 |title=Inclusi\u00f3n de torta de Cacay (Caryodendron orinocense) en la degradaci\u00f3n in vitro in situ de la materia seca |url=https://repository.udca.edu.co/handle/11158/552 |publisher=[[University of Applied and Environmental Sciences]] |language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Garcia Urrea\">{{Cite journal |last1=Garcia Urrea |first1=Lili Johanna |last2=Martinez Tamara |first2=Ferney Eduardo |date=2017 |title=El Cacay en bebidas funcionales y su uso gastron\u00f3mico |url=http://repositorio.uniagustiniana.edu.co/handle/123456789/401 |publisher=Universitaria Agustiniana |language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Padilla\">{{Cite journal |last1=Padilla |first1=F.C. |last2=Alfaro |first2=M.J. |last3=Ch\u00e1vez |first3=J.F.|date=1998 |title=Composici\u00f3n qu\u00edmica de las semillas del nogal de Barquisimeto (Caryodendron orinocense, euphorbiaceae)  |url=https://doi.org/10.1177%2F108201329800400407 |publisher=[[Journal of Food Science and Technology]] |language=es }} </ref>\n\n<ref name=\"P\u00e9rez\">{{Cite book |last1=P\u00e9rez |first1=M.N.  |last2=Alfaro |first2=M. de J. |last3=Padilla |first3=F.C. |date=2001 |title=Evaluation of \u2019Nuez de Barinas\u2019 (Caryodendron Orinocense) Oil for Possible Use in Cosmetic  |url=https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1467-2494.1999.196565.x |publisher=International Journal of Cosmetic Science}} </ref>\n\n<ref name=\"FAO\">{{Cite book |date=1987 |title=Especies forestales productoras de frutas y otros alimentos 3. Ejemplos de America Latina  |url=http://www.fao.org/publications/card/es/c/ff69b89d-bece-55ee-b04d-e889893e9880/ | publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization|Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations]] |language=es }} </ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Jim\u00e9nez\">{{Cite book |last1=Jim\u00e9nez |first1=Luis Carlos  |last2=Yesid Bernal |first2=Henry |date=1992 |title=El \"inchi\", Caryodendron orinocense Karsten (Euphorbiaceae): la oleaginosa mas promisoria de la subregion andina |series=2nd |url=https://www.si.edu/object/siris_sil_496276 |publisher=Programa de Recursos Vegetales del Convenio Andres Bello|language=es }} </ref>\n\n<ref name=\"UNAL\">{{Cite web | url=http://catalogoplantasdecolombia.unal.edu.co/es/resultados/especie/Caryodendron%20orinocense/ | title=Cat\u00e1logo de Plantas y L\u00edquenes de Colombia  | access-date=11 November 2019 | website=catalogoplantasdecolombia.unal.edu.co | publisher= [[National University of Colombia]] |language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IUCN-Redlist\">{{Cite journal | url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2019-2.RLTS.T145669319A145669321.en | title=Botanic Gardens Conservation International (BGCI) & IUCN SSC Global Tree Specialist Group 2019. Caryodendron orinocense.  | access-date=13 November 2019 | publisher= [[IUCN Red List]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Orduz\">{{Cite book |last1=Orduz R. |first1=Javier Orlando  |last2=Rangel M. |first2=Jorge Alberto|date=2002 |title=Frutales Tropicales Potentiales para el Piedmonte Llanero |url=http://hdl.handle.net/20.500.12324/13427 |publisher=Corporaci\u00f3n Colombiana de Investigaci\u00f3n Agropecuaria|language=es }} </ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GRIN\">{{Cite journal | url= http://wgb.cimmyt.org/gringlobal/taxonomyfamily.aspx?type=tribe&id=1976 | title=USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System |date=2019 | access-date=29 March 2020 |publisher= [[Germplasm Resources Information Network]] (GRIN-Taxonomy). National Germplasm Resources Laboratory, Beltsville, Maryland. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Instituto-Sinchi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sinchi.org.co/files/PUBLICACIONES%20DIGITALES/Fichas%20Tecnicas%20agroforestal/Fichas%20Tecnicas%20de%20Especies%20de%20uso%20Forestal%20y%20Agroforestal%20de%20la%20Amazonia%20Colombiana_28%20INCHI.pdf | title=Fichas Tecnicas de Especies de uso Forestal y Agroforestal de la Amazonia Colombiana: Inchi  | access-date=19 November 2019 | website=sinchi.org.co | publisher= Instituto Amaz\u00f3nico de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas \u00abSinchi\u00bb|language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CETEP\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/33378012/Nueza_criolla_Diagn%C3%B3stico_participativo_de_su_situaci%C3%B3n_en_el_estado_Lara_Venezuela|title=Nueza criolla, Diagn\u00f3stico participativo de su situaci\u00f3n en el estado Lara, Venezuela |last=Alzuru|first=Angel|date=September 2007|journal=Centro para la Gesti\u00f3n Tecnol\u00f3gica Popular (CETEP)|access-date=19 November 2019|doi=|pmid=|language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Pabon\">{{Cite book|last=Pabon E.|first=Miguel A.|enlaceautor=|title=Oleaginosas de la Amazon\u00eda: el inchi|url=http://hdl.handle.net/20.500.12324/29656|access-date=|date=1982|publisher=Corporaci\u00f3n Colombiana de Investigaci\u00f3n Agropecuaria|isbn=|editor=|ubicaci\u00f3n=|p\u00e1gina=|language=es}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Martinez\">{{Cite journal|url=http://hdl.handle.net/20.500.12324/15160|title=El inch\u00ed (Caryodendron orinocense Karst) |last=Mart\u00ednez S.|first=J.B. |journal=Corporaci\u00f3n Forestal de Nari\u00f1o|date=1979|language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Nieto\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.rngr.net/publications/ttsm/species/PDF.2003-12-03.2608/?searchterm=Caryodendron%20orinocense|title=El inch\u00ed (Caryodendron orinocense Karst) |last1=Nieto |first1=V.M. |last2=Rodriguez |first2=J. |journal=Tropical Tree Seed Manual - Species Descriptions }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Espinosa\">{{Cite book |last1=Espinosa |first1=Roc\u00edo |last2=L\u00f3pez |first2=Andr\u00e9s M. |title=Arboles nativos importantes para la conservaci\u00f3n de la biodiversidad: Propagaci\u00f3n y uso en paisajes cafeteros |url=http://hdl.handle.net/10778/1087 |access-date=23 November 2019 |date=2019 |isbn=978-958-8490-37-3| journal=Centro Nacional de Investigaciones de Cafe (Cenicaf\u00e9) |language=es}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Angulo-Ospina\">{{Cite journal | url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CA514617177&sid=googleScholar&v=2.1&it=r&linkaccess=abs&issn=01200739&p=IFME&sw=w|title=Crecimiento de cuarenta especies forestales nativas, aptas para restauraci\u00f3n en la Orinoquia colombiana |last1=Angulo-Ospina |first1=Carlos Alberto |last2=Silva-Herrera |first2=Luis Jairo |date=2016 |journal=Colombia Forestal |volume=19 |issue=S1 |pages=15 |access-date=23 November 2019|doi=|pmid=|language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Cisneros Torres\">{{Cite journal |last1=Cisneros Torres |first1=Diana Evelin  |last2=D\u00edaz Hern\u00e1ndez |first2=Andrea Del Rosario |date=2006 |title=Obtenci\u00f3n de aceite de la nuez Caryodendron Orinocense originaria del Departamento del Caquet\u00e1 en la Planta Piloto de la Universidad de La Salle  |url=https://ciencia.lasalle.edu.co/ing_alimentos/92/ |publisher=[[La Salle University, Colombia|La Salle University]] |language=es}} </ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Garcia 2012\"> {{Cite journal |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281715882_Caracterizacion_de_la_viabilidad_de_semillas_de_inchi_Caryodendron_orinocense_Karsten_de_dos_procedencias |title=Caracterizaci\u00f3n de la viabilidad de semillas de inchi (Caryodendron orinocense Karsten) de dos procedencias |last1=Garc\u00eda|first1=Judith J. |last2=Basso|first2=Carmen |journal=Revista Cientifica UDO Agricola |volume=12 |date=2012|language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Garcia 2009\"> {{Cite journal|url=http://www.bioline.org.br/pdf?cg09094|title=Evaluaci\u00f3n de dos m\u00e9todos de propagaci\u00f3n asexual en inchi (Caryodendron orinocense Karsten) |last1=Garc\u00eda|first1=Judith J. |last2=Moratinos|first2=Humberto |last3=Perdomo|first3=Dinaba |publisher=[[Central University of Venezuela]] |date=2009|language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Geilfus\"> {{Cite journal |url=http://www.manioc.org/recherch/T11006 |title=El \u00e1rbol al servicio del agricultor: manual de agroforesteria para el desarrollo rural. Tome 2 |last1=Geilfus|first1=Frans |isbn=9977-57-174-0| publisher=[[ Centro Agron\u00f3mico Tropical de Investigaci\u00f3n y Ense\u00f1anza|Centro Agron\u00f3mico Tropical de Investigaci\u00f3n y Ense\u00f1anza (CATIE)]] |date=1994|language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Wang\"> {{Cite journal|url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.foodchem.2018.05.055|title=Sacha inchi (Plukenetia volubilis L.): Nutritional composition, biological activity, and uses. |last1=Wang|first1=Sunan |last2=Zhu|first2=Fan |last3=Yukio|first3=Kakuda | journal=Food Chemistry |volume=265 |pages=316-328 |date=2018 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"FAO-2\"> {{Cite journal|url=http://www.fao.org/ag/aga/agap/frg/agrofor1/Pound7.htm|title=Cultivos de Cobertura para la Agricultura Sostenible en Am\u00e9rica |last=Pound|first=Barry | publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization|Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations]]|access-date=29 March 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Reckin\">{{Cite journal|title=The Orinoconut - A promising tree crop for the Tropics |last=Reckin|first=J.|year=1983|journal=International Tree Crops Journal|volume=2|issue=2|pages=105\u2013119|doi=10.1080/01435698.1983.9752746}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Janick\">{{Cite book |last1=Janick |first1=Jules  |last2=Paull |first2= Robert E. |year=2008 |title=Encyclopedia of Fruit and Nuts  |editor=Cabi Publishing | isbn=978-0-85199-638-7 |pages=366\u2013368 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cjHCoMQNkcgC&dq=}} </ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Piedemonte\">{{Cite journal |last1=Kellogg |first1=James  |last2=Egbue |first2=Obi |date=May 2012 |title=Three-dimensional structural evolution and kinematics of the Piedemonte Llanero, Central Llanos foothills, Eastern Cordillera, Colombia |volume=39|pages=216-227|doi=10.1016/j.jsames.2012.04.012 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/241689024_Three-dimensional_structural_evolution_and_kinematics_of_the_Piedemonte_Llanero_Central_Llanos_foothills_Eastern_Cordillera_Colombia}} </ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Caryodendron orinocense}}\n{{Commons|Caryodendron orinocense}}\n\n* [https://eol.org/pages/1148517 \u00ab''Caryodendron orinocense'' H. Karst.\u00bb], Encyclopedia of Life.\n* [https://www.gbif.org/species/3055897 \u00abCaryodendron orinocense Karst.\u00bb], Global Biodiversity Information Facility.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5753991}}\n\n[[Category:Flora of northern South America]]\n[[Category:Plants_described_in_1858]]\n[[Category:Flora of western South America]]\n[[Category:Acalyphoideae]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Frutos de Cacay.jpg\n| image_caption = Cacay fruits, near [[Puerto Gaitan]], [[Meta Department|Meta]], [[Colombia]].\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN-Redlist\"/>\n| genus = Caryodendron\n| species = orinocense\n| authority = [[Gustav Karl Wilhelm Hermann Karsten|H.Karst.]]\n| range_map = Caryodendron orinocense distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = Approximate distribution of ''Caryodendron orinocense''<ref name=\"IUCN-Redlist\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Caryodendron orinocense''''', commonly known as '''cacay''', '''inchi''' or '''orinoconut''', is an [[evergreen]] tree belonging to the family [[Euphorbiaceae]].\n\nThis [[species]] of [[flowering plant]] is [[indigenous (ecology)|indigenous]] to the north-west of [[South America]], particularly from the [[drainage basin|drainage basins]] of the [[Orinoco]] and [[Amazon River|Amazon]] rivers located in [[Colombia]], [[Venezuela]], [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]] and [[Brazil]]. Originally described by [[Gustav Karl Wilhelm Hermann Karsten|Hermann Karsten]] in 1858, the cacay tree distinguishes itself by its dense and leafy top, as well as its production of fruits, each one containing three edible nuts. Cacay is notable for the oil extracted from its nuts, which is edible and is also used in [[cosmetics]].\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:C. orinocense \u00e1rbol adulto de cacay.jpg|thumb|left|Adult trees in a plantation]]\n''Caryodendron orinocense'' is a [[tree]] which can grow to {{convert|30|\u2013|40|m|ft|-1}} tall in the forest.<ref name=\"FAO\"/> In plantations, the tree reaches heights of up to {{convert|15|m|ft|-1}}.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/> Its [[Trunk (botany)|trunk]] is straight and cylindrical before separating into numerous branches.<ref name=\"FAO\"/> Its outer [[Bark (botany)|bark]] is smooth, and exhibits periodic shedding as laminar plates. It possesses a wide and superficial [[root]] system, such that its thick roots are sometimes visible above ground.<ref name=\"FAO\"/> The longevity of the species exceeds 60 years.<ref name=\"Universidad EIA\"/>\n\nCacay is an [[evergreen]] tree and has a dense and leafy [[Crown (botany)|crown]].<ref name=\"Universidad EIA\"/> Its leaves are [[Leaf#Divisions of the lamina (blade)|simple]] and are [[Phyllotaxis|arranged in an alternate pattern on the stem]]. Their shape is elliptical or oval, between {{convert|12|\u2013|25|cm|in}} long and {{convert|4|\u2013|10|cm|in}} wide.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/>\n\nIt is a [[Dioecy|dioecious]] plants, with male and female specimens. Its masculine flowering is a terminal [[raceme]] with small greenish flowers between {{convert|2.5|\u2013|3.5|mm|in}} in diameter. Neither male nor female flowers display any [[petal|petals]]. Its feminine flowering is a terminal [[Ear (botany)|ear]], also with greenish flowers ranging between {{convert|2.5|\u2013|3.5|mm|in}} in diameter, containing large and persistent [[Bract|bracts]].<ref name=\"FAO\"/>\n\nIts fruit is a brownish/grey oval and woody capsule between {{convert|3.2|\u2013|4.5|cm|in}} in diameter. Each fruit contains three nuts or kernels (rarely two or four), which are slightly convex and have three [[Face (geometry)|faces]].<ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"Jim\u00e9nez\"/> Each nut contains a single seed covered by a [[Seed#Seed_coat|testa]] and weights approximately {{convert|2.7|g|oz}}.<ref name=\"Cisneros Torres\"/>\n\n== Taxonomy and etymology ==\n\n[[File:Caryodendron_orinocense_Karst.jpg|thumb|upright=.75|Illustration in ''[[Florae Columbiae]]'' (1858)]]\n\nThe species ''Caryodendron orinocense''  was described in 1858 by the German botanist [[Gustav Karl Wilhelm Hermann Karsten|Hermann Karsten]], and was published in ''[[Florae Columbiae]]''.<ref name=\"Tropicos\"/> In its scientific name, the term '''''Caryodendron''''' is derived from the [[ancient Greek]] ''[[wiktionary:en:\u03ba\u03ac\u03c1\u03c5\u03bf\u03bd|k\u00e1ryon]]'', meaning \"nut\", and ''[[wiktionary:en:\u03b4\u03ad\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd|d\u00e9ndron]]'', meaning \"tree\". Its epithet '''''orinocense''''' suggests that the species was first identified near the [[Orinoco|Orinoco river]].<ref name=\"Universidad EIA\"/>\n\n''Caryodendron orinocense'' is found under the following phylogenetic tree within the [[Caryodendreae]] [[tribe (biology)|tribe]].{{refn|group=\"notes\"|In some sources, the scientific name ''Dioicia tetrandia'' <small>L.</small> appears as a [[Synonym (taxonomy)|synonym]] of ''Caryodendron orinocense''.<ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"Martinez\"/>}} The number in parenthesis represents the year in which the species was described.<ref name=\"Tropicos-Caryodendron-SubordinateTaxa\"/><ref name=\"GRIN\"/>\n\n{{Clade\n|style= font-size:100%; line-height:100%\n| label1=''[[Caryodendreae]]''\n| 1={{Clade\n      | 1={{Clade\n            |1=''[[Alchorneopsis]]''\n           }}\n      | 2={{Clade\n          | label1=''[[Caryodendron]]''\n          | 1= {{Clade\n               |1= ''[[Caryodendron amazonicum]]'' (1943)\n               |2= ''[[Caryodendron angustifolium]]'' (1929)\n               |3= ''[[Caryodendron janeirense]]'' (1874)\n               |5= '''''Caryodendron orinocense''''' (1858)\n               }}\n          }}\n      | 3={{Clade\n            |1=''[[Discoglypremna]]''\n           }}\n    }}\n}}\n\n=== Common names ===\nThe [[common name|vernacular names]] of ''Caryodendron orinocensese'' include:\n* '''Cacay''' <ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\"/><ref name=\"Losada A.\"/><ref name=\"Garcia Urrea\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Morillo-Coronado\"/>\n* '''Inchi''' <ref name=\"Universidad EIA\"/><ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Morillo-Coronado\"/><ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/><ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"Jim\u00e9nez\"/>{{refn|group=\"notes\"|''Caryodendron orinocensese'' (commonly known as cacay, inchi, or orinoconut) should not be mistaken with ''[[Plukenetia volubilis]]'', which is commonly known as ''sacha inchi''.<ref name=\"Wang\"/>}}\n* '''Tacay''' <ref name=\"Universidad EIA\"/><ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/>\n* '''Orinoconut''' <ref name=\"Reckin\"/> or '''Orinoco nut''' <ref name=\"Janick\"/>\n* '''Man\u00ed de \u00e1rbol''' <ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/>\n* '''Nuez''' o '''nogal de Barquisimeto''' <ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\"/><ref name=\"Padilla\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/>\n* '''Nuez de Barinas''' <ref name=\"P\u00e9rez\"/>\n* '''Meto huayo''' <ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\"/> or '''Metohuayo''' <ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/>\n* '''Palo de nuez''' <ref name=\"FAO\"/>\n* '''Nueza criolla''' <ref name=\"CETEP\"/>\n\n== Distribution, habitat, and ecology == \n[[File:C. orinocense flor femenina.jpg|thumb|left|Female flowers]]\nCacay is an [[Indigenous (ecology)|indigenous]] species to the [[drainage basin|drainage basins]] of the [[Orinoco]] and [[Amazon River|Amazon]] rivers, and can be found in [[Colombia]], [[Venezuela]], [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]] and [[Brazil]].<ref name=\"Losada A.\"/> In Colombia, cacay is distributed across the [[w:es:Piedemonte llanero|Piedemonte llanero]]{{refn|group=\"notes\"|The Piedemonte Llanero is a wedge duplex zone on the eastern flank of the [[Cordillera Oriental (Colombia)|Eastern Ranges of Colombia]].<ref name=\"Piedemonte\"/>}} in the eastern foothills of the [[Andes|Andes Mountains]].<ref name=\"Pabon\"/> It is also found in the watershed of the [[Magdalena River]].<ref name=\"IUCN-Redlist\"/> The species has been reported in five Colombian departments ([[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]], [[Caquet\u00e1 Department|Caquet\u00e1]], [[Cundinamarca Department|Cundinamarca]], [[Meta Department|Meta]], [[Putumayo Department|Putumayo]]) with influence over three Colombian natural regions ([[Andean natural region|Andean]], [[Orinoqu\u00eda natural region|Orinoqu\u00eda or Eastern Plains]], and [[Amazon natural region|Amazon]]).<ref name=\"UNAL\"/> In Venezuela, the plant grows in the [[States of Venezuela|states]] of [[Apure|Apure]], [[Lara (state)|Lara]], y [[Barinas (state)|Barinas]].<ref name=\"P\u00e9rez\"/><ref name=\"Pabon\"/> Cacay can also be found in Ecuador, Peru and Brazil in the western part of the Amazon river watershed.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Orduz\"/>\n\nTh tree grows in the transition between [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|tropical moist forest and tropical wet forest]], receiving an average annual precipitation of {{convert|2000|\u2013|5000|mm|in|-1}}.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Nieto\"/> It develops preferably in terrains with good drainage that do not easily flood.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\" /> It tolerates a few months of moderate drought, but does not support long dry periods. The species is also able to support short periods of water saturation, but cannot withstand permanent [[Waterlogging (agriculture)|waterlogging]].<ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\" /> Cacay prospers in fertile soils originating from [[Alluvium|alluvial deposits]], but can adapt to [[:en:Ultisol|ultisol]] and [[Oxisol|oxisol]] soils which are acidic and poor in nutrient content.<ref name=\"Pabon\"/>\n\nCacay develops best in warm climates and in low-altitude plains, with average temperatures of {{convert|22|\u2013|28|C|F}} and [[relative humidity]] of 70-90%.<ref name=\"Orduz\"/><ref name=\"Instituto-Sinchi\"/> However, cacay is found in altitudes ranging from sea level to 2300 [[Metres above sea level|m a.s.l.]]<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\" />\n\n== Propagation ==\n[[File:Flor_macho.jpg|thumb|right|Male flowers]]\nUnder natural conditions, the reproduction of cacay is sexual; its seeds germinate well on the ground, one to two weeks after falling from the tree.<ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/> The species' seeds are [[recalcitrant seed|seed]], as the seeds quickly lose their viability when under storage.<ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"Garcia 2012\"/> A study conducted in 2012 by Judith Garc\u00eda and Carmen Basso concluded that cacay seeds tolerate up to eight days of storage before losing viability, preferably in temperatures of {{convert|12|\u2013|13|C|F}}.<ref name=\"Garcia 2012\"/>\n\nThe species can also reproduce through vegetative (asexual) means, especially through [[grafting]], which is commonly used in cacay farming.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/> Conversely, [[Cutting (plant)|propagation by plant cutting]] does not yield satisfactory results, as even when the plant shows [[Callus (cell biology)|callus]] growth, it does not produce any new development of roots or buds.<ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/><ref name=\"Garcia 2009\"/>\n\n== Farming ==\n[[File:C.orinocense.jpg|thumb|left|A two year old [[Juvenile (organism)|juvenile]] tree in a plantation]]\n\nThe cultivated cacay tree initially grows slowly. During this stage, moderate shade favorably contributes to its development.<ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/><ref name=\"CETEP\"/> Cacay can be planted in bags in a [[Plant nursery|nursery]] for approximately one year, until the tree reaches a height of about {{convert|50|cm|in}}.<ref name=\"Geilfus\"/> When the tree is actively producing fruits, the cacay plant is a [[heliophyte]], although it tolerates some shade. Cacay be planted in parallel with another plant that grows rapidly and that possesses a small crown which may provide shade to the juvenile cacay tree, but which does not compete for sunlight during the cacay's adult stage.<ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/> Some plantations associate the cacay tree with another crop that may provide a live vegetable groundcover,{{refn|group=\"notes\"|A cover crop is a crop that provides a vegetable coverage of the ground, whether temporary or permanent, and which is planted in association with another crop.<ref name=\"FAO-2\"/>}} for example [[Pueraria montana var. lobata|kudzu]].<ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\"/>\n\n[[File:C. orinocense fruta de cacay en crecimiento.jpg|thumb|Fruit]]\n\nThe ripe cacay fruit physiologically separates itself from the plant and falls to the ground.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/> Cacay trees begin to produce fruit at ages 4-7 years. A single 10 year old cacay tree may produce {{convert|100|\u2013|250|kg|lb|-1}} of nuts per year,<ref name=\"Geilfus\"/> although some trees have been reported to produce up to {{convert|800|kg|lb|-1}} of nuts per year.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/>\n\n== Properties and uses ==\n\n=== Cacay oil ===\nCacay is renowned for the quality of its [[Types of plant oils|plant oil]].<ref name=\"Jim\u00e9nez\"/> Each cacay fruit generally produces three nuts, from which a liquid oil with a yellow-greenish color can be extracted.<ref name=\"FAO\"/> This oil comprises between 40-60% of the seed's weight.<ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Pabon\"/> Several studies (P\u00e9rez 2001, Cisneros Torres 2006) report that the cacay oil is composed of 71-75% of [[linoleic acid]], an [[essential fatty acid]] from the [[Omega-6 fatty acid|omega-6 fatty acid family]], which is important for skincare purposes.<ref name=\"Cisneros Torres\"/><ref name=\"Martinez\"/><ref name=\"P\u00e9rez\"/> This high concentration of [[Polyunsaturated fat|polyunsaturated fats]] (in this case, of linoleic acid) is superior to that of [[soybean oil]] (60%), [[Corn oil|corn/maize oil]] (55.5%), [[sesame oil]] (42%), [[peanut oil]] (26%), [[coconut oil]] (14%), [[olive oil]] (9.5%), and [[palm oil]] (8%).<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/>\n\nCacay oil is used in the production of [[Cosmetics|cosmetic]] products such as soaps, sunscreens, and skincare creams.<ref name=\"CETEP\"/> The full value proposition of this oil for cosmetic purposes is still being developed; however, various studies (P\u00e9rez 2001, Ortega \u00c1lvarez 2014) have already remarked on the future potential of cacay in this field.<ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\"/><ref name=\"P\u00e9rez\"/> The cacay oil is also used directly as an edible oil.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"CETEP\"/>\n\n=== Nutrition ===\n[[File:C. orinocense fruta de cacay madura.jpg|thumb|right|Ripe fruit with three seeds]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Composition of the cacay nut/kernel\n|'''Properties''' \n|'''Quantity''' \n|-\n|Plant oil\n|40-60%<ref name=\"Pabon\"/><ref name=\"FAO\"/><ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/>\n|-\n|Polyunsaturated fat (in the oil)\n|71-75%<ref name=\"P\u00e9rez\"/><ref name=\"Cisneros Torres\"/><ref name=\"Martinez\"/>\n|-\n|Calories per nut\n|641-691<ref name=\"Martinez\"/><ref name=\"Instituto-Sinchi\"/>\n|-\n|Protein\n|15-19%<ref name=\"Martinez\"/><ref name=\"Cisneros Torres\"/><ref name=\"Padilla\"/>\n|-\n|[[Starch]]\n|17%<ref name=\"Martinez\"/>\n|}\n\nThe cacay nut is rich in [[phosphorus]], [[calcium]], and [[iron]].<ref name=\"Martinez\"/><ref name=\"Instituto-Sinchi\"/> About 15-19% of the nut is composed of protein, while the [[press cake]] (the dry organic matter after the oil is extracted) is composed 43-46% of protein.<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Martinez\"/> The nuts from ripe cacay fruits are edible and have a pleasant taste, similar to that of [[Peanut|peanuts]].<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\"/><ref name=\"Instituto-Sinchi\"/> Nuts can be eaten uncooked, toasted, fried, or boiled with salt. The nuts can also be used to prepare foods such as cakes, [[Turr\u00f3n|turr\u00f3n]], beverages, and cookies. After grinding down the nut, its flour can be used to produce vitamin supplements, as well as to elaborate [[functional food|functional foods]].<ref name=\"Garcia Urrea\"/>\n\n=== Other uses ===\nIts lumber can be used for [[Cabinetry|woodworking structures]], and may be utilized as firewood and in the production of [[charcoal]].<ref name=\"Jim\u00e9nez\"/><ref name=\"Pabon\"/> Cacay trees may also be used to provide shade to other crops that need it (as possibly coffee plantations) and for other animals.<ref name=\"Pabon\"/><ref name=\"Geilfus\"/> Within the domain of [[agroforestry]], cacay trees may be introduced into areas that are not adequate for intense agricultural and cattle raining activities.<ref name=\"Pabon\"/> Furthermore, the tree may be used as an allurement for bees, as its leaves excrete a nectar that is attractive to bees to help the tree's [[pollination]].<ref name=\"CETEP\"/> Additionally, nut's press cake can also serve as food for cattle due to their high content of proteins and minerals.<ref name=\"CETEP\"/>\n\n== Ecological value ==\nIndigenous crops such as ''Caryodendron orinocense'' may provide benefits to their ecosystem important to the conservation of the area's biodiversity.<ref name=\"Espinosa\"/> These benefits include:\n\n* [[Conservation biology|Conservation]]: increase in the available habitat for autochtonous and migratory species, as well as serving as a refuge and [[wildlife corridor]] for them.<ref name=\"Espinosa\"/>\n* [[Reforestation]]: atmospheric carbon dioxide capture, retention of water and nutrients in the soil, prevention of erosion and [[desertification]].<ref name=\"Angulo-Ospina\"/>\n\nCacay has been recommended as an indigenous tree that may serve in the ecological restoration of areas with soils with invasive species of grasses such as ''[[w:es:brachiaria humidicola|brachiaria humidicola]]'', particularly in areas of the [[savanna]] of the [[Orinoqu\u00eda natural region|Eastern Plains region of Colombia]].<ref name=\"Angulo-Ospina\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"notes\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Tropicos\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tropicos.org/Name/12805145 |title= ''Caryodendron orinocense''|access-date=4 November 2019 |website= Tropicos.org. |publisher=[[Missouri Botanical Garden]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tropicos-Caryodendron-SubordinateTaxa\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tropicos.org/Name/40002097?tab=subordinatetaxa |title= ''Caryodendron'' H. Karst. - Subordinate Taxa |access-date=19 November 2019 |website= Tropicos.org. |publisher=[[Missouri Botanical Garden]] }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Universidad EIA\">{{Cite web |url=https://catalogofloravalleaburra.eia.edu.co/species/118 |title= ''Cat\u00e1logo virtual de flora del Valle de Aburr\u00e1''|access-date=4 November 2019 |publisher= [[w:es:Universidad EIA|Universidad EIA]] |language=es}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Ortega \u00c1lvarez\">{{Cite journal |last=Ortega \u00c1lvarez |first=Deysi D |date=2014 |title=Caracterizaci\u00f3n de la composici\u00f3n fitoqu\u00edmica del aceite vegetal de la especie man\u00ed de \u00e1rbol (Caryodendron orinocense h. Karst) e investigar su aplicaci\u00f3n en emulsiones cosm\u00e9ticas |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/334099611/Tesis-de-Deysi-Daniela-Ortega-Alvarez |publisher=[[w:es:Universidad Estatal Amaz\u00f3nica|Universidad Estatal Amaz\u00f3nica]] |language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"\u00c1vila\">{{Cite journal |last1=\u00c1vila |first1=Luz Mar\u00eda |last2=D\u00edaz Merch\u00e1n |first2=Jos\u00e9 Andr\u00e9s |date=2002 |title=Sondeo del mercado mundial de Inchi (Caryodendron orinocense) |url=http://hdl.handle.net/20.500.11761/31486 | access-date=29 March 2020 |publisher=[[ Alexander von Humboldt Biological Resources Research Institute]] |language=es }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1les Coral\">{{Cite journal |last1=Gonz\u00e1les Coral |first1=Agust\u00edn |last2=Torres Reyna |first2=Guiuseppe Melecio |date=2010 |title=Manual de cultivo de metohuayo Caryodendron orinocense Karst|url=http://repositori