{"title_page": "PLA Unit 61398", "text_new": "{{Expand Chinese|\u89e3\u653e\u8ecd61398\u90e8\u968a|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name =People's Liberation Army Unit 61398\n|native_name=61398\u90e8\u961f\n|image= \n|caption= \n|dates= \n|country={{flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|allegiance=\n|command_structure=\n|branch=[[File:PLASSF.svg|23px]] [[People's Liberation Army Strategic Support Force]]\n|type= [[Cyber force]]\n|specialization=[[Cyberwarfare in China|Cyber warfare]] <br> [[Electronic warfare]]\n|size=\n|garrison= Tonggang Road, [[Pudong]], [[Shanghai]]\n|commander1_label=\n|commander1=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3_label=\n|commander3=\n|nickname=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=\n* [[GhostNet|Operation GhostNet]]\n* [[Operation Aurora]]\n* [[Operation Shady RAT]]\n|formally called=\n* APT 1<br/>Comment Crew<br/>Comment Panda<br/>GIF89a<br/>Byzantine Candor<br/>Group 3<br/>Threat Group 8223\n|notable_commanders =\n|anniversaries =\n|identification_symbol=\n}}\n'''PLA Unit 61398''' (also known as '''APT 1''', '''Comment Crew''', '''Comment Panda''', '''GIF89a''', and '''Byzantine Candor''' )({{zh|61398\u90e8\u961f}}, [[Pinyin]]: 61398 ''b\u00f9du\u00ec'') is the Military Unit Cover Designator (MUCD)<ref name=MandiantAPT1>{{cite web|url=http://intelreport.mandiant.com/Mandiant_APT1_Report.pdf|title=APT1: Exposing One of China's Cyber Espionage Units|publisher=Mandiant|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref> of a [[People's Liberation Army]] [[advanced persistent threat]] unit that has been alleged to be a source of Chinese [[hacker (computer security)|computer hacking]] attacks.<ref name=\"NYT 2013-02-18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/19/technology/chinas-army-is-seen-as-tied-to-hacking-against-us.html?emc=na&_r=1&|title= Chinese Army Unit Is Seen as Tied to Hacking Against U.S.|work=[[New York Times]]|author=David E. Sanger, David Barboza and Nicole Perlroth|date=18 February 2013|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/feb/19/chinese-military-unit-prolific-hacking|title=Chinese military unit behind 'prolific and sustained hacking'|publisher=The Guardian|date=19 February 2013|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref> The unit is stationed in [[Pudong]], [[Shanghai]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.zju.edu.cn/chinese/redir.php?catalog_id=101913&object_id=106021|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u519b61398\u90e8\u961f\u62db\u6536\u5b9a\u5411\u7814\u7a76\u751f\u7684\u901a\u77e5|date=2004-05-13|website=Zhejiang University|trans-title=A notification of PLA Unit 64398 to recruit postgraduate students as PLA-funded scholarship student.|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:FBI20140519.jpg|thumb|left|From left, Chinese military officers Gu Chunhui, Huang Zhenyu, Sun Kailiang, Wang Dong Schlong, and Wen Xinyu indicted on cyber espionage charges.]]{{See also|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\n\n===2014 Indictment===\n\nOn 19 May 2014, the [[US Department of Justice]] announced that a Federal [[grand jury]] had returned an indictment of five 61398 officers on charges of theft of confidential business information and intellectual property from U.S. commercial firms and of planting [[malware]] on their computers.<ref>Finkle, J., Menn, J., Viswanatha, J. [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cybercrime-usa-china-idUSKCN0J42M520141120 ''U.S. accuses China of cyber spying on American companies.''] Reuters, 20 Nov 2014.</ref><ref>Clayton, M. [http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Security-Watch/Cyber-Conflict-Monitor/2014/0519/US-indicts-five-in-China-s-secret-Unit-61398-for-cyber-spying-on-US-firms ''US indicts five in China's secret 'Unit 61398' for cyber-spying.''] Christian Science Monitor, 19 May 2014</ref> The five are Huang Zhenyu (\u9ec4\u632f\u5b87), Wen Xinyu (\u6587\u65b0\u5b87), Sun Kailiang (\u5b59\u51ef\u4eae), Gu Chunhui (\u987e\u6625\u6656), and Wang Dong (\u738b\u4e1c).  Forensic evidence traces the base of operations to a 12-story building off Datong Road in a public, mixed-use area of [[Pudong]] in Shanghai.<ref name=\"NYT 2013-02-18\"/> The group is also known by various other names including \"[[APT1|Advanced Persistent Threat 1]]\" (\"APT1\"), \"the Comment group\" and \"Byzantine Candor\", a codename given by US intelligence agencies since 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiercegovernmentit.com/story/chinese-attacks-byzantine-candor-penetrated-federal-agencies-says-leaked-ca/2010-12-06 |title=Chinese attacks 'Byzantine Candor' penetrated federal agencies, says leaked cable |author=David Perera |date=6 December 2010 |website=fiercegovernmentit.com |publisher=Fierce Government IT |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"CSMonitor\">{{cite web|last=Clayton|first=Mark|title=Stealing US business secrets: Experts ID two huge cyber 'gangs' in China|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/2012/0914/Stealing-US-business-secrets-Experts-ID-two-huge-cyber-gangs-in-China|publisher=[[CSMonitor]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|date=14 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloomberg EU DC\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=China's Comment Group Hacks Europe\u2014and the World|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-08-02/chinas-comment-group-hacks-europe-and-the-world|accessdate=12 February 2013|newspaper=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date=2 August 2012|author=Michael Riley|author2=Dune Lawrence}}</ref>\n\nA report by the [[computer security]] firm [[Mandiant]] stated that PLA Unit 61398 is believed to operate under the 2nd Bureau of the [[People's Liberation Army General Staff Department]] (GSD) [[People's Liberation Army#Third Department|Third Department]] (\u603b\u53c2\u4e09\u90e8\u4e8c\u5c40).<ref name=MandiantAPT1/> and that there is evidence that it contains, or is itself, an entity Mandiant calls [[APT1]], part of the [[advanced persistent threat]] that has attacked a broad range of corporations and government entities around the world since at least 2006. APT1 is described as comprising four large networks in Shanghai, two of which serve the Pudong New Area. It is one of more than 20 APT groups with origins in China.<ref name=MandiantAPT1/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/china-hacking-pla-unit-61398-2013-2|title=REPORT: An Overwhelming Number Of The Cyber-Attacks On America Are Coming From This Particular Army Building In China|publisher=Business Insider|date= 18 February 2013|author=Joe Weisenthal and Geoffrey Ingersoll|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref> The Third and [[People's Liberation Army#Fourth Department|Fourth Department]], responsible for [[electronic warfare]], are believed to comprise the PLA units mainly responsible for infiltrating and manipulating computer networks.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost professional\">{{cite web|last=Bodeen|first=Christopher|title=Sign That Chinese Hackers Have Become Professional: They Take Weekends Off|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/25/chinese-hackers_n_2756914.html|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=25 February 2013|accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe group often compromises internal software \"comment\" features on legitimate web pages to infiltrate target computers that access the sites, leading it to be known as \"the Comment group\".<ref name=\"NYMag Comment Crew\">{{cite web|last=Martin|first=Adam|title=Meet 'Comment Crew,' China's Military-Linked Hackers|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/02/meet-comment-crew-chinas-military-hackers.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|NYMag.com]]|publisher=[[New York Media]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|date=19 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Comment Group: The hackers hunting for clues about you|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21371608|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2013|author=Dave Lee|date=12 February 2013}}</ref> The collective has stolen [[trade secret]]s and other confidential information from numerous foreign businesses and organizations over the course of seven years such as [[Lockheed Martin]], [[Telvent]], and other companies in the shipping, aeronautics, arms, energy, manufacturing, engineering, electronics, financial, and software sectors.<ref name=\"CSMonitor\"/>\n\n[[Dell SecureWorks]] says it believed the group includes the same group of attackers behind [[Operation Shady RAT]], an extensive computer espionage campaign uncovered in 2011 in which more than 70 organizations over a five-year period, including the United Nations, government agencies in the United States, Canada, [[South Korea]], Taiwan and Vietnam were targeted.<ref name=\"NYT 2013-02-18\"/>\n\nThe attacks documented in the summer of 2011 represent a fragment of the Comment group's attacks, which go back at least to 2002, according to incident reports and investigators. [[FireEye, Inc.]] alone has tracked hundreds of targets in the last three years and estimates the group has attacked more than 1,000 organizations.<ref name=\"Bloomberg EU DC\">{{cite web |last1=Riley |first1=Michael |title=Hackers Linked to China's Army Seen From EU to D.C.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-26/china-hackers-hit-eu-point-man-and-d-c-with-byzantine-candor.html|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|author2=Dune Lawrence|date=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nMost activity between [[malware]] embedded in a compromised system and the malware's controllers takes place during business hours in Beijing's time zone, suggesting that the group is professionally hired, rather than private hackers inspired by patriotic passions.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost professional\"/>\n\n== Public position of the Chinese government ==\nUntil 2013, the [[Government of China]] has consistently denied that it is involved in hacking.<ref name=\"MW Feb 20\">{{cite web|last=Xu |first=Weiwei|title=China denies hacking claims|url=http://www.morningwhistle.com/html/2013/PoliticsSociety_0220/217214.html|publisher=Morning Whistle|accessdate=8 April 2013 |date=20 February 2013}}</ref> In response to the [[Mandiant]] Corporation report about Unit 61398, [[Hong Lei (politician)|Hong Lei]], a spokesperson for the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Chinese foreign ministry]], said such allegations were \"unprofessional\".<ref name=\"MW Feb 20\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hello, Unit 61398|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/02/chinese-cyber-attacks?spc=scode&spv=xm&ah=9d7f7ab945510a56fa6d37c30b6f1709|accessdate=5 March 2013|newspaper=The Economist|date=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, China changed its position and openly admitted to having secretive cyber warfare units in both the military and the civilian part of the government{{snd}}however, the details of their activities were left to speculation.<ref>{{cite news|title=China Finally Admits focusing on Cyber Warfare|url=http://www.ucsusa.org/sites/default/files/attach/2015/03/chinese-nuclear-strategy-full-report.pdf | date=19 March 2015}}</ref> As a show of force towards the rest of the global community the Chinese government now openly lists their abilities when it comes to digital spying and network attack capabilities.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-22430224 | title=US accuses China government and military of cyber-spying | date=7 May 2013 | accessdate=15 January 2019 | author= BBC}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Titan Rain]]\n* [[Chinese espionage in the United States]]\n* [[National Security Agency]] of the United States\n* [[PLA Unit 61486]]\n* [[Signals intelligence]]\n* [[Tailored Access Operations]] of the United States\n* [[Mandiant]]\n* [[FireEye]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{coord|31|20|57.43|N|121|34|24.74|E|region:CN_type:landmark_source:MandiantReportPage12|display=title}}\n\n{{Hacking in the 2000s}}\n{{Hacking in the 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Cyberwarfare in China]]\n[[Category:Advanced persistent threat]]\n[[Category:Information operations units and formations]]\n[[Category:Hacking (computer security)]]\n[[Category:Injection exploits]]\n[[Category:Web security exploits]]\n[[Category:Sabotage]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Chinese intelligence agencies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Chinese|\u89e3\u653e\u8ecd61398\u90e8\u968a|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name =People's Liberation Army Unit 61398\n|native_name=61398\u90e8\u961f\n|image= \n|caption= \n|dates= \n|country={{flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|allegiance=\n|command_structure=\n|branch=[[File:PLASSF.svg|23px]] [[People's Liberation Army Strategic Support Force]]\n|type= [[Cyber force]]\n|specialization=[[Cyberwarfare in China|Cyber warfare]] <br> [[Electronic warfare]]\n|size=\n|garrison= Tonggang Road, [[Pudong]], [[Shanghai]]\n|commander1_label=\n|commander1=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3_label=\n|commander3=\n|nickname=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=\n* [[GhostNet|Operation GhostNet]]\n* [[Operation Aurora]]\n* [[Operation Shady RAT]]\n|formally called=\n* APT 1<br/>Comment Crew<br/>Comment Panda<br/>GIF89a<br/>Byzantine Candor<br/>Group 3<br/>Threat Group 8223\n|notable_commanders =\n|anniversaries =\n|identification_symbol=\n}}\n'''PLA Unit 61398''' (also known as '''APT 1''', '''Comment Crew''', '''Comment Panda''', '''GIF89a''', and '''Byzantine Candor''' )({{zh|61398\u90e8\u961f}}, [[Pinyin]]: 61398 ''b\u00f9du\u00ec'') is the Military Unit Cover Designator (MUCD)<ref name=MandiantAPT1>{{cite web|url=http://intelreport.mandiant.com/Mandiant_APT1_Report.pdf|title=APT1: Exposing One of China's Cyber Espionage Units|publisher=Mandiant|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref> of a [[People's Liberation Army]] [[advanced persistent threat]] unit that has been alleged to be a source of Chinese [[hacker (computer security)|computer hacking]] attacks.<ref name=\"NYT 2013-02-18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/19/technology/chinas-army-is-seen-as-tied-to-hacking-against-us.html?emc=na&_r=1&|title= Chinese Army Unit Is Seen as Tied to Hacking Against U.S.|work=[[New York Times]]|author=David E. Sanger, David Barboza and Nicole Perlroth|date=18 February 2013|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/feb/19/chinese-military-unit-prolific-hacking|title=Chinese military unit behind 'prolific and sustained hacking'|publisher=The Guardian|date=19 February 2013|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref> The unit is stationed in [[Pudong]], [[Shanghai]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.zju.edu.cn/chinese/redir.php?catalog_id=101913&object_id=106021|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u519b61398\u90e8\u961f\u62db\u6536\u5b9a\u5411\u7814\u7a76\u751f\u7684\u901a\u77e5|date=2004-05-13|website=Zhejiang University|trans-title=A notification of PLA Unit 64398 to recruit postgraduate students as PLA-funded scholarship student.|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:FBI20140519.jpg|thumb|left|From left, Chinese military officers Gu Chunhui, Huang Zhenyu, Sun Kailiang, Wang Dong, and Wen Xinyu indicted on cyber espionage charges.]]{{See also|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\n\n===2014 Indictment===\n\nOn 19 May 2014, the [[US Department of Justice]] announced that a Federal [[grand jury]] had returned an indictment of five 61398 officers on charges of theft of confidential business information and intellectual property from U.S. commercial firms and of planting [[malware]] on their computers.<ref>Finkle, J., Menn, J., Viswanatha, J. [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cybercrime-usa-china-idUSKCN0J42M520141120 ''U.S. accuses China of cyber spying on American companies.''] Reuters, 20 Nov 2014.</ref><ref>Clayton, M. [http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Security-Watch/Cyber-Conflict-Monitor/2014/0519/US-indicts-five-in-China-s-secret-Unit-61398-for-cyber-spying-on-US-firms ''US indicts five in China's secret 'Unit 61398' for cyber-spying.''] Christian Science Monitor, 19 May 2014</ref> The five are Huang Zhenyu (\u9ec4\u632f\u5b87), Wen Xinyu (\u6587\u65b0\u5b87), Sun Kailiang (\u5b59\u51ef\u4eae), Gu Chunhui (\u987e\u6625\u6656), and Wang Dong (\u738b\u4e1c).  Forensic evidence traces the base of operations to a 12-story building off Datong Road in a public, mixed-use area of [[Pudong]] in Shanghai.<ref name=\"NYT 2013-02-18\"/> The group is also known by various other names including \"[[APT1|Advanced Persistent Threat 1]]\" (\"APT1\"), \"the Comment group\" and \"Byzantine Candor\", a codename given by US intelligence agencies since 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiercegovernmentit.com/story/chinese-attacks-byzantine-candor-penetrated-federal-agencies-says-leaked-ca/2010-12-06 |title=Chinese attacks 'Byzantine Candor' penetrated federal agencies, says leaked cable |author=David Perera |date=6 December 2010 |website=fiercegovernmentit.com |publisher=Fierce Government IT |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"CSMonitor\">{{cite web|last=Clayton|first=Mark|title=Stealing US business secrets: Experts ID two huge cyber 'gangs' in China|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/2012/0914/Stealing-US-business-secrets-Experts-ID-two-huge-cyber-gangs-in-China|publisher=[[CSMonitor]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|date=14 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloomberg EU DC\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=China's Comment Group Hacks Europe\u2014and the World|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-08-02/chinas-comment-group-hacks-europe-and-the-world|accessdate=12 February 2013|newspaper=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date=2 August 2012|author=Michael Riley|author2=Dune Lawrence}}</ref>\n\nA report by the [[computer security]] firm [[Mandiant]] stated that PLA Unit 61398 is believed to operate under the 2nd Bureau of the [[People's Liberation Army General Staff Department]] (GSD) [[People's Liberation Army#Third Department|Third Department]] (\u603b\u53c2\u4e09\u90e8\u4e8c\u5c40).<ref name=MandiantAPT1/> and that there is evidence that it contains, or is itself, an entity Mandiant calls [[APT1]], part of the [[advanced persistent threat]] that has attacked a broad range of corporations and government entities around the world since at least 2006. APT1 is described as comprising four large networks in Shanghai, two of which serve the Pudong New Area. It is one of more than 20 APT groups with origins in China.<ref name=MandiantAPT1/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/china-hacking-pla-unit-61398-2013-2|title=REPORT: An Overwhelming Number Of The Cyber-Attacks On America Are Coming From This Particular Army Building In China|publisher=Business Insider|date= 18 February 2013|author=Joe Weisenthal and Geoffrey Ingersoll|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref> The Third and [[People's Liberation Army#Fourth Department|Fourth Department]], responsible for [[electronic warfare]], are believed to comprise the PLA units mainly responsible for infiltrating and manipulating computer networks.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost professional\">{{cite web|last=Bodeen|first=Christopher|title=Sign That Chinese Hackers Have Become Professional: They Take Weekends Off|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/25/chinese-hackers_n_2756914.html|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=25 February 2013|accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe group often compromises internal software \"comment\" features on legitimate web pages to infiltrate target computers that access the sites, leading it to be known as \"the Comment group\".<ref name=\"NYMag Comment Crew\">{{cite web|last=Martin|first=Adam|title=Meet 'Comment Crew,' China's Military-Linked Hackers|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/02/meet-comment-crew-chinas-military-hackers.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|NYMag.com]]|publisher=[[New York Media]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|date=19 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Comment Group: The hackers hunting for clues about you|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21371608|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2013|author=Dave Lee|date=12 February 2013}}</ref> The collective has stolen [[trade secret]]s and other confidential information from numerous foreign businesses and organizations over the course of seven years such as [[Lockheed Martin]], [[Telvent]], and other companies in the shipping, aeronautics, arms, energy, manufacturing, engineering, electronics, financial, and software sectors.<ref name=\"CSMonitor\"/>\n\n[[Dell SecureWorks]] says it believed the group includes the same group of attackers behind [[Operation Shady RAT]], an extensive computer espionage campaign uncovered in 2011 in which more than 70 organizations over a five-year period, including the United Nations, government agencies in the United States, Canada, [[South Korea]], Taiwan and Vietnam were targeted.<ref name=\"NYT 2013-02-18\"/>\n\nThe attacks documented in the summer of 2011 represent a fragment of the Comment group's attacks, which go back at least to 2002, according to incident reports and investigators. [[FireEye, Inc.]] alone has tracked hundreds of targets in the last three years and estimates the group has attacked more than 1,000 organizations.<ref name=\"Bloomberg EU DC\">{{cite web |last1=Riley |first1=Michael |title=Hackers Linked to China's Army Seen From EU to D.C.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-26/china-hackers-hit-eu-point-man-and-d-c-with-byzantine-candor.html|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|author2=Dune Lawrence|date=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nMost activity between [[malware]] embedded in a compromised system and the malware's controllers takes place during business hours in Beijing's time zone, suggesting that the group is professionally hired, rather than private hackers inspired by patriotic passions.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost professional\"/>\n\n== Public position of the Chinese government ==\nUntil 2013, the [[Government of China]] has consistently denied that it is involved in hacking.<ref name=\"MW Feb 20\">{{cite web|last=Xu |first=Weiwei|title=China denies hacking claims|url=http://www.morningwhistle.com/html/2013/PoliticsSociety_0220/217214.html|publisher=Morning Whistle|accessdate=8 April 2013 |date=20 February 2013}}</ref> In response to the [[Mandiant]] Corporation report about Unit 61398, [[Hong Lei (politician)|Hong Lei]], a spokesperson for the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Chinese foreign ministry]], said such allegations were \"unprofessional\".<ref name=\"MW Feb 20\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hello, Unit 61398|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/02/chinese-cyber-attacks?spc=scode&spv=xm&ah=9d7f7ab945510a56fa6d37c30b6f1709|accessdate=5 March 2013|newspaper=The Economist|date=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, China changed its position and openly admitted to having secretive cyber warfare units in both the military and the civilian part of the government{{snd}}however, the details of their activities were left to speculation.<ref>{{cite news|title=China Finally Admits focusing on Cyber Warfare|url=http://www.ucsusa.org/sites/default/files/attach/2015/03/chinese-nuclear-strategy-full-report.pdf | date=19 March 2015}}</ref> As a show of force towards the rest of the global community the Chinese government now openly lists their abilities when it comes to digital spying and network attack capabilities.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-22430224 | title=US accuses China government and military of cyber-spying | date=7 May 2013 | accessdate=15 January 2019 | author= BBC}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Titan Rain]]\n* [[Chinese espionage in the United States]]\n* [[National Security Agency]] of the United States\n* [[PLA Unit 61486]]\n* [[Signals intelligence]]\n* [[Tailored Access Operations]] of the United States\n* [[Mandiant]]\n* [[FireEye]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{coord|31|20|57.43|N|121|34|24.74|E|region:CN_type:landmark_source:MandiantReportPage12|display=title}}\n\n{{Hacking in the 2000s}}\n{{Hacking in the 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Cyberwarfare in China]]\n[[Category:Advanced persistent threat]]\n[[Category:Information operations units and formations]]\n[[Category:Hacking (computer security)]]\n[[Category:Injection exploits]]\n[[Category:Web security exploits]]\n[[Category:Sabotage]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Chinese intelligence agencies]]\n", "name_user": "173.79.137.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PLA_Unit_61398"}
{"title_page": "Shoebite", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Shoebite\n| image          = Shoe Bite.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = <!-- {{Infobox name module|language|title}} or {{Infobox name module|title}} -->\n| director       = [[Shoojit Sircar]]\n| producer       = [[Ronnie Screwvala]]\n| writer         = \n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{Based on|title of the original work|creator of the original work|additional creator(s), if necessary}} -->\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Amitabh Bachchan]]|[[Sarika]]|[[Dia Mirza]]|[[Jimmy Sheirgill]]}}\n| narrator       = \n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = [[UTV Motion Pictures]]\n| distributor    = <!-- or: | distributors = -->\n| released       = <!-- {{Film date|df=yes/no|year|month|day|location}} -->\n| runtime        =\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Shoebite''''' is the story of a man in his early 60s played by [[Amitabh Bachchan]]. The film is based on a story '''''Labour Of Love''''' by [[M. Night Shyamalan]].  It is directed by [[Shoojit Sircar]] and produced by [[UTV Software Communications|UTV Motion Pictures]]. The lyrics are penned by [[Gulzar]].<ref>http://www.bollywood.com/shyamalan-stalls-release-amitanh-bachchan-film {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/shyamalan-stalls-release-of-big-b-film/story-CQRWJOLK0YKvOCPSZYA7eO.html|title=Shyamalan stalls release of Big B film?|date=2012-03-17|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nDuring production, the movie was titled '''''Johnny Mastana''''' and later '''''Johnny Walker'''''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/01/berlin-sixth-senses-m-night-shyamalan-bruce-willis-re-team-for-labor-of-love-673107/|title=Berlin: \u2018Sixth Sense\u2019s M. Night Shyamalan, Bruce Willis Re-Team For \u2018Labor Of Love\u2019|last=Jr|first=Mike Fleming|last2=Jr|first2=Mike Fleming|date=2014-01-29|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n''Shoebite'' is the story of a man in his early 60s named John Pereira who sets out on a journey of self-discovery.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Amitabh Bachchan]] as John Pereira<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmibeat.com/bollywood/gupshup/2008/amitabh-sarika-shoebite-070208.html|title=Amitabh Bachchan's wife Sarika dies|last=Glamsham|first=By: Abid|date=2008-02-07|website=Filmbeat|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apunkachoice.com/titles/joh/johnny-mastana/mid_25508/photos/mopho_25508_40840_2/2.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308123044/http://www.apunkachoice.com/titles/joh/johnny-mastana/mid_25508/photos/mopho_25508_40840_2/2.html |archivedate=8 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Sarika]] as Aditi<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-17/news-interviews/28553964_1_child-labour-love-story-shoebite/ Shoebite's a very unique love story: Sarika]</ref>\n* [[Dia Mirza]]\n* [[Jimmy Sheirgill]]\n* [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]]<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Ive-grown-up-watching-C-grade-movies-Nawazuddin-Part-1/Article1-882169.aspx/ Ive grown up watching C grade movies: Nawazuddin Part 1] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808053902/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Ive-grown-up-watching-C-grade-movies-Nawazuddin-Part-1/Article1-882169.aspx |date=8 August 2012 }}</ref>\n* Apurva Mathur\n\n==Filming==\nDuring the [[Manali, Himachal Pradesh|Manali]] schedule of the film, the shooting unit converted the [[Snow and Avalanche Study Establishment]](SASE) into a hospital.<ref>[http://www.apunkachoice.com/titles/joh/johnny-mastana/mid_25508/photos/mopho_25508_40840_2/2.html \"Johnny Mastana\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308123044/http://www.apunkachoice.com/titles/joh/johnny-mastana/mid_25508/photos/mopho_25508_40840_2/2.html |date=8 March 2012 }},''Apunkachoice'', URL Retrieved on 8 April 2010</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[Percept Picture Company]] announced a film called ''Johnny Walker'' starring Bachchan and directed by Sircar, but the film was never made. Sircar took the film to [[UTV Software Communications|UTV Motion Pictures]], renaming it ''Shoebite''. Percept filed a lawsuit against UTV seeking to prevent ''Shoebite'' from being made. After a long legal battle, the lawsuit was dismissed in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2008/shoebite-delhi-high-court-order-240708.html |title=Amitabh's Shoebite in trouble |work=OneIndia |date=2008-07-24 |accessdate=2012-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.co.in/utv-wins-case-against-percept-on-shoebite/ |title=UTV Wins Case Against Percept On Shoebite |date=2012-04-17 |work=Boxofficeindia.co.in |accessdate=2012-07-27}}</ref> The production of the film has been speculated to be stalled.<ref>[http://www.bollywood.com/shyamalan-stalls-release-amitanh-bachchan-film Shyamalan stalls release of Amitanh Bachchan film?]</ref> The director of the film [[Shoojit Sircar]] made film ''[[Vicky Donor]]'' and got it released since he started to face delays in Shoebite.<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/never-expected-families-to-turn-up-for-vicky-donor-says-director/943993/0 Never expected families to turn up for 'Vicky Donor', says director]</ref> Sircar released ''[[Madras Cafe]]'' in 2013, and the film has now been cancelled.<ref name=\"tehelka2012\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main52.asp?filename=hub120512VICKY.asp|title=Vicky Donor is born|last=Vol 9, Issue 19|first=|date=2012-05-12|website=|publisher=Tehelka|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> In March 2018, Bachchan requested the makers to release the film in his tweet, saying ''Yes... put aside the internal debate, issues, or personal view points and give this labour of love from Shoojit Sircar a chance for others to appreciate this novel story and film... Please..'' <ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/amitabh-bachchan-put-aside-issues-give-shoebite-a-chance/articleshow/63428907.cms</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/gupshup/2008/amitabh-bachchan-shoebite-290108.html''Article on oneindia.com'']\n\n{{Shoojit Sircar}}\n{{UTV Movies}}\n\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Unreleased Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Cancelled films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Shoojit Sircar]]\n[[Category:UTV Motion Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Shoebite\n| image          = Shoe Bite.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = <!-- {{Infobox name module|language|title}} or {{Infobox name module|title}} -->\n| director       = [[Shoojit Sircar]]\n| producer       = [[Ronnie Screwvala]]\n| writer         = \n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{Based on|title of the original work|creator of the original work|additional creator(s), if necessary}} -->\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Amitabh Bachchan]]|[[Sarika]]|[[Dia Mirza]]|[[Jimmy Sheirgill]]}}\n| narrator       = \n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = [[UTV Motion Pictures]]\n| distributor    = <!-- or: | distributors = -->\n| released       = <!-- {{Film date|df=yes/no|year|month|day|loc